{"title_page": "Sol Rosevear", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name = Sol Rosevear\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Sol Rosevear.jpg\n| constituency_MP = [[Division of Dalley|Dalley]]\n| parliament = Australian\n| majority = \n| predecessor = [[Ted Theodore]]\n| successor = [[Arthur Greenup]]\n| term_start = 19 December 1931\n| term_end = 21 March 1953\n| office2       = 11th [[Speaker of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n| predecessor2  = [[Walter Nairn]]\n| successor2    = [[Archie Cameron]]\n| term_start2   = 22 June 1943\n| term_end2     = 21 February 1950\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1892|1|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Pyrmont, New South Wales]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1953|3|21|1892|1|4}} \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Australia]]n\n| spouse = Clara May White\n| party = [[Australian Labor Party (NSW)|NSW Labor]] (1931\u201336) <br /> [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] (1936\u201340) <br /> [[Australian Labor Party (Non-Communist)|Labor (N-C)]] (1940\u201341) <br /> [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] (1941\u201353)\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Timber worker\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''John Solomon \"Sol\" Rosevear''' (4 January 1892{{spaced ndash}}21 March 1953) was an [[Australia]]n politician, and was [[Speaker of the Australian House of Representatives]] from 1943 to 1949.\n\n==Early life==\nRosevear was born on 4 January 1892 in [[Pyrmont, New South Wales|Pyrmont, Sydney, New South Wales]]. He was the seventh child of Maria (n\u00e9e McGuirk) and William John Rosevear. His father was a [[wikt:carter|carter]]. Rosevear attended the local public school before beginning work in the timber industry, where he became known as a skilled tradesman. He married Clara May White on 23 September 1916, with whom he had two children.<ref name=adb>{{cite news|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/rosevear-john-solomon-11565|title=Rosevear, John Solomon (1892\u20131953)|first=Frank|last=Bongiorno|authorlink=Frank Bongiorno|work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]|year=2002|volume=16}}</ref>\n\nRosevear became involved in the [[Australian labour movement|labour movement]] at a young age as a member of the Timber Workers' Union. He was active in the [[Leichhardt, New South Wales|Leichhardt]] branch of the ALP and served as president of the electorate council for [[Division of Dalley|Dalley]]. He managed [[Ted Theodore]]'s campaign at the [[1929 Australian federal election|1929 federal election]].<ref name=adb/> In the same year, Rosevear played an active role in a big strike within the timber industry. He lost his job and led the Leichhardt Unemployed Workers' Relief Movement during the [[Great Depression in Australia|Great Depression]]. He registered for [[the dole]], and was due to receive his first payment on the day he was elected to federal parliament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/18508924/1058888|title=Mr. Rosevear's Stern Rule In House|newspaper=[[The Sunday Herald (Sydney newspaper)|The Sunday Herald]]|date=22 March 1953}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:John Solomon Rosevear (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sol Rosevear]]\nRosevear was an [[Australian Labor Party]] official and organised [[Ted Theodore]]'s campaign in 1929. After the 1931 Labor split, however, Rosevear joined the [[Lang Labor]] breakaway and defeated Theodore in his seat of [[Division of Dalley|Dalley]] in the [[1931 Australian federal election|election of that year]]. He sat in the [[House of Representatives (Australia)|House of Representatives]] under the leadership of [[Jack Beasley]] until 1936, when the two factions reunited. Following the second split of 1940, Rosevear was deputy-leader of the [[Australian Labor Party (Non-Communist)]].\n\nIn 1941, [[John Curtin]] reunited the Labor Party and Rosevear rejoined the ALP. In July 1942, under special wartime circumstances, he was appointed Controller of Footwear and Leather Supplies within the [[Department of Supply and Development (1939\u201342)|Department of Supply and Development]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/25924038|title=Leather and footwear|newspaper=[[The Hobart Mercury]]|date=1 August 1942}}</ref> By ministerial decree in November 1942, he was given the power to regulate the manufacture of footwear and materials for the manufacture of footwear.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/232679012|title=Control of Production and Distribution of Footwear Order|first=Jack|last=Beasley|authorlink=Jack Beasley|date=25 November 1942|work=Commonwealth of Australia Gazette}}</ref>\n\n===Speaker of the House===\nRosevear was disappointed not to receive a cabinet post, but was appointed [[Speaker of the Australian House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]] on 22 June 1943. He gained a reputation as an inflexible Speaker, accused by the media and the Opposition of partisanship; journalist E.H. Cox claimed that he was \"frequently drunk in the Chair\". Rosevear also permitted illegal gambling in the Chamber, and participated himself.\n\nRosevear continued to be influential in caucus, and it was rumoured that he hoped to succeed [[Ben Chifley]] as party leader, but his \"taste for grog\" was seen as a disqualification by some. In the [[1949 Australian federal election|1949 election]] the Chifley government was defeated by the [[Coalition (Australia)|Liberal/Country Party coalition]] led by [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] [[Robert Menzies]] and Rosevear lost the Speakership. He continued to sit in the House until his death of [[coronary occlusion]] on 21 March 1953. He was survived by his wife, a son and a daughter. A portrait of Rosevear by [[Joshua Smith (artist)|Joshua Smith]] won the [[Archibald Prize]] in 1944.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Sol Rosevear (Australian politician)}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Speaker of the Australian House of Representatives]] | before = [[Walter Nairn]] | after = [[Archie Cameron]] | years = 1943\u20131949}}\n{{succession box | title=Member for [[Division of Dalley|Dalley]] | before= [[Ted Theodore]] | after= [[Arthur Greenup]] | years=1931\u20131953}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Speaker of the Australian House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosevear, Sol}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Lang Labor members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Dalley]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n| name = Sol Rosevear\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Sol Rosevear.jpg\n| constituency_MP = [[Division of Dalley|Dalley]]\n| parliament = Australian\n| majority = \n| predecessor = [[Ted Theodore]]\n| successor = [[Arthur Greenup]]\n| term_start = 19 December 1931\n| term_end = 21 March 1953\n| office2       = 11th [[Speaker of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n| predecessor2  = [[Walter Nairn]]\n| successor2    = [[Archie Cameron]]\n| term_start2   = 22 June 1943\n| term_end2     = 21 February 1950\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1892|1|4}}\n| birth_place = [[Pyrmont, New South Wales]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1953|3|21|1892|1|4}} \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Australia]]n\n| spouse = Clara May White\n| party = [[Australian Labor Party (NSW)|NSW Labor]] (1931\u201336) <br /> [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] (1936\u201340) <br /> [[Australian Labor Party (Non-Communist)|Labor (N-C)]] (1940\u201341) <br /> [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] (1941\u201353)\n| relations =\n| children =\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = Timber worker\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''John Solomon \"Sol\" Rosevear''' (4 January 1892{{spaced ndash}}21 March 1953) was an [[Australia]]n politician, and was [[Speaker of the Australian House of Representatives]] from 1943 to 1949.\n\n==Early life==\nRosevear was born on 4 January 1892 in [[Pyrmont, New South Wales|Pyrmont, Sydney, New South Wales]]. He was the seventh child of Maria (n\u00e9e McGuirk) and William John Rosevear. His father was a [[wikt:carter|carter]]. Rosevear attended the local public school before beginning work in the timber industry, where he became known as a skilled tradesman. He married Clara May White on 23 September 1916, with whom he had two children.<ref name=adb>{{cite news|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/rosevear-john-solomon-11565|title=Rosevear, John Solomon (1892\u20131953)|first=Frank|last=Bongiorno|authorlink=Frank Bongiorno|work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]|year=2002|volume=16}}</ref>\n\nRosevear became involved in the [[Australian labour movement|labour movement]] at a young age as a member of the Timber Workers' Union. He was active in the [[Leichhardt, New South Wales|Leichhardt]] branch of the ALP and served as president of the electorate council for [[Division of Dalley|Dalley]]. He managed [[Ted Theodore]]'s campaign at the [[1929 Australian federal election|1929 federal election]].<ref name=adb/> In the same year, Rosevear played an active role in a big strike within the timber industry. He lost his job and led the Leichhardt Unemployed Workers' Relief Movement during the [[Great Depression in Australia|Great Depression]]. He registered for [[the dole]], and was due to receive his first payment on the day he was elected to federal parliament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/18508924/1058888|title=Mr. Rosevear's Stern Rule In House|newspaper=[[The Sunday Herald (Sydney newspaper)|The Sunday Herald]]|date=22 March 1953}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:John Solomon Rosevear (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Sol Rosevear]]\nRosevear was an [[Australian Labor Party]] official and organised [[Ted Theodore]]'s campaign in 1929. After the 1931 Labor split, however, Rosevear joined the [[Lang Labor]] breakaway and defeated Theodore in his seat of [[Division of Dalley|Dalley]] in the [[1931 Australian federal election|election of that year]]. He sat in the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] under the leadership of [[Jack Beasley]] until 1936, when the two factions reunited. Following the second split of 1940, Rosevear was deputy-leader of the [[Australian Labor Party (Non-Communist)]].\n\nIn 1941, [[John Curtin]] reunited the Labor Party and Rosevear rejoined the ALP. In July 1942, under special wartime circumstances, he was appointed Controller of Footwear and Leather Supplies within the [[Department of Supply and Development (1939\u201342)|Department of Supply and Development]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/25924038|title=Leather and footwear|newspaper=[[The Hobart Mercury]]|date=1 August 1942}}</ref> By ministerial decree in November 1942, he was given the power to regulate the manufacture of footwear and materials for the manufacture of footwear.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/232679012|title=Control of Production and Distribution of Footwear Order|first=Jack|last=Beasley|authorlink=Jack Beasley|date=25 November 1942|work=Commonwealth of Australia Gazette}}</ref>\n\n===Speaker of the House===\nRosevear was disappointed not to receive a cabinet post, but was appointed [[Speaker of the Australian House of Representatives|Speaker of the House of Representatives]] on 22 June 1943. He gained a reputation as an inflexible Speaker, accused by the media and the Opposition of partisanship; journalist E.H. Cox claimed that he was \"frequently drunk in the Chair\". Rosevear also permitted illegal gambling in the Chamber, and participated himself.\n\nRosevear continued to be influential in caucus, and it was rumoured that he hoped to succeed [[Ben Chifley]] as party leader, but his \"taste for grog\" was seen as a disqualification by some. In the [[1949 Australian federal election|1949 election]] the Chifley government was defeated by the [[Coalition (Australia)|Liberal/Country Party coalition]] led by [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] [[Robert Menzies]] and Rosevear lost the Speakership. He continued to sit in the House until his death of [[coronary occlusion]] on 21 March 1953. He was survived by his wife, a son and a daughter. A portrait of Rosevear by [[Joshua Smith (artist)|Joshua Smith]] won the [[Archibald Prize]] in 1944.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Sol Rosevear (Australian politician)}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Speaker of the Australian House of Representatives]] | before = [[Walter Nairn]] | after = [[Archie Cameron]] | years = 1943\u20131949}}\n{{succession box | title=Member for [[Division of Dalley|Dalley]] | before= [[Ted Theodore]] | after= [[Arthur Greenup]] | years=1931\u20131953}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Speaker of the Australian House of Representatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosevear, Sol}}\n[[Category:1892 births]]\n[[Category:1953 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Lang Labor members of the Parliament of Australia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the Australian House of Representatives for Dalley]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Australian House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian politicians]]\