{"title_page": "London Assembly", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox legislature\n| background_color  = #353C42\n| name              = \n| native_name       =\n| legislature       =\n| coa_pic           = London Assembly logo.svg\n| coa_res           = 250px\n| coa-pic           =\n| coa-res           =\n| foundation        = 3 July 2000\n| house_type        = [[Unicameral]] [[deliberative assembly]] of [[London]]\n| leader1_type      = [[Speaker (politics)|Chair]]\n| leader1           = [[Jennette Arnold]], [[London Labour Party|Labour]]\n| election1         = 2 May 2019\n| leader2_type      = Deputy Chair\n| leader2           = [[Tony Arbour]], [[London Conservatives|Conservative]]\n| election2         = 2 May 2019\n| leader3_type      = Group leaders\n| leader3   = {{plainlist|\n*[[Len Duvall]], Labour\n*[[Gareth Bacon]], Conservative\n*[[Caroline Russell]], [[London Green Party|Green]]\n*[[Peter Whittle (politician)|Peter Whittle]], [[Brexit Alliance]]\n*[[Caroline Pidgeon]], [[London Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrat]]\n}}\n| members           = 25\n| structure1        = London Assembly Current Composition.svg\n| structure1_res    = 250px\n| political_groups1 = {{unbulleted list\n | {{nowrap|{{Color box|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[London Labour Party|Labour]] (12)}}\n | {{nowrap|{{Color box|{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[London Conservatives|Conservative]] (8)}}\n | {{nowrap|{{Color box|{{Green Party of England and Wales/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[London Green Party|Green]] (2)}}\n | {{nowrap|{{Color box|{{UKIP/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Brexit Alliance]] (2)}}\n | {{nowrap|{{Color box|{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[London Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrats]] ([[Caroline Pidgeon|1]])}}\n }}\n| committees1       = {{Collapsible list|title=List|Audit|Budget and Performance|Budget Monitoring|Confirmation Hearings|Economy|Education|Environment|GLA Oversight|Health|Housing|Planning|Police and Crime|Regeneration|Transport}}\n| house1            =\n| voting_system1    = [[Additional Member System]]\n| voting_system2    =\n| last_election1    = [[2016 London Assembly election|5 May 2016]]\n| next_election1    = [[2021 London Assembly election|6 May 2021]]\n| session_room      = GLA Chamber.jpg\n| session_res       = 150px\n| meeting_place     = [[City Hall (London)|City Hall]], [[Southwark]]\n| website           = [http://www.london.gov.uk/about-us/london-assembly www.london.gov.uk]\n| footnotes         =\n}}\n{{Politics of London}}\nThe '''London Assembly''' is a 25-member elected body, part of the [[Greater London Authority]], that scrutinises the activities of the [[Mayor of London]] and has the power, with a two-thirds super-majority, to amend the Mayor's annual budget and to reject the Mayor's draft statutory strategies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2011/20/section/229 |title=Localism Act 2011 |publisher=Legislation.gov.uk |date=2012-02-07 |accessdate=2015-04-03}}</ref> The London Assembly was established in 2000 and meets at [[City Hall (London)|City Hall]] on the south bank of the [[River Thames]], close to [[Tower Bridge]]. The Assembly is also able to investigate other issues of importance to Londoners ([[Transport for London|transport]], environmental matters, etc.), publish its findings and recommendations, and make proposals to the Mayor.\n\n==Assembly Members==\nThe Assembly comprises 25 Assembly Members elected using the [[Additional Member System]] of [[proportional representation]], with 13 seats needed for a majority. Elections take place every four years \u2013 at the same time as for the [[Mayor of London|Mayor]]. There are 14 geographical super-constituencies each electing one Member, with a further 11 members elected from a party list to make the total Assembly Members from each party proportional to the votes cast for that party across the whole of London using a modified [[D'Hondt method|D'Hondt]] allocation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-17769428 |title=BBC News \u2013 How the London election works |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=25 April 2012 |accessdate=18 November 2012}}</ref> A party must win at least 5% of the party list vote in order to win any seats. Members of the London Assembly have the [[post-nominal title]] 'AM', as do Members of the [[Welsh Assembly]]. The annual salary for a London Assembly Member is approximately \u00a355,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/london_assembly_members.jsp |title=London Assembly Members |work=The London Assembly |publisher=Mayor of London, the London Assembly and the Greater London Authority |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515185946/http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/london_assembly_members.jsp |archivedate=15 May 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Former Assembly Members===\nSince its creation in 2000, thirteen Assembly Members have subsequently been elected to the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]]: [[David Lammy]], [[Meg Hillier]] and [[Diana Johnson]] for Labour; [[Andrew Pelling]], [[Bob Neill]], [[Angie Bray]], [[Bob Blackman (politician)|Bob Blackman]], [[Eric Ollerenshaw]], [[Victoria Borwick]], [[James Cleverly]], [[Kit Malthouse]] and [[Kemi Badenoch]] for the Conservatives; and [[Lynne Featherstone]] for the Liberal Democrats. One Assembly Member, [[Jenny Jones, Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb|Jenny Jones]], was appointed to the House of Lords as the first life peer for the Green Party, and simultaneously sat in the Assembly until May 2016. [[Sally Hamwee, Baroness Hamwee|Sally Hamwee]], [[Graham Tope, Baron Tope|Graham Tope]] and [[Toby Harris, Baron Harris of Haringey|Toby Harris]] were life peers elected to the assembly, while [[Lynne Featherstone]] and [[Dee Doocey]] were appointed peers after leaving the Assembly. In addition, [[Val Shawcross]], Assembly Member for [[Lambeth and Southwark (London Assembly constituency)|Lambeth and Southwark]] was selected, but unsuccessful, as the Labour parliamentary candidate for the constituency of [[Bermondsey and Old Southwark (UK Parliament constituency)|Bermondsey and Old Southwark]] at the 2010 general election, as was [[Navin Shah]] who stood for Labour in [[Harrow East]] in 2017. [[Andrew Dismore]], [[Graham Tope]], and [[Richard Tracey]] are all former MPs who were later elected to the Assembly. One Assembly Member \u2013 [[John Biggs (politician)|John Biggs]], former AM for [[City and East (London Assembly constituency)|City and East]] \u2013 became the directly-elected [[Mayor of Tower Hamlets]] in 2015. He is currently serving as the Mayor, having been re-elected in 2018.\n\n===Structure of the Assembly===\nLondon Assembly elections have been held under the [[Additional Member System]], with a set number of constituencies elected on a first-past-the-post system and a set number London-wide on a closed party list system.\n\nIn December 2016, an Electoral Reform Bill was introduced which would have changed the election system to [[first-past-the-post]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/electoral-reform-proportional-representation-pr-system-london-assembly-electoral-reform-bill-a7492531.html|title=Tory and Labour MPs gang up in bid to strip London Assembly of PR voting system|date=23 December 2016|publisher=}}</ref> At the [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 UK general election]], the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] manifesto proposed changes to how the assembly is elected, to first-past-the-post.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mayorwatch.co.uk/tories-confirm-london-assembly-also-faces-election-rules-shake-up/|title=Tories confirm London Assembly also faces election rules shake-up|date=19 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref> However, since the general election of 2017, which resulted in a hung Parliament with the Conservatives and the DUP in a supply and confidence arrangement, no action has been taken with regard to the electoral arrangements of the London Assembly and it is generally assumed that the 2021 elections will be held on the current electoral system of MMP (constituencies and regional list)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 rowspan=2 | Political party\n! colspan=6 | Assembly members\n|-\n! 2000\n! 2004\n! 2008\n! 2012\n! colspan=2 | 2016\n|-\n{{party colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 9\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 7\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 8\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 12\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''12'''\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|12|25|hex={{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n{{party colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 9\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 9\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 11\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 9\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''8'''\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|8|25|hex={{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n{{party colour|Green Party of England and Wales}}\n| [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 3\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 2\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 2\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 2\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|2|25|hex={{Green Party of England and Wales/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n{{party colour|UK Independence Party}}\n| [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | \n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 2\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | \n| style=\"text-align: right\" | \n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''2'''\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|2|25|hex={{UK Independence Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n{{party colour|Liberal Democrats (UK)}}\n| [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 4\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 5\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 3\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 2\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | '''1'''\n| {{Infobox political party/seats|1|25|hex={{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n{{party colour|British National Party}}\n| [[British National Party]]\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | \n| style=\"text-align: right\" | \n| style=\"text-align: right\" | 1\n| style=\"text-align: right\" | \n| style=\"text-align: right\" | \n| {{Infobox political party/seats|0|25|hex={{Independent/meta/color}}}}\n|}\n\nOn 12 December 2018, following Peter Whittle's departure from UKIP, he and David Kurten disbanded the UKIP grouping and formed the Brexit Alliance group, though David Kurten still remains a member of UKIP.\n\n===List of Assembly Members===\n{{further|London Assembly constituencies}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Constituency\n! Member\n! colspan=\"2\" | Political party\n|-\n| [[Barnet and Camden (London Assembly constituency)|Barnet and Camden]]\n| [[Andrew Dismore]]\n{{party colour|Labour Co-operative}}\n| [[Labour Co-operative]]\n|-\n| [[Bexley and Bromley (London Assembly constituency)|Bexley and Bromley]]\n| [[Gareth Bacon]]\n{{party colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| [[Brent and Harrow (London Assembly constituency)|Brent and Harrow]]\n| [[Navin Shah]]\n{{party colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|-\n| [[City and East (London Assembly constituency)|City and East]]\n| [[Unmesh Desai]]\n{{party colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|-\n| [[Croydon and Sutton (London Assembly constituency)|Croydon and Sutton]]\n| [[Stephen O'Connell]]\n{{party colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| [[Ealing and Hillingdon (London Assembly constituency)|Ealing and Hillingdon]]\n| [[Onkar Sahota]]\n{{party colour|Labour Party (UK)}}\n| [[Labour Party (UK