{"title_page": "Anti-Defamation League", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name         = Anti-Defamation League\n|image        = ADL logo (2018).svg\n|size         = 200px\n|motto        = We Hate Christ\n|formation    = {{Start date and age|1913|09}} (as Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith)\n|founder      = [[Sigmund Livingston]]\n|headquarters = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|type         = [[Civil rights]] law\n|leader_title = Director\n|leader_name  = [[Jonathan Greenblatt]]\n|key_people   = Sigmund Livingston (Founder)<br />Robert G. Sugarman (Chairman)\n|website      = [http://www.adl.org/ www.adl.org/]\n}}\n{{Antisemitism}}\nThe '''Anti-Defamation League''' ('''ADL'''; formerly known as the '''Anti-Defamation League of [[B'nai B'rith]]''') is an international [[Jews|Jewish]] [[non-governmental organization]] based in the [[United States]]. It was founded in late September 1913 by the Independent Order of [[B'nai B'rith]], a [[Jews|Jewish]] [[service organization]]. ADL subsequently split from B'nai B'rith and continued as an independent U.S. Section 501(c)(3) nonprofit. In its 2017 annual information Form 990, ADL reported total revenues of just over $70 million, from contributions and grants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdf.guidestar.org/PDF_Images/2017/131/818/2017-131818723-1035a764-9.pdf|title=ANTI-DEFAMATION LEAGUE FORM 990|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> \n\nADL states that its mission is a dual one: \"To stop the defamation of the Jewish people, and to secure justice and fair treatment to all\" via the development of \"new programs, policies and skills to expose and combat whatever holds us back.\"<ref name=\"ADLCharter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-mission|title=Our Mission|website=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Opposing [[Antisemitism]] and extremism, ADL describes its \"ultimate goal\" as \"a world in which no group or individual suffers from bias, discrimination or hate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are|title=Who We Are|website=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe headquarters of ADL are located in [[New York City]]. [[Abraham Foxman]] was the national director from 1987 for more than a quarter century. In November 2014, it was announced that [[Jonathan Greenblatt]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/leadership/staff/jonathan-greenblatt|title=Jonathan Greenblatt, CEO and National Director|last=Anti-Defamation League|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> a serial social entrepreneur, former Silicon Valley tech executive and former Obama Administration official who had not operated within the Jewish communal organization world prior to his hiring, would succeed Foxman as national director in July 2015.<ref>[http://www.jta.org/2014/11/06/news-opinion/united-states/white-house-aide-to-succeed-abe-foxman-as-adl-chief-1 \"White House aide Jonathan Greenblatt to succeed Abe Foxman as ADL chief\"], ''[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]'', November 6, 2014.</ref> The national chair of the governing board of directors is Esta Gordon Epstein.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newengland.adl.org/news/longtime-adl-boston-leader-esta-epstein-named-chair-of-organizations-national-board/|title=LONGTIME ADL BOSTON LEADER ESTA GORDON EPSTEIN NAMED CHAIR OF ORGANIZATION'S NATIONAL BOARD|last=|first=|date=November 8, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>[http://www.adl.org/about-adl/adl-leadership.html Barry Curtiss-Lusher, National Chair] ADL.org, ''accessed November 9, 2014.''</ref> ADL has 25 regional offices in the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-in-the-us|title=Anti-Semitism in the US|work=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019|quote=Through our network of 25 regional offices}}</ref> including a Government Relations Office in Washington DC, and is also active overseas, with an office in Israel and staff in Europe.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-globally|title=Anti-Semitism Globally|work=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nADL has been criticized both from the right<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/12/anti-defamation-league-trump-232049|title=ADL combats criticism of being too tough on Trump|last=|first=|date=January 1, 2016|website=Politico.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and left of the U.S. political spectrum, including within the American Jewish community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/opinion/.premium-from-left-and-right-why-is-a-league-of-haters-descending-on-the-adl-1.6053744|title=Opinion From Left and Right, Why Is a League of Haters Descending on the ADL?|newspaper=Haaretz|date=May 3, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020|last1=Cohen|first1=Debra Nussbaum}}</ref> This is in large part -- but by no means only -- because the American far left (which includes some American Jewish groups, such as [[Jewish Voice for Peace]]) has increasingly condemned and sought sanctions against Israel for its treatment of Israeli Arabs and Palestinians living in the territories and has extrapolated from that position that ADL cannot credibly claim to be a civil rights organization as long as it also supports Israel as a Jewish homeland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.losangelesblade.com/2019/01/31/creating-change-2019-creates-controversy-again/|title=Creating Change 2019 creates controversy, again|last=|first=|date=January 31, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28. 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://droptheadl.wordpress.com/why-droptheadl/|title=#DropTheADL: Communities say NO to the Anti-Defamation League in our schools, coalitions, and movements|last=|first=|date=May 30, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the left, key ADL former or present positions that generate criticism, even condemnation, are the organization's support for the existence of [[Israel]] as a Jewish homeland, domestic spying allegations, its former stance on the [[Armenian Genocide]],<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|first1=Rupen|last1=Janbazian|accessdate=2019-09-25|title=ADL's Official Recognition of Armenian Genocide Ends Years-Long Controversy|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2016/05/16/adl-armenian-genocide-2016/|date=16 May 2016|website=The Armenian Weekly}}</ref> since repudiated and apologized for,<ref name=\":0\" /> and what frequently is alleged by the left to be ADL's conflation of opposition to Israel with [[antisemitism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/how-a-jewish-civil-rights-group-became-a-villain-on-the-far-left/|title=How a Jewish civil rights group became a villain on the far-left|last=Sales|first=Ben|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Shira|last1=Hanau|accessdate=2019-09-25|title=Can ADL Be A Moral Voice For Millennials?|url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/can-adl-be-a-moral-voice-for-millennials/|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, rightwing groups and pundits, including very conservative Jewish groups, have attacked ADL, labeling it an arm of the Democratic party (presumably in part because its CEO, [[Jonathan Greenblatt]], was in the Obama administration)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/amari-sohrab/the-adl-smears-mike-pompeo/|title=The ADL Smears Mike Pompeo|last=Ahmari|first=Sohrab|date=April 19, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jns.org/opinion/whatever-happened-to-the-adl/|title=Whatever happened to the ADL?: The attack on Kavanaugh's nomination to the Supreme Court is the latest instance of how Jonathan Greenblatt has turned the venerable anti-Semitism watchdog into a partisan outfit.|last=Tobin|first=Jonathan|date=July 13, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and decrying its civil rights agenda, which is vehemently in support of immigrants and refugees, trans rights and other [[LGBT|LGBTQ]] rights, against establishment of religion, and against [[Islamophobia|Islamaphobia]]. The ADL has also called for the firing of Trump administration official [[Stephen Miller (political advisor)|Stephen Miller]], the architect of the Administration's immigration policy.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/jewish-groups-stephen-miller-resign-white-nationalist_n_5dd69935e4b0e29d72800575?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly91cy5zZWFyY2gueWFob28uY29tLw&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAG5GoJ0dtOkPudr5tkzXMWY-wRmtd1nHDOfZ1c7WOW3gYQKtSQgDjZaIXDUnko0UMrEJVEYUXG3jMWrrsrV52jBKycFPCh7lje-saS6lbR17o5_4ikE4B7PIIACorUKfLxJXapH0BueU1WTMTER8dUqZKRH2Ep2TZ2Y83nmA0kDE|title=Jewish Groups Demand Stephen Miller Resign From White House|last=Mathias|first=Christopher|date=November 21, 2019|website=HuffPost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Origin ==\nFounded in late September 1913 by [[B'nai B'rith]], with [[Sigmund Livingston]] as its first leader, the ADL's charter states, {{quote|The immediate object of the League is to stop, by appeals to reason and conscience and, if necessary, by appeals to law, the defamation of the Jewish people. Its ultimate purpose is to secure justice and fair treatment to all citizens alike and to put an end forever to unjust and unfair discrimination against and ridicule of any sect or body of citizens.<ref name=ADLCharter />}}\nThe Anti-Defamation League was founded by B'nai B'rith as a response to attacks on Jews; the recent conviction of [[Leo Frank]] was mentioned by [[Adolf Kraus]] when he announced the creation of ADL.<ref>{{cite book|last=Moore|first=Deborah Dash|title=B'nai B'rith and the Challenge of Ethnic Leadership|year=1981|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-87395-480-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/bnaibrithch00moor/page/108 108]|url=https://archive.org/details/bnaibrithch00moor/page/108}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jews in American Politics: Essays|year=2001|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-7425-0181-2|page=105|author=Jerome A. Chanes|editor1=Louis S |editor2=y Maisel |editor3=Ira N. Forman |editor4=Donald Altschiller |editor5=Charles Walker Bassett |chapter=Who Does What?}}</ref>\n\n== Goals ==\n[[File:Jonathan Greenblatt by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Jonathan Greenblatt, National Director and CEO of the Anti-Defamation League since 2015]]\nThe stated purpose of the ADL is to fight: {{quote|anti-Semitism and all forms of bigotry (in the United States) and abroad, combat international terrorism, probe the roots of hatred, advocate before the United States Congress, come to the aid of victims of bigotry, develop educational programs, and serve as a public resource for government, media, law enforcement, and the public, all towards the goal of countering and reducing hatred.}} Historically, ADL has opposed groups and individuals it considered to be anti-Semitic and/or racist, including: [[Nazism|Nazis]], the [[Ku Klux Klan]], [[Henry Ford]], Father [[Charles Coughlin]] (leader of the [[Christian Front (United States)|Christian Front]]), the [[Christian Identity]] movement, the [[German-American Bund]], [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazis]], the [[Militia (United States)|American militia]] movement and [[white power skinhead]]s (although ADL acknowledges that there are also non-racist [[skinhead]]s).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/racist_skinheads/ |title=Racist Skinhead Project |publisher=ADL}}</ref><ref>Salberg, Melvin. [https://www.nytimes.com/1994/04/29/opinion/l-adl-acknowledges-nonracist-skinheads-932108.html Letter to the editor (\"A.D.L. Acknowledges Nonracist Skinheads\")]. ''The New York Times''. April 29, 1994.</ref> ADL publishes reports on a variety of countries, regarding alleged incidents of anti-Jewish attacks and propaganda.  Along with the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC), ADL's Center on Extremism (COE) is generally viewed as the most authoritative non-governmental experts on domestic extremists in the United States.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nADL maintains that some forms of [[anti-Zionism]] and [[criticism of Israel]] cross the line into anti-Semitism. The Anti-Defamation League states:\n{{quote|Criticism of particular Israeli actions or policies in and of itself does not constitute anti-Semitism. Certainly the sovereign State of Israel can be legitimately criticized just like any other country in the world. However, it is undeniable that there are those whose criticism of Israel or of \"Zionism\" is used to mask anti-Semitism.<ref>{{cite web|title=Response To Common Inaccuracy: Israel Critics are Anti-Semites|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-israel-critics-are-anti-semites|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 2010, ADL published a list of the \"ten leading organizations responsible for maligning Israel in the US\", which has included [[ANSWER]], the [[International Solidarity Movement]], and [[Jewish Voice for Peace]] for its call for [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS]].<ref>Benhorin, Yitzhak. \"[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3969798,00.html Jewish group makes ADL blacklist].\" ynet news. October 15, 2010.</ref>  It has not published such a list since.   \n\n=== Fighting antisemitism ===\nIn the second decade of the 21st century ADL and Jews, as well as non-Jews, throughout the United States were generally shocked at the global resurgence of antisemitism,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pope-antisemitism-idUSKBN1ZJ1LT|title=Pope condemns 'barbaric resurgence' of anti-Semitism|last=|first=|newspaper=Reuters|date=January 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> which was manifested in the rise of extremist activity both online and off.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/17/695593556/-antisemitism-here-and-now-author-discusses-resurgence-of-public-anti-semitism|title='Antisemitism: Here And Now' Author Discusses Resurgence Of Public Anti-Semitism|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/anti-semitic-assaults-u-s-more-doubled-2018-adl-reports-n1000246|title=Anti-Semitic assaults in the U.S. more than doubled in 2018, ADL reports|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>A foundational theme of white supremacists was antisemitism, which accompanied or underlay the anti-Muslim, xenophobic, racist, homophobic and other bigotry of these individuals and groups.<ref name=\":3\" /> Social media in particular, amplified hatred and provided what ADL officials characterized as a virtual \"24/7 neo-Nazi rally.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishwebsite.com/featured/adl-urges-congress-to-help-social-media-giants-address-anti-semitism/50933/|title=ADL urges Congress to help social media giants address anti-Semitism|last=|first=|date=January 16, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The number of hate crimes and extremist murders shook the ADL, leading it to reformulate its strategy to focus more resources on fighting antisemitism and extremism: the 2017 white supremacist rally in Charlottesville, Virginia, in which extremists chanted \"Jews will not replace us\" and which led to the murder of [[Charlottesville car attack|Heather Heyer]]; [[Dylann Roof|Dylan Roof]]'s 2015 massacre of African Americans at a prayer group in Charleston, South Carolina; the murder of 11 Jews at Sabbath services in the 2018 [[Pittsburgh synagogue shooting]]; the 2019 [[Poway synagogue shooting]] in California; the 2019 [[Christchurch mosque shooting]]<nowiki/>s in New Zealand; the 2019 Monsey, NY [[Monsey Hanukkah stabbing|Hanukkah stabbing;]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/30/opinion/monsey-new-york-attack.html|title=The Right Response to the Anti-Semitic Attack in Monsey, N.Y.|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 30, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020|last1=Lowey|first1=Nita|last2=Harris|first2=David}}</ref> the series of antisemitic hate crimes in Brooklyn, NY in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/12/27/jewish-mom-son-assaulted-in-latest-anti-semitic-attack-in-brooklyn/|title=Four Jewish women targeted in latest anti-Semitic attacks in Brooklyn|last=|first=|date=December 27, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL has financially supported litigation against the organizers of the Charlottesville rally<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-announces-support-for-ifas-lawsuit-against-neo-nazis-white-supremacists-and|title=ADL Announces Support for IFA's Lawsuit Against Neo-Nazis, White Supremacists, and Hate Groups Responsible for Charlottesville Violence|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and has lobbied for an array of federal and state laws and policies designed to track, expose, and combat extremism, and has also developed and marketed education programs on the subject.<ref name=\":4\" />  ADL also works in close collaboration with Law Enforcement in response to hate crimes.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-in-the-us|title=Anti-Semitism in the US|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2020, after a year's work, ADL published ''Antisemitism Uncovered: A Guide to Old Myths in a New Era.''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://antisemitism.adl.org/?_ga=2.171810404.555282254.1584044588-1012598960.1553545971|title=Antisemitism Uncovered: A Guide to Old Myths in a New Era|last=Anti-Defamation League|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The Guide is intended to be \"a comprehensive resource with historical context, fact-based descriptions of prevalent antisemitic myths, contemporary examples and calls-to-action for addressing this hate.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> It is organized around seven \"myths\" or antisemitic tropes, and is composed of modules.<ref name=\":1\" /> This Guide also represented ADL's shift from using the spelling \"anti-Semitism\" to \"antisemitism.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://antisemitism.adl.org/?_ga=2.171810404.555282254.1584044588-1012598960.1553545971|title=Antisemitism Uncovered: Notes from the CEO, Footnote 8|last=|first=|date=|website=ADL|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/culture/166092/should-anti-semitism-be-hyphenated/|title=Should anti-semitism be hyphenated|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Coronavirus pandemic of 2020 also saw the launch of Jew hatred and at least two types of conspiracy theory that were resuscitated and revised to encompass the virus crisis,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/listen-tablets-yair-rosenberg-talks-anti-semitism-during-coronavirus-crisis/|title=Listen: Tablet's Yair Rosenberg talks anti-Semitism during coronavirus crisis|last=Rosenberg|first=Yair|date=March 27, 2020|website=The Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> an analysis with which ADL agreed and also exposed. \"'There are people out there in the conspiracy theorist swamp who are talking about this being some kind of Mossad thing, or Israel-operative thing,' Rosenberg said. And there's the other type of theorist 'who just celebrates when Jews die from it, under the cover that anti-Zionism makes it okay to celebrate when random people die.' Many of these people, he said, tweeted horrific things after Israel's first victim, Holocaust survivor Aryeh Stern, passed away.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=@JGreenblattADL|title=Tweet re@yair_rosenberg on #antisemitism and #coronavirusMarch|last=|first=|date=March 27, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Tracking extremists ===\nDuring the 1930s, ADL, along with the American Jewish Committee, coordinated American Jewish groups across the country in monitoring the activities of the German-American Bund and its pro-Nazis, nativist allies in the United States. In many instances, these community-based defense organizations paid informants to infiltrate these groups and report on what they discovered. The longest-lived and most effective of these American Jewish resistance organizations was the Los Angeles Jewish Community Committee (LAJCC), which was backed financially by the Jewish leaders of the motion picture industry. The day-to-day operations of the LAJCC were supervised by a Jewish attorney, [[Leon L. Lewis]]. Lewis was uniquely qualified to combat the rise of Nazism in Los Angeles, having served as the first national secretary of the Anti-Defamation League in Chicago from 1925-1931. From 1934-1941, the LAJCC maintained its undercover surveillance of the German-American Bund, the Silver Shirts and dozens of other pro-Nazi, nativist groups that operated in Los Angeles. Partnering with the American Legion in Los Angeles, the LAJCC channeled eyewitness accounts of sedition onto federal authorities. Working with the ADL, Leon Lewis and the LAJCC played a strategic role in counseling the McCormack-Dickstein Committee investigation of Nazi propaganda activities in the United States (1934) and the Dies Committee investigation of \"un-American activities\" (1938-1940). In their final reports to Congress, both Committees found that the sudden rise in political antisemitism in the United States during the decade was due, in part, to the German government's support of these domestic groups.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rosenzweig|first=Laura|url=https://nyupress.org/books/9781479855179/|title=Hollywood's Spies: The Undercover Surveillance of Nazis in Los Angeles|date=2017|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=9781479855179|location=New York|page=|author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Steven|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/us/hitler-in-los-angeles-9781620405642/|title=Hitler in Los Angeles: How Jews Foiled Nazi Plots Against Hollywood and America|date=2017|publisher=Bloomsbury|isbn=9781620405642|location=New York|page=|author-link=}}</ref>\n\nSince the 1970s, ADL has partnered with the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) field offices, sharing information learned from monitoring of extremist groups.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=5SOAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA167 \"Confronting Right Wing Extremism and Terrorism in the USA\"], George Michael. Routledge, Sep 2, 2003. p. 167. Retrieved 27 feb 2017</ref>\n\nADL keeps track of the activities of extremist groups and movements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/sites/default/files/documents/assets/pdf/combating-hate/ADL_CR_Bigots_on_Bikes_online.pdf|title=Bigots on Bikes: The Growing Links between White Supremacists and Biker Gangs|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> According to ADL Director Abe Foxman: \"Our mission is to monitor and expose those who are anti-Jewish, racist, anti-democratic, and violence-prone, and we monitor them primarily by reading publications and attending public meetings \u2026. Because extremist organizations are highly secretive, sometimes ADL can learn of their activities only by using undercover sources \u2026 [who] function in a manner directly analogous to investigative journalists. Some have performed great service to the American people\u2014for example, by uncovering the existence of right-wing extremist paramilitary training camps\u2014with no recognition and at considerable personal risk.\"<ref>\"A League of His Own\", letter to the editor, ''The Village Voice'' 38:20 (May 18, 1993)</ref> A person apprehended in connection to the [[2002 white supremacist terror plot]] had drawn a cartoon of himself blowing up the Boston offices of ADL.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/16/national/16PLOT.html|title=Boston Couple Plotted Blasts to Incite Race War, Prosecutor Says|date=July 16, 2002|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nADL regularly releases reports on [[Anti-Semitism in the USA|US anti-Semitism]] and extremist activities on both the [[Far-left politics|far left]] and the [[Far-right politics|far right]]. As part of its Law Enforcement Agency Resource Network (L.E.A.R.N.), ADL has published information about the [[Militia Movement]]<ref name=\"militia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/militia-movement|title=The Militia Movement|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en}}</ref> in America and a guide for law enforcement officials titled ''Officer Safety and Extremists''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/sites/default/files/documents/assets/pdf/combating-hate/Officer-Safety-and-Extremists-An-Overview.pdf|title=Officer Safety and Extremists|publisher=ADL|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> An archive of \"[[Mark Pitcavage#Militia Watchdog|The Militia Watchdog]]\" research on U.S. right-wing extremism (including groups not specifically cited as anti-Semitic) from 1995 to 2000 is also available on ADL website.<ref name=\"militia\" />\n\nIn the 1990s, some details of ADL's monitoring activities became public knowledge; the ADL had gathered information about some non-extremist groups which became a contentious issue. In 2013, J.M. Berger, a former nonresident fellow of the [[Brookings Institution]], wrote that media organizations should be more cautious when citing the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC) and ADL, arguing that they are \"not objective purveyors of data\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berger|first1=J. M.|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2013/03/12/the-hate-list/|title=The Hate List|work=Foreign Policy}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, ADL announced that they would be developing profiles on 36 [[alt-right]] and [[alt-lite]] leaders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/adl-releases-whos-who-guide-of-alt-right-and-alt-lite-extremists/|title=ADL releases 'Who's Who' guide of alt-right and alt-lite extremists|work=The Times of Israel|access-date=2017-07-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/from-alt-right-to-alt-lite-naming-the-hate|title=From Alt Right to Alt Lite: Naming the Hate|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref>  In 2019 and 2020 ADL executives and staff testified multiple times in front of Congressional committees concerning the dangers of domestic extremists,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/defense-national-security/how-to-stop-it-congress-asks-what-the-military-is-doing-about-white-nationalism-in-the-ranks|title='How to stop it': Congress asks what the military is doing about white nationalism in its ranks|last=|first=|date=February 12, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> noting that the large majority of extremist murders in the United States over the past decade had been committed by white supremacists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/i-testified-at-a-congressional-hearing-on-white-nationalism-heres-some-of-what-i-wish-we-had|title=I Testified at a Congressional Hearing on White Nationalism. Here's Some of What I Wish We Had Discussed.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/adl-tells-congress-to-curb-online-hate-speech-if-social-media-giants-wont/|title=ADL tells Congress to curb online hate speech if social media giants won't|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> In early 2020, as the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus pandemic]] raged, ADL's Center on Extremism<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-on-extremism|title=Who We Are: Center on Extremism|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> began tracking and publishing reports of upsurges in extremist hate and violence targeting Asian-Americans, Chinese, Jews and immigrants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/coronavirus-crisis-elevates-antisemitic-racist-tropes|title=Coronavirus Elevates Antisemitic Racist Tropes|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/03/20/yang-anti-defamation-league-ceo-avoid-coronavirus-scapegoating-racism-column/2877976001/|title=Yang & Anti-Defamation League CEO: Avoid coronavirus racism and scapegoating|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Separation of church and state   ===\nOne of ADL's major focuses is [[Freedom of religion#Judaism|religious freedom]] for people of all faiths.<ref name=\"RelFree\">{{cite web|title=Primer on the First Amendment & Religious Freedom|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/the-first-amendment-and-religious-freedom|website=Anti-Defamation League|accessdate=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Religious Freedom|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/discrimination/religious-freedom|website=Anti-Defamation League|accessdate=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> In the context of public schools, ADL has taken the position that because [[creationism]] and [[intelligent design]] are religious beliefs, and the government is prohibited from endorsing the beliefs of any particular religion, they should not be taught in [[science]] classrooms: \"The U.S. Constitution guarantees the rights of Americans to believe the religious theories of creation (as well as other theories), but it does not permit them to be taught in public school science classes.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adl.org/issue_religious_freedom/create/creationism_QA.asp |title=Religion in the Science Class? Why Creationism and Intelligent Design Don't Belong |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 6, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020407123320/http://www.adl.org/issue_religious_freedom/create/creationism_QA.asp |archive-date=April 7, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Similarly, ADL supports the legal precedent that it is [[constitutionality|unconstitutional]] for the government to post the [[Ten Commandments]] in courthouses, schools, and other public places: \"True religious liberty means freedom from having the government impose the religion of the majority on all citizens.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adl.org/10comm/Prohibitions.asp |title=The Ten Commandments Controversy: A First Amendment Perspective \u2013 Prohibitions on Display of the Ten Commandments |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 7, 2006 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20020920090047/http://www.adl.org/10comm/prohibitions.asp |archive-date=September 20, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ADL has also condemned the public school [[Bible]] curriculum published by the [[National Council on Bible Curriculum in Public Schools]], saying that it raises \"serious constitutional problems\" and \"advocates the acceptance of one faith tradition's interpretation of the Bible over another\".<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Says Bible Teaching Guide for Public Schools 'Unacceptable' |publisher=ADL |date=November 7, 2005 |url=http://www.jewsonfirst.org/05a/public024.html |access-date=July 11, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022212940/http://www.jewsonfirst.org/05a/public024.html |archive-date=October 22, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\nIn 2008 ADL opposed [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Proposition 8]] in California; Prop 8 was a successful ballot proposition for a state constitutional amendment opposing same sex marriage that was subsequently overturned by the federal courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2008_California_Proposition_8|title=2008 California Proposition 8|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL submitted amicus briefs supporting same sex marriage in those cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://38.106.4.56/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentID=1228|title=BRIEF OF AMICI CURIAE ANTI-DEFAMATION LEAGUE ET AL. IN SUPPORT OF RESPONDENTS|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307154233/http://38.106.4.56/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentID=1228|archive-date=March 7, 2013|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> While basing its ongoing opposition to that and other anti-LGBTQ+ laws and campaigns primarily on equality and anti-discrimination legal rationales, ADL also consistently cites church/state separation arguments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/its-not-ok-for-businesses-to-discriminate-in-the-name-of-religion|title=It's Not OK for Businesses to Discriminate in the Name of Religion|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Thus, a frequent theme of ADL argument is that freedom of religion was meant to be a shield to protect religious freedom (particularly of minorities and vulnerable constituencies), and not a sword to attack the religious freedom of others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/ADL-slams-controversial-religious-freedom-laws-in-US-396007|title=ADL slams controversial 'religious freedom' laws in US|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nADL has also based its support for women's equality and reproductive choice on, among other legal arguments, the argument that the state should not adopt as law a particular religious belief,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/abortion-bans-undermine-equality-for-all|title=Abortion and Religious Freedom: The Right-Wing Assault on Religious Diversity in Reproductive Freedom|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> although the United States federal courts have not accepted this religious freedom and state/church separation line of argument.\n\n=== Holocaust awareness ===\nADL holds that it is important to remember [[the Holocaust]], in order to prevent such an event from reoccurring. Along with sponsoring events opposing [[Holocaust denial|Holocaust deniers]] and revisionists, ADL has been active in urging action to end modern-day [[ethnic cleansing]] and [[genocide]] in places such as [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]], [[Darfur]], and [[Sudan]].{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} ADL gives out its [[Courage to Care Award]] to honor rescuers of Jews during the Holocaust.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nADL spoke out against an advertising campaign by [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]] (PETA) beginning in 2003 that equated meat-eating with the Holocaust. A press release from ADL stated that, \"PETA's effort to seek 'approval' for their 'Holocaust on Your Plate' campaign is outrageous, offensive and takes chutzpah to new heights. Rather than deepen our revulsion against what the Nazis did to the Jews, the project will undermine the struggle to understand the Holocaust and to find ways to make sure such catastrophes never happen again.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Denounces Peta for its \"Holocaust On Your Plate\" Campaign; Calls Appeal for Jewish Community Support 'The Height Of Chutzpah' |publisher=ADL |date=February 24, 2003 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/HolNa_52/4235_52.htm}}</ref> In May 2005, PETA apologized for its campaign, with PETA President [[Ingrid Newkirk]] stating that causing pain \"was never our intention, and we are deeply sorry\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Rabbinate to phase out 'shackle and hoist' animal slaughter. More humane method to be adopted following claims of cruelty|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=February 19, 2008|last=Wagner|first=Matthew|quote=PETA has denied being motivated by anti-Semitism and even mentions on its Web site the humaneness of traditional Jewish slaughtering methods when done properly. However, PETA has a history of controversial campaigns. On May 5, 2005, PETA issued an apology for its 'Holocaust on Your Plate' exhibit, which traveled to more than 100 cities. The exhibit compared the treatment of farm animals to that of victims of the Nazi concentration camps. PETA President Ingrid Newkirk said she realized that the campaign had caused pain: 'This was never our intention, and we are deeply sorry.'}}</ref>\n\nADL's Education Department focuses on Holocaust and Genocide Education, primarily through its Echoes and Reflections Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://echoesandreflections.org/|title=CONFIDENTLY TEACH ABOUT THE HOLOCAUST: Echoes & Reflections empowers middle and high school educators with dynamic classroom materials and professional development.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Mrach 29, 2020}}</ref> Echoes and Reflections is sponsored by ADL, [[Yad Vashem]], and the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|United States Holocaust Museum]]. In 2019-20, ADL's national lobbying group and the regional offices refocused efforts on federal and state funding of Holocaust and genocide education, in part as a result of the upsurge of antisemitism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/why-we-need-legislation-to-ensure-the-holocaust-is-taught-in-schools|title=Why We Need Legislation to Ensure the Holocaust is Taught in Schools|last=|first=|date=February 21, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal and State Hate Crimes Legislation ===\nADL was also one of the lead organizations campaigning for thirteen years, ultimately successfully, for the [[Matthew Shepard Act|Matthew Shepard and James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act.]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.duke.edu/news/michael-lieberman-81/|title=Michael Lieberman '81|last=|first=|date=|website=Duke Law News Releases|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/attorney-general-loretta-e-lynch-hosts-63rd-annual-attorney-general-awards-honoring|title=Attorney General Loretta E. Lynch Hosts the 63rd Annual Attorney General Awards Honoring Department Employees and Others For Their Service|last=|first=|date=October 21, 2015|website=|page=|type=U.S. Department of Justice News Release|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>  The hold-up in passing that law focused on the inclusion of the term \"sexual orientation\" as one of the bases that a crime could be deemed a hate crime.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/year-blaze-bernsteins-killing-parents-turn-alleged-hate/story?id=59754707|title=1 year after Blaze Bernstein's killing, parents look to turn alleged hate crime into 'movement of hope'|last=|first=|date=December 30, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> ADL also drafted the model hate crimes legislation in the 1980's; it serves a model for the legislation that a majority of states have adopted.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/hate-crime-laws-dont-prevent-violence-against-lgbt-people/|title=Hate Crime Laws Don't Prevent Violence Against LGBT People: So why do many LGBT people, and others, feel so deeply about the need to have them?|journal=The Nation|date=October 2, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last1=Bronski|first1=Michael|last2=Pellegrini|first2=Ann|last3=Amico|first3=Michael}}</ref>\n\n=== Online content moderation ===\nAs part of its goal of opposing anti-Semitism, ADL has founded the \"Center for Technology and Society\" to target online harassment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-for-technology-and-society|title=Center for Technology and Society|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The goal of this center is to combat cyberbullying through research, education, and active intervention via industry and law-enforcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-for-technology-and-society/about|title=About the Center for Technology and Society|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The ADL has participated in [[YouTube]]'s Trusted Flagger program, and has encouraged YouTube to remove videos which they flag as hate speech, citing the need to \"fight against terrorist use of online resources and cyberhate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-applauds-google-and-youtube-in-expanding-initiative-to-fight-online-hate|title=ADL Applauds Google and YouTube in Expanding Initiative to Fight Online Hate|website=ADL.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2019/06/05/adl-praises-youtube-for-decision-to-remove-racist-extremist-content/|title=ADL Praises YouTube for Decision to Remove Racist, Extremist Content|website=Algemeiner}}</ref> CTS is also playing a lead role working with the online game industry to fight white supremacist activity on platforms connected with gaming.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/07/25/anti-defamation-league-65-of-gamers-have-experienced-severe-harassment-in-online-games/|title=Anti-Defamation League: 65% of gamers have suffered severe harassment online|last=|first=|date=July 26, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/two-thirds-of-us-online-gamers-have-experienced-severe-harassment-new-adl-study|title=Two-Thirds of U.S. Online Gamers Have Experienced Severe Harassment, New ADL Study Finds|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\nADL supports [[Israel]] as a [[Jewish and democratic state]],<ref>[https://www.adl.org/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-israel-cant-be-jewish-democratic Response To Common Inaccuracy: Israel Can't be Jewish & Democratic], Anti-Defamation League.</ref> and supports a [[two-state solution]] to the [[Israeli-Palestinian conflict]], negotiated by the parties.<ref>[https://www.adl.org/education/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-bi-national-one-state-solution Response To Common Inaccuracy: Bi-National/One-State Solution], Anti-Defamation League.</ref> The organization vociferously opposed the [[UN General Assembly Resolution 3379|1975 United Nations resolution]] ([[UN General Assembly Resolution 4686|revoked in 1991]]) which equated [[Zionism]] with racism,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/durban/adl_quotes.asp |title=U.N. World Conference Against Racism |publisher=ADL}}</ref> and attempts to revive that formulation at the 2001 U.N. [[World Conference Against Racism]] in [[Durban]], [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/durban/un_anti-zionism.asp |title=U.N. World Conference Against Racism |publisher=ADL}}</ref> ADL also has expressed concern over Israeli legislative proposals that would stifle freedom of expression and undermine Israeli democracy.<ref>[http://www.adl.org/press-center/press-releases/israel-middle-east/adl-concerned-that-proposed-legislation-on-ngo-funding.html ADL 'Concerned That Proposed Legislation on NGO Funding in Israel Would Erode Nation's Democratic Character,'] Anti-Defamation League January 11, 2016:'In 2011, the League urged the Israeli government to work to modify two similar bills regarding donations from foreign governments to Israeli NGOs, and voiced concern over laws that stifle free expression.'</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/reform-joins-adl-ajc-in-opposing-israels-ngo-bill/|title=Reform joins ADL, AJC in opposing Israel's NGO bill|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nWhile ADL was a lead supporter of Congressional legislation prohibiting US individuals and businesses from joining \"unsanctioned boycotts\" such as the 1970's [[Arab League boycott of Israel|Arab League Boycott]] against Israel,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/glossary-terms/arab-economic-boycott|title=Arab Economic Boycott|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> it has taken a different, case-by-case approach to state anti-boycott laws more recently enacted in response to the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS movement]]. Several of these laws, which seek to prohibit State agencies and instrumentalities from investing in companies that boycott Israel and from entering into contracts with entities that boycott Israel, have been successfully challenged in the courts. The legal challenges have primarily been brought by the [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]] and [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations|CAIR]] on First Amendment constitutional grounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/26/us/texas-bds-law/index.html|title=Texas has a law that says contractors can't boycott Israel. But a federal judge just blocked it|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/blog/free-speech/arizona-lawmakers-running-scared-after-anti-boycott-law-ruled-unconstitutional|title=Arizona Lawmakers Running Scared After Anti-Boycott Law Ruled Unconstitutional|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>ADL generally has not publicly supported laws it felt were constitutionally suspect under the First Amendment, both for legal reasons and because the organization believed that such laws, even if what ADL describes as \"well-intentioned,\" were not an effective means of combating the BDS movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-urges-texas-city-to-remove-no-israel-boycott-requirement-from-aid|title=ADL Urges Texas City to Remove 'No Israel Boycott' Requirement from Aid Application|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> However, as a general matter the organization also has not publicly opposed such state laws, preferring to work behind the scenes to try to make such laws less infirm under the Constitution or to propose non-binding resolutions opposing BDS. A possible division of internal views in ADL was disclosed when the liberal Jewish news media organization, [[The Forward]], published ostensibly leaked internal ADL staff memos dating from 2016 that opposed the anti-boycott laws.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/news/416030/revealed-secret-adl-memo-slammed-anti-bds-laws-as-harmful-to-jews/|title=REVEALED: Secret ADL Memo Slammed Anti-BDS Laws As 'Harmful' To Jews|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL did not comment directly on the leaked memos, but the statement it issued in response appeared to acknowledge that there had been, if were not still, sharply divided views within the organization and that it did not try to suppress internal robust discussion.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nADL has publicly stated that it believes that certain founders and leaders of the BDS movement are antisemitic, but has noted that many supporters of BDS, both Jewish and non-Jewish, are not antisemitic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/backgrounders/bds-the-global-campaign-to-delegitimize-israel|title=BDS: The Global Campaign to Delegitimize Israel|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> \n\nADL has condemned the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]]'s (UNHRC)  list of companies doing business with Jewish settlements in Israeli-run territories (West Bank, East Jerusalem, Golan Heights), issued in February 2020, calling it a \"blacklist.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.com/news/world/310631/unhrc-releases-blacklist-of-companies-conducting-business-in-israeli-settlements/|title=UNHRC Releases 'Blacklist' of Companies Conducting Business in Israeli Settlements|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-strongly-condemns-un-councils-blacklist-of-israeli-companies|title=ADL Strongly Condemns U.N. Council's Blacklist of Israeli Companies|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, ADL condemned Senate Republicans in the United States for attempting to ban [[same-sex marriage]] with the [[Federal Marriage Amendment]], and called the proposal discriminatory.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Welcomes Demise Of Same-Sex Marriage Amendment; Expresses 'Dismay' At Senate Vote |publisher=ADL |date=June 7, 2006 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/DiRaB_41/4832_41.htm}}</ref> That same year, the ADL warned that the debate over [[illegal immigration]] was drawing [[neo-nazis]] and [[anti-Semites]] into the ranks of the [[The Minuteman Project Inc.|Minutemen Project]].\n\nIn 2010, during a hearing for Florida House Bill 11 (Crimes Against Homeless Persons), which was to revise the list of offenses judged to be [[Hate crime laws in the United States|hate crimes]] in Florida by adding a person's homeless status,<ref>{{cite web\n| title = flhouse.gov HB 11 \u2013 Crimes Against Homeless Persons\n| url = http://flhouse.gov/Sections/Bills/billsdetail.aspx?BillId=42143&\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}}</ref> the League lobbied against the bill, which subsequently passed in the House by a vote of 80 to 28 and was sent to the Senate,<ref>{{cite web\n| title = flhouse.gov HB 11 Apr 20 2010 \u2013 Voting record Florida House of Representatives\n| url = http://flhouse.gov/Sections/Bills/floorvote.aspx?VoteId=10836&BillId=42143&\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}}</ref> taking the position that adding more categories to the list would dilute the effectiveness of the law, which already includes race, religion, sexual orientation, disability, and age.<ref>{{cite web\n| title = Homeless could be added to Florida's hate crimes law\n| url = http://www.miamiherald.com/2010/04/21/1589541/homeless-could-be-added-to-floridas.html\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}} ''Miami Herald'', Miami Herald Media Co., April 21, 2010, by Lee Logan, Tallahassee Bureau: \"During a committee hearing on the bill, the Anti-Defamation League spoke against the bill, arguing that adding more categories to the hate crimes law would dilute its effect. But lawmakers were swayed by arguments in favor of protecting the homeless.\"</ref>\n\nWhen the [[anti-Mormon]] film ''[[The God Makers]]'' (1982) was produced, Rhonda M. Abrams, Central Pacific (San Francisco) Regional Director for ADL, wrote a critical review, including the following statement:\n\n{{quote|Had a similar movie been made with either Judaism or Catholicism as its target, it would be immediately denounced for the scurrilous piece that it is. I sincerely hope that people of all faiths will similarly repudiate ''The Godmakers'' as defamatory and untrue, and recognize it for what it truly represents - a challenge to the religious liberty of all.<ref>[http://www.fairmormon.org/perspectives/publications/the-truth-about-the-god-makers/ia Letter to Dr. Richard Lindsay], Director of Public Communications, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, May 25, 1984</ref>}}\n\nADL supports [[Comprehensive Immigration Reform Act of 2007|Comprehensive]] and [[DREAM Act]] legislation that would provide conditional permanent residency to certain illegal aliens of good moral character who graduate from U.S. high schools, arrived in the United States as minors, and lived in the country continuously for at least five years prior to the bill's enactment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Afirman que con el debate de reforma migratoria subieron los cr\u00edmenes de odio|publisher=EFE News Services|date=January 25, 2013|quote= La Liga Antidifamaci\u00f3n Jud\u00eda ( ADL ) asegur\u00f3 hoy que desde que se inici\u00f3 el debate sobre una reforma migratoria integral en Estados Unidos se ha registrado un aumento de los cr\u00edmenes de odio contra los hispanos. ... Por su parte, el director del Departamento de Asuntos Legales de ADL, Steven Freeman, dijo a Efe que esta organizaci\u00f3n aboga por una reforma migratoria integral y el Dream Act}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, ADL condemned remarks by [[Ovadia Yosef]] that the sole purpose of non-Jews was to serve the Jews.<ref>Mozgovaya, Natasha. \"[http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/adl-slams-shas-spiritual-leader-for-saying-non-jews-were-born-to-serve-jews-1.320235?localLinksEnabled=false ADL slams Shas spiritual leader for saying non-Jews 'were born to serve Jews'].\" Haaretz Service. October 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nADL has spoken out against [[McCarthyism]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Norwood|first1=Stephen Harlan|last2=Pollack|first2=Eunice G.|title=Encyclopedia of American Jewish History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IB3mBsgfIHQC&pg=PA245|year=2008|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-638-1|page=245}}</ref>\n\nADL has supported some moves of the Trump Administration, and criticized others. For example, the organization welcomed President Trump moving the U.S. Embassy to Jerusalem, thereby underscoring that Jerusalem was the capitol of Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-welcomes-president-trumps-announcement-on-jerusalem-calls-for-focus-on|title=ADL Welcomes President Trump's Announcement on Jerusalem; Calls for Focus on Peace Negotiations and Reducing Tensions|last=|first=|date=December 6, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL CEO and National Director Jonathan Greenblatt traveled to Israel to join Trump administration officials at the official opening ceremony of the embassy in Jerusalem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-celebrates-historic-milestone-as-us-embassy-opens-in-jerusalem|title=ADL Celebrates 'Historic Milestone' as U.S. Embassy Opens in Jerusalem|last=|first=|date=May 14, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL has also called for key Trump Administration executive Stephen Miller, the architect of the Trump administration policies on immigration, to be fired and condemned him as a white supremacist.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Relations with religious and ethnic groups ==\n\n=== Relations with Arabs and Muslims ===\n{{See also|Projects working for peace among Israelis and Arabs}}\n\nIn 2012, ADL released a statement opposing groups like the [[Stop Islamization of America]] and [[Stop Islamization of Europe]], and activists such as [[Pamela Geller]] and [[David Yerushalmi]], describing them as \"anti-Muslim bigots\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/article/stop-islamization-of-america-sioa|title=Stop Islamization of America (SIOA)|website=Anti-Defamation League}}</ref>\n\nSince U.S. Reprentatives [[Rashida Tlaib]] (D-MI) and [[Ilhan Omar]] (D-MN) were elected to the U.S. House of Representatives in late 2018, becoming in 2019 the first two Muslim women to serve in the U.S. Congress,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5445303/ilhan-omar-rashida-tlaib-midterm/|title=Ilhan Omar and Rashida Tlaib Just Became the First Muslim Women Elected to Congress|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL at times has defended them from racist and [[Islamophobia|Islamaphobic]] attacks,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JGreenblattADL/status/1102207176746156035|title=Tweet from ADL CEO Jonathan Greenblatt|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> as well as from what ADL has viewed as partisan efforts to weaponize accusations of antisemitism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitchy.com/brettt-3136/2019/05/13/adl-ceo-says-its-unacceptable-for-elected-officials-to-weaponize-rashida-tlaibs-comments/|title=ADL CEO says it's unacceptable for elected officials to 'weaponize' Rashida Tlaib's comments|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Indeed, Rep. Omar's \"inspiring\" story, as the first Somali-American lawmaker, was included in a book commissioned by ADL. ''The Good Fight,'' published before Rep. Omar's election to Congress, tells the stories of Americans who have fought for equality''.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ADL/status/943186695666708481|title=ADL Tweet, December 19, 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegoodfightbook.org/|title=Publishers' blurbs for \"The Good Fight\"|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Since their election to Congress, however, ADL also has repeatedly and harshly criticized Reps. Omar and Tlaib<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-statement-concerning-rep-rashida-tlaibs-tweet-on-pending-bds-bill-in|title=ADL Statement Concerning Rep. Rashida Tlaib's Tweet on Pending BDS Bill in Congress|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-calls-on-house-leadership-to-take-action-after-rep-omars-anti-semitic|title=ADL Calls on House Leadership to Take Action After Rep. Omar's Anti-Semitic Tweets|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/adl-rejects-omars-good-faith-defense-asks-pelosi-to-condemn-anti-semitic-rhetoric/|title=ADL Rejects Omar's 'Good Faith' Defense, Asks Pelosi to Condemn Anti-Semitic Rhetoric|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> for what it deemed to be antisemitic remarks and the spreading of dangerous antisemitic tropes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/jan/28/rashida-tlaib-responds-after-adl-accuses-her-of-sp/|title=Rep. Rashida Tlaib responds after ADL accuses her of spreading anti-Semitic 'blood libel'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>  \n\n=== Relations with African-Americans ===\nIn 1997, the National Center for Black-Jewish Relations of [[Dillard University]], a [[historically black college|historically black university]] in [[New Orleans]], awarded the director of ADL, Abraham H. Foxman, with its first Annual [[Martin Luther King, Jr]].\u2013Donald R. Mintz Freedom and Justice Award.\n\nIn 2004, ADL became the lead partner in the Peace and Diversity Academy, a new New York City public high school with predominantly black and Hispanic students. In celebration of [[Black History Month]], the ADL created and distributed lesson plans to middle and high school teachers about [[Shirley Chisholm]] (1924\u20132005), the first black woman elected to the [[US Congress]], and an important civil rights leader.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nADL has also publicly accused a number of prominent African Americans of being anti-Semitic:\n\n* ADL has catalogued a more than three-decade history of [[Nation of Islam]] leader [[Louis Farrakhan]]'s espousal of anti-Semitic rhetoric such as claims that certain Jews are \"not real Jews\" and that they are \"wicked deceivers of the American people\" who \"sucked [Americans'] blood\", and that powerful Jews promote homosexuality and control black leadership.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/special_reports/farrakhan_own_words2/farrakhan_own_words.asp |title=Farrakhan In His Own Words |publisher=ADL}}</ref> Farrakhan first attracted the attention of the ADL with comments in a March 11, 1984, radio broadcast saying that, \"[[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] was a very great man\".<ref name=\"finalcall\">{{cite journal |title=Farrakhan and the Jewish Rift; How It All Started |journal=[[The Final Call]] |url=http://www.finalcall.com/perspectives/rift.html}}</ref> Farrakhan insists that he was using the word 'great' in the sense of 'Great Depression' or 'great white shark'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.noi.org/judaism-religion/|title=Minister Farrakhan rebuts fraudulent \"Judaism is a Gutter Religion\" canard|date=August 5, 2010|publisher=}}</ref> and on June 24, 1984, he described the Jewish state as \"structured on injustice, thievery, lying and deceit and using the name of God to shield your dirty religion under His holy and righteous name.\"<ref name=\"finalcall\" /> ADL has urged various groups including the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]] (whose leader [[Benjamin Chavis]] developed a working relationship with Farrakhan in 1994) to dissociate themselves from Farrakhan and his views.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Foxman |first=Abraham H. |authorlink=Abraham Foxman |date=July 20, 1994 |title=Today's N.A.A.C.P. Draws on History; Set Farrakhan Aside |journal=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9503E7DE143EF933A15754C0A962958260}}</ref>\n* In 1984 ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' reported that then-ADL national director Nathan Perlmutter said that Rev. [[Jesse Jackson]], Sr. was anti-Semitic, after Jackson referred to New York City as \"Hymietown\".<ref>{{cite journal |date=February 23, 1984 |title=Post Reaffirms Report On Jackson Comment |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=13 |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0E10FB3B5D0C708EDDAB0894DC484D81}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |date=February 27, 1984 |title=Jackson Admits Saying 'Hymie' And Apologizes At A Synagogue |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=16 |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30A14F83C5D0C748EDDAB0894DC484D81}}</ref> However, ADL later reconciled with Jackson and has worked with him on the issue of the Iranian Jewish community.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Rev. Jesse Jackson Meets with Iranian Jewish Families Pledges to Intercede on Behalf of Imprisoned Jews |publisher=ADL |date=June 11, 1999 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASInt_13/3401_13.asp}}</ref>\n* Film Director [[Spike Lee]] was criticized by the Anti-Defamation League for his portrayal of Jewish nightclub owners Moe and Josh Flatbush in his film ''[[Mo' Better Blues]]'' (1990). The Anti-Defamation League said that the characterizations of the nightclub owners \"dredge up an age-old and highly dangerous form of anti-Semitic stereotyping\", and it was \"disappointed that Spike Lee \u2013 whose success is largely due to his efforts to break down racial stereotypes and prejudice \u2013 has employed the same kind of tactics that he supposedly deplores\".<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 16, 1990 |title=Spike Lee's Jews and the Passage From Benign Cliche Into Bigotry|journal=[[The New York Times]] |author=Caryn James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/16/movies/critic-s-notebook-spike-lee-s-jews-passage-benign-cliche-into-bigotry.html}}</ref> Lee's portrayal also angered the B'nai B'rith and other such Jewish organizations, causing Lee to apologize via an Opinion-Editorial article in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 13, 2006 |title=The Angriest Auteur|journal=[[New York Magazine]] |author=Ariel Levy|url=http://nymag.com/movies/profiles/19144/}}</ref>\n* During the 2002 election cycle, ADL, in a letter to ''The New York Times'', harshly criticized [[Congressional Black Caucus]] member [[Cynthia McKinney]] of Georgia for launching attacks perceived as racial against her Jewish opponent. According to an August 19, 2002, article in ''The New York Times'', ADL Director Abraham Foxman said, \"It made sense that Jewish Americans would want to contribute to efforts to replace Ms. McKinney\".\n* In February 2005, ADL National Director Abraham Foxman called it hypocritical for hip-hop producer [[Russell Simmons]] to lead an ad campaign against anti-Semitism while, in Foxman's view, also defending or excusing Louis Farrakhan's anti-Semitic statements.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Calls on Russell Simmons to Distance Himself from Minister Farrakhan |publisher=ADL |date=February 14, 2005 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASUS_12/4645_12.htm}}</ref> Later that year ADL urged prominent black leaders including Simmons to reconsider their support for Farrakhan and [[Malik Zulu Shabazz]] organizing the [[Millions More Movement]] and to \"stand up\" against black anti-Semitism.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Urges Prominent African-American Leaders to Reconsider Their Support for the \"Millions More Movement\" |publisher=ADL |date=May 2, 2005 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASUS_12/4707_12.htm}}</ref> Simmons, responding to ADL Director Abraham Foxman, said, \"simply put, you are misguided, arrogant, and very disrespectful of African Americans, and most importantly, your statements will unintentionally or intentionally lead to a negative impression of Jews in the minds of millions of African Americans\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.millionsmoremovement.com/news/russell-simmons05-09-2005.htm |title=Russell Simmons Responds to Abraham Foxman about the Millions More Movement |last=Simmons |first=Russell |authorlink=Russell Simmons |date=May 9, 2005 |publisher=[[Millions More Movement]]}}</ref> Foxman replied, \"If there were a Jewish event which was led by an out-and-out racist, I would expect Black leaders to say to me that ADL should have nothing to do with it. And I would agree with them, rather than condemn them for their action.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/media_watch/internet/20050510-Russell+Simmons.htm |title=Response to Russell Simmons |date=May 9, 2005 |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 16, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607153052/http://www.adl.org/media_watch/internet/20050510-Russell+Simmons.htm |archive-date=June 7, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Interfaith camp ===\nADL's New England Regional Office has also established a faith-based initiative called \"The Interfaith Youth Leadership Program\", better known as \"Camp If\", or Camp Interfaith. Involving teenagers of the Christian, Jewish, and Islamic faiths, the camp brings the teens together for a week at camp where the teens bond and learn about each other's cultures. The camp has emerged as a new attempt to foster good relations between younger members of the Abrahamic faiths.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Siek |first=Stephanie V. |date=April 6, 2006 |title=A different kind of camp |journal=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2006/04/06/a_different_kind_of_camp/}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n{{POV section|date=December 2018}}\n\n===Arab American and African American lawsuit against ADL===\nIn 1996, ADL settled a federal civil lawsuit filed by groups representing [[African Americans]] and [[Arab Americans]] that alleged that the ADL hired agents with police ties to gather information. ADL did not admit any wrongdoing, but agreed to a restraining injunction barring ADL from obtaining information from state employees who are forbidden by law to divulge such information. ADL also agreed to contribute $25,000 to a fund that funds inter-community relationship projects, and cover the plaintiffs' legal costs of $175,000.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1996-09-04/news/mn-40507_1_anti-defamation-league Anti-Defamation League Settles Lawsuit by Civil Rights Groups], LA Times, 4 September 1996</ref><ref>[https://www.jta.org/1996/09/06/archive/adl-to-pay-200000-to-settle-suit-alleging-spying-activities ADL to Pay $200,000 to Settle Suit Alleging Spying Activities], JTA, 6 September 1996</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QM1hloeMQqgC&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=%22Anti-Defamation+League%22+settlement+1996&source=bl&ots=d1L3G8qgX8&sig=Auo9IfPqSIcVRuL2g7zlDpFJTF4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjO5Y7Pr7XfAhWQDuwKHeNbB1MQ6AEwC3oECAIQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Anti-Defamation%20League%22%20settlement%201996&f=false American Jewish Year, Book 1998], page 96</ref>\n\n=== Armenian Genocide controversy ===\n{{Undue weight section|date=February 2019}}\nIn 2007, Abraham Foxman came under criticism for his stance on the [[Armenian Genocide]]. ADL had previously described it as a \"massacre\" and an \"atrocity,\" but not as a \"genocide.\"<ref name=\"http\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/Mise_00/5114_00.htm\n|title=ADL Statement on the Armenian Genocide\n|date=August 21, 2007}}</ref> Foxman had earlier opposed calls for the U.S. Government to recognise it as a \"genocide.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewcy.com/feature/2007-07-09/fire_foxman |title=Fire Foxman: Denying the Armenian Genocide should be the last atrocity perpetrated by the ADL chief.}}</ref> \"I don't think congressional action will help reconcile the issue. The resolution takes a position; it comes to a judgement,\" said Foxman in a statement issued to the [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]. \"The [[Turkey|Turks]] and [[Armenia]]ns need to revisit their past. The Jewish community shouldn't be the arbiter of that history, nor should the U.S. Congress, and \"a Congressional resolution on such matters is a counterproductive diversion and will not foster reconciliation between Turks and Armenians, and may put at risk the Turkish Jewish community and the important multilateral relationship between Turkey, Israel, and the United States.\"\n\nIn early August 2007, complaints about the Anti-Defamation League's refusal to acknowledge the [[Armenian Genocide]] led to [[Watertown, Massachusetts]]'s, unanimous town council decision to end its participation in ADL's \"No Place for Hate\" campaign. (Watertown is known for its Armenian population.) Also in August 2007, an editorial in ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' criticized ADL by saying that, \"as an organization concerned about human rights, it ought to acknowledge the [[genocide]] against the Armenian people during [[World War I]], and criticize Turkish attempts to repress the memory of this historical reality.\"<ref>{{cite news |date= August 3, 2007 |url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/editorials/articles/2007/08/03/a_genocide_not_to_be_denied/ |title=A genocide not to be denied |work=[[Boston Globe]]}}</ref> Then on August 17, 2007, ADL fired its regional [[New England]] director, Andrew H. Tarsy, for breaking ranks with the main organization and for saying that ADL should recognize the genocide.<ref name=obrien>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/18/adl_local_leader_fired_on_armenian_issue/\n|title=ADL local leader fired on Armenian issue: Genocide question sparked bitter debate\n|work=The Boston Globe\n|first=Keith\n|last=O'Brien\n|date=August 18, 2007}}</ref> In an August 21, 2007, news release, ADL changed its position and acknowledged the genocide, but maintained its opposition to congressional resolutions aimed at recognizing it.<ref name=\"http\" /> Foxman wrote, \"the consequences of those actions,\" by the [[Ottoman Empire]] against Armenians, \"were indeed tantamount to genocide.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/22/adl_chief_bows_to_critics/\n|title=ADL chief bows to critics: Foxman cites rift, calls Armenian deaths genocide\n|first=Keith\n|last=O'Brien\n|date=August 22, 2007\n|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The [[Turkish government]] condemned the league's statement.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/24/turkey_condemns_statement_by_adl/\n|title=Turkey condemns statement by ADL\n|first=Michael\n|last=Levenson\n|date=August 24, 2007\n|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> Andrew H. Tarsy was rehired by the league on August 27,<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/city_region/breaking_news/2007/08/antidefamation_1.html\n|title=Anti-Defamation League rehires New England director\n|first=Keith\n|last=O'Brien\n|work=The Boston Globe\n|date=September 7, 2007}}</ref> though he has since chosen to step down from his position.<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/news/?content_id=4108\n |title        = Tarsy Resignation Draws Mixed Emotions From Area Colleagues\n |first        = Rachel\n |last         = Axelbank\n |publisher    = Jewish Advocate\n |date         = December 6, 2007\n |access-date  = January 7, 2008\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071210223450/http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/news/?content_id=4108\n |archive-date = December 10, 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nThe 2007 ADL \"Statement on the Armenian Genocide,\" was criticized by activists as failing to be a full, unequivocal acknowledgment of the [[Armenian genocide]], because the use of the qualifier \"tantamount\" was seen as inappropriate, and the use of the word \"consequences\" was seen as an attempt to circumvent the international legal definition of genocide by avoiding any language that would imply intent, a crucial aspect of the 1948 UN [[Genocide Convention]] definition. \n\nAfter Foxman's capitulation, the New England ADL pressed the organization's national leadership to support a congressional resolution acknowledging the genocide.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\" /> AT ADL's annual national meeting in early November 2007, the issue of the Armenian Genocide was discussed. After hours of closed-door debate at the annual national meeting in New York, the proposal was withdrawn.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\" /> The organization ultimately issued a one-sentence statement, saying \"The National Commission of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) today, at its annual meeting, decided to take no further action on the issue of the Armenian genocide.\"<ref>http://www.adl.org/PresRele/Mise_00/5162_00.htm</ref>\n\nThe ADL was criticized by many in the Armenian community, including ''The Armenian Weekly'' newspaper, in which writer Michael Mensoian stated:\n\n{{quote|The belated backtracking of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) in acknowledging the planned, systematic massacre of 1,500,000 Armenian men, women and children as \"\u2026tantamount to genocide\u2026\" is discouraging. Tantamount means something is equivalent. If it's equivalent, why avoid using the term? For the ADL to justify its newly adopted statement because the word genocide did not exist at the time indicates a halfhearted attempt to placate Armenians while not offending Turkey. Historians use the term genocide simply because it is the proper term to describe the horrific events that the Ottoman Turkish government unleashed on the Armenian people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://armenianweekly.com/|title=Home|website=The Armenian Weekly}}</ref>}}\n\nADL had earlier received direct pressure from the Turkish Foreign ministry.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.co.il/hasite/spages/911393.html \u05d8\u05d5\u05e8\u05e7\u05d9\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc: \u05e2\u05d6\u05e8\u05d5 \u05dc\u05e0\u05d5 \u05dc\u05e2\u05e6\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d4\u05db\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d0\u05de\u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d0\u05d9\u05ea \u05d1\u05e9\u05d5\u05d0\u05d4 \u05d4\u05d0\u05e8\u05de\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea] Haaretz, 10/10/07, Barak Ravid</ref> Tarsy submitted his resignation on December 4.<ref name=Woolhouse>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/12/05/adls_regional_leader_resigns/\n|title=ADL's regional leader resigns: Backers cite rift on genocide issue\n|first=Megan\n|last=Woolhouse\n|work=The Boston Globe\n|date=December 5, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn the subsequent months, some [[human rights]] commissions in other Massachusetts communities decided to follow Watertown's lead and withdraw from the ADL's No Place for Hate anti-discrimination program.<ref name=Woolhouse /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://medford.wickedlocal.com/x96464381|title=City recognizes Armenian genocide, suspends ADL membership|last=Esker/medford@cnc.com|first=Sharon Tosto|work=Medford Transcript|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2016, [[Jonathan Greenblatt]], then ADL's CEO and National Director for less than a year, published a blog post in which he wrote \"What happened to the Armenian people was unequivocally genocide\" and urged the U.S. to take a position recognizing the Armenian genocide.<ref>[[Jonathan Greenblatt|Greenblatt, Jonathan]] (May 13, 2016) [https://www.adl.org/blog/adl-on-the-armenian-genocide \"ADL on the Armenian Genocide\"] Anti-Defamation League website</ref>  In late 2019, ADL publicly endorsed and lobbied for a historic Congressional resolution commemorating the Armenian genocide, which passed the House of Representatives with bipartisan support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-endorses-congressional-resolution-commemorating-the-armenian-genocide|title=ADL Endorses Congressional Resolution Commemorating the Armenian Genocide|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/29/us/politics/armenian-genocide-resolution.html|title=House Passes Resolution Recognizing Armenian Genocide|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/12/us/politics/senate-armenian-genocide.html|title=Senate Passes Resolution Recognizing Armenian Genocide, in Defiance of Trump|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>  The U.S. Senate passed a similar resolution, which was also backed by ADL, but in December 2019 the Trump Administration, under pressure from Turkey's President Recep Tayyip Erdogan, refused to back recognition of the Armenian genocide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-armenian-genocide-erdogan-turkey-native-americans-a9250281.html|title=Trump refuses to back recognition of Armenian genocide after Erdogan threat|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Role in cancellation of speech by Tony Judt at Polish Consulate ===\nIn 2006, ADL, in addition to the [[American Jewish Committee]], was criticized by academic [[Tony Judt]] for allegedly pressuring the [[Poland|Polish]] [[List of diplomatic missions of Poland#North America|Consulate-General]] in New York to cancel a scheduled appearance by Judt at Network 20/20, a non-profit organization that rents space from the consulate. In an interview with the ''[[New York Sun]]'', Foxman claimed that the group \"had nothing to do with the cancellation,\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Stoll |first=Ira |authorlink=Ira Stoll |date=October 4, 2006 |title=Poland Abruptly Cancels a Speech By Local Critic of the Jewish State |journal=[[The New York Sun]] |url=http://www.nysun.com/article/40911?page_no=1}}</ref> insisting that ADL only called to ask if the event was being sponsored by the Polish government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/media_watch/newspapers/20061116-Chronicle+of+Higher+Ed.htm |title=Article on Free Speech and Israel Gets it Wrong |last=Foxman |first=Abraham H. |authorlink=Abraham Foxman |date=November 16, 2006 |publisher=ADL |access-date=December 18, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070213233147/http://www.adl.org/media_watch/newspapers/20061116-Chronicle+of+Higher+Ed.htm |archive-date=February 13, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Polish Consul General Krzysztof Kasprzyk suggested in an interview with ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that calls by the ADL and the American Jewish Committee were \"exercising a delicate pressure.\"<ref name=\"WP sparks\">{{cite journal |last=Powell |first=Michael |date=October 9, 2006 |title=In N.Y., Sparks Fly Over Israel Criticism |journal=[[The Washington Post]] |pages=A03 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/08/AR2006100800817.html}}</ref> In reference to the role of ADL and the American Jewish Committee in organizing the cancellations, Judt told ''The Washington Post'': \"This is serious and frightening, and only in America\u2014not in Israel\u2014is this a problem. These are Jewish organizations that believe they should keep people who disagree with them on the Middle East away from anyone who might listen.\"<ref name=\"WP sparks\" /> ADL denied the charges. According to Foxman, \"I think they made the right decision... He's taken the position that Israel shouldn't exist. That puts him on our radar.\"<ref name=\"WP sparks\" />\n\n=== Denver defamation suit ===\nIn 1994, ADL became embroiled in a dispute between neighbors in Denver, Colorado. Upon the involvement of ADL, the petty quarreling of next door neighbors, initially about garden plants and pets, quickly escalated into both civil and criminal court cases involving charges of anti-Semitism, and counter charges of defamation.\n\nCandace and Mitchell Aronson, Jewish next door neighbors of William and Dorothy Quigley, used a [[Radio Shack]] police scanner to listen in on the cordless telephone conversations of Mr. and Mrs. Quigley. When the Aronsons heard the Quigleys discuss a campaign to drive them from the neighborhood with \"Nazi scare tactics,\" the Aronsons contacted the Denver office of ADL. Upon the advice of ADL, the Aronsons then recorded the Quigley's private telephone conversations. The conversations included discussions of putting pictures of oven doors on the Aronsons' home (a reference to the Holocaust), burning one of the Aronson children, and wishing that the Aronsons had been killed in a suicide bombing. (The Quigleys later indicated that these remarks were not anti-Semitic, and were only intended to be sick humor.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/13674/edition_id/264/format/html/displaystory.html|title=Jewish News Weekly|publisher=}}</ref> Neither the Aronsons nor ADL were aware that Congress had amended federal wiretap law which made it illegal to record conversations from a cordless telephone, to transcribe the material, and to use the transcriptions for any purpose.\n\nNot knowing about the new federal law, the Aronsons used the tapes as the basis for a federal civil lawsuit against the Quigleys in December 1994. A day later, Saul Rosenthal, Regional Director of ADL, appeared at a news conference with the Aronsons in which he described their encounter with the Quigleys as \"a vicious anti-Semitic campaign,\" based solely on conversations he and associates had with the Aronsons. Later that day, Mr. Rosenthal expanded on his remarks in an interview on a Denver radio talk show.\n\nTwo days later, Jefferson County prosecutors used the tapes as the basis for filing criminal charges against the Quigleys.\n\nThe Quigleys became the target of scorn and ridicule. They received threats, and were forced to hire security guards for their home. A package of dog feces was mailed to their house. When they attended church, their priest openly chastised them in his sermon. The family was forced to shop in other towns, to avoid being recognized.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quigley v. Rosenthall|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-10th-circuit/1360107.html|website=Findlaw|publisher=Findlaw|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> Mr. Quigley's career with [[United Artists]] suffered serious damage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lane|first1=George|title=Charges of bigotry backfire|url=http://extras.denverpost.com/news/news0429.htm|accessdate=June 23, 2015|issue=April 29, 2000|newspaper=Denver Post}}</ref>\n\nUpon investigation, and after assistant district attorney Steven Jensen heard on the tapes the context of Mrs. Quigley's remarks, all charges but one, a misdemeanor traffic violation against Mr. Quigley, were dropped. The district attorney issued two letters of apology to the Quigleys, saying he found no evidence that either had engaged in \"anti-Semitic conduct or harassment.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/13/us/privacy-rights-win-over-bias-charges-in-defamation-case.html | work=The New York Times | title=Privacy Rights Win Over Bias Charges In Defamation Case | date=May 13, 2000}}</ref>\n\nThe Quigleys brought a lawsuit against ADL, Rosenthal, the Aronsons, and two ADL volunteer attorneys. The two attorneys agreed to pay $350,000 to the Quigleys in settlement of their claims. The Quigley settlement with the Aronsons did not involve a cash payment. The Quigleys maintained their action against ADL and Rosenthal, which was heard in federal court. A federal jury returned a verdict of $10 million in favor of the Quigleys. ADL appealed.\n\nAccording to an April 13, 2001, article in ''[[The Forward]]'', upon hearing the appeal, a federal judge \"lambasted the ADL for labeling a nasty neighborhood feud as an anti-Semitic event\" and upheld most of Quigley's $10 million [[lawsuit]] for [[slander and libel|defamation]]. According to a report in the ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'', with accrued interest, the judgment amounted to more than $12 million.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-114248316.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608173726/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-114248316.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 8, 2013|title=ADL Pays More Than $12 Million to Former Evergreen Couple. (City Desk/Local)|date=March 12, 2004}}</ref>\n\n=== New antisemitism controversy ===\n{{Main|New antisemitism}}\nA book entitled ''The [[New Anti-Semitism]]'' (New York, 1974) by ADL national leaders Arnold Forster and Benjamin R. Epstein argued that a new kind of anti-Semitism is on the rise. A subsequent book, ''The Real Anti-Semitism in America'' (New York, 1982) was written by ADL national leader Nathan Perlmutter and his wife, Ruth Ann Perlmutter. In ''Never Again? The Threat of the New Anti-Semitism'' (San Francisco, 2003), by ADL's national director Abraham Foxman, he states on page 4: \"We currently face as great a threat to the safety and security of the Jewish people as the one we faced in the 1930s\u2014if not a greater one.\"<ref name=\"adl.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/Anti_semitism/never_again.asp |title=Never Again? The Threat of the New Anti-Semitism |publisher=ADL}}</ref>\n\nReviewing Forster and Epstein's work in a May 1974 issue of ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'', Earl Raab, founding director of the Nathan Perlmutter Institute for Jewish Advocacy at [[Brandeis University]], argued that a \"new anti-Semitism\" was indeed emerging in America, in the form of opposition to the collective rights of the Jewish people, but he criticized Forster and Epstein for conflating it with anti-Israel bias.<ref>Raab, Earl. \"Is there a New Anti-Semitism?\", ''Commentary'', May 1974, pp. 53\u201354.</ref> Allan Brownfeld writes that Forster and Epstein's new definition of antisemitism trivialized the concept by turning it into \"a form of political blackmail\" and \"a weapon with which to silence any criticism of either Israel or U.S. policy in the Middle East,\"<ref>{{cite journal\n  |title = Anti-Semitism: Its Changing Meaning\n  |last = Brownfeld\n  |first = Allan\n  |journal = [[Journal of Palestine Studies]]\n  |publisher = [[Institute for Palestine Studies]]\n  |issn = 1533-8614\n  |volume = 16\n  |issue = 3\n  |year = 1987\n  |pages = 53\u201367\n  |doi = 10.2307/2536789\n  |jstor = 2536789\n  }}</ref> while Edward S. Shapiro, in ''A Time for Healing: American Jewry Since World War II'', has written that, \"Forster and Epstein implied that the new anti-Semitism was the inability of Gentiles to love Jews and Israel enough.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Shapiro|first=Edward S.|title=A Time for Healing: American Jewry Since World War II|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|year=1992|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780801843471/page/47 47]|isbn=0-8018-4347-2|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780801843471/page/47}}</ref>\n\n[[Norman Finkelstein]] has written that organizations such as the Anti-Defamation League have brought forward charges of new anti-Semitism at various intervals since the 1970s, \"not to fight antisemitism, but rather to exploit the historical suffering of Jews in order to immunize Israel against criticism.\"<ref name=Finkelstein21>{{cite book|last=Finkelstein|first=Norman|title=Beyond Chutzpah: On the Misuse of Anti-Semitism and the Abuse of History|publisher=University of California Press|year=2005|pages=21\u201322}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' has reported that the ADL has repeatedly accused Finkelstein of being a \"[[Holocaust denial|Holocaust denier]],\" and that \"these charges have proved baseless.\"<ref name=\"WP sparks\" />\n\n=== Conflict with Jews for the Preservation of Firearms Ownership ===\nADL is an advocate for [[gun control]] legislation.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.adl.org/civil_rights/platformcommittee-2004.pdf\n|title= ADL Presentation to the Platform Committees of the Democratic and Republican National Conventions\n|accessdate= January 23, 2008\n|date=June 2004\n|publisher= ADL\n|quote= The Anti-Defamation League has been an advocate for strong, effective, and sensible gun control legislation.\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080227040630/http://www.adl.org/civil_rights/platformcommittee-2004.pdf| archivedate= February 27, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> The ADL filed amicus briefs in support of challenged gun control legislation in the Supreme Court cases of ''[[District of Columbia v. Heller]]'' and ''[[McDonald v. City of Chicago]]'', citing the need to keep guns out of the possession of violent extremists.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jta.org/2008/06/27/default/jewish-groups-slam-handgun-decision|publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|date=June 27, 2008|title=Jewish groups slam handgun decision}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/sites/default/files/documents/civil-rights/adl-in-the-courts/amicus-briefs/brief-pdfs/ab-2010-mcdonald-v-city-of-chicago.pdf|title=Brief of Amicus Curiae Anti-Defamation League in Support of Respondent|work=McDonald v. City of Chicago}}</ref>\n\nGun rights group [[Jews for the Preservation of Firearms Ownership]] (JPFO), which espouses the [[Nazi gun control argument]], has been highly critical of the ADL.<ref>The Liberty Crew (September 20, 2007) [http://www.jpfo.org/alerts/alert20070920.htm \"Why Does the ADL Support Nazi-Based Laws?\"] JPFO.org.</ref><ref>Editors (1997\u20131999) [http://www.jpfo.org/filegen-a-m/jpfacts.htm \"JPFO Facts vs. ADL Lies.\"] JPFO.org.</ref><ref>JPFO editors [http://www.jpfo.org/images02/handbill-adl.jpg \"The Anti-Defamation League Is Anti-American.\"] JPFO.org.</ref> Foxman has written about the JPFO: \"Anti-Semitism has a long and painful history, and the linkage to gun control is a tactic by Jews for the Preservation of Firearms Ownership to manipulate the fear of anti-Semitism toward their own end.\"<ref>Foxman, Abraham H. (May 21, 1995) [https://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/21/opinion/l-nra-doesn-t-represent-george-bush-or-even-most-members-jewish-pro-gun-group-549095.html \"N.R.A. Doesn't Represent George Bush or Even Most Members; Jewish Pro-Gun Group.\"] ''New York Times.''</ref>\n\n=== Park51 Community Center controversy ===\nOn July 28, 2010, ADL issued a statement in which it expressed opposition to the [[Park51]] Community Center, which sponsors planned to build near the [[World Trade Center site]] in New York. ADL stated, \"The controversy which has emerged regarding the building of a Community Center at this location is counterproductive to the healing process. Therefore, under these unique circumstances, we believe the City of New York would be better served if an alternative location could be found.\"<ref name=\"berk\" /> ADL denounced what it saw as bigoted attacks on the project. Foxman opined that some of those who oppose the mosque are \"bigots,\" and that the plan's proponents may have every right to build the mosque at that location. Nevertheless, he said that building the mosque at that site would unnecessarily cause more pain for families of some victims of 9/11.<ref name=\"berk\">Jacob Berkman, [http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/07/30/2740283/adl-opposes-world-trade-center-mosque ADL opposes World Trade Center Mosque] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100803005159/http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/07/30/2740283/adl-opposes-world-trade-center-mosque |date=August 3, 2010 }}, [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]], July 30, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jacoby |first=Susan |url=http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/spirited_atheist/2010/08/ground_zero_mosque_protected_by_first_amendment--but_its_still_salt_in_a_wound.html |title=The Spirited Atheist: Ground Zero mosque protected by First Amendment \u2013 but it's still salt in a wound|newspaper=The Washington Post |date=August 6, 2010 |accessdate=April 24, 2015| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100817115334/http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/spirited_atheist/2010/08/ground_zero_mosque_protected_by_first_amendment--but_its_still_salt_in_a_wound.html| archivedate= August 17, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes6\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/05/opinion/l05mosque.html | work=The New York Times | title=The ADL, the Mosque and the Fight Against Bigotry | date=August 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.adl.org/PresRele/CvlRt_32/5820_32.htm \"Statement On Islamic Community Center Near Ground Zero\"], Anti-Defamation League, July 28, 2010.</ref>\n\nThis opposition to the Community Center led to criticism of the statement from various parties, including one ADL board member, the [[American Jewish Committee]], the [[Jewish Community Relations Council|Jewish Community Relations Council of New York]], Rabbi [[Irwin Kula]], columnists [[Jeffrey Goldberg]] and [[Peter Beinart]], the [[Interfaith Alliance]],<ref>Adam Dickter, [http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new_york/wake_adl_jewish_groups_back_ground_zero_mosque \"In Wake Of ADL, Jewish Groups Back Ground Zero Mosque\"], ''[[The Jewish Week]]'', August 3, 2010.</ref> and the [[Shalom Center]].<ref>Grace Rauh, [http://manhattan.ny1.com/content/top_stories/123265/jewish-leaders-rally-in-support-of-wtc-mosque/ \"Jewish Leaders Rally In Support Of WTC Mosque\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816033945/http://manhattan.ny1.com/content/top_stories/123265/jewish-leaders-rally-in-support-of-wtc-mosque |date=August 16, 2010 }}, ''[[NY1]]'', August 5, 2010.</ref> In an interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'' Abe Foxman published a statement in reaction to criticism.<ref>Abraham H. Foxman, [http://www.adl.org/ADL_Opinions/Interfaith/Mosque_Ground_Zero.htm \"The Mosque at Ground Zero\"], originally published in ''[[Huffington Post]]'', August 2, 2010.</ref> In protest of ADL's stance, [[CNN]] host [[Fareed Zakaria]] returned the Hubert H. Humphrey First Amendment Freedoms Prize ADL awarded him in 2005.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/08/07/new.york.zakaria.adl/ CNN host returns ADL award over stance on Islamic center], [[CNN]], August 9, 2010.</ref> ADL chair Robert G. Sugarman responded to a critical ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorial<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/04/opinion/04wed1.html A Monument to Tolerance], ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorial, August 3, 2010.</ref> writing, \"we have publicly taken on those who criticized the mosque in ways that reflected anti-Muslim bigotry or used the controversy for that purpose\" and stating that ADL has combated [[Islamophobia]].<ref>Robert G. Sugarman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/05/opinion/l05mosque.html \"Letter to New York Times\"] (August 4, 2010) ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU)\n*[[American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee]]\n*[[Antisemitism in the United States]]\n*[[Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations]]\n* ''[[Defamation (film)|Defamation]]'' (Documentary movie by [[Yoav Shamir]])\n*[[Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]]\n*[[Israel lobby in the United States]]\n*[[Jewish Council for Public Affairs]]\n*[[Jews Against Anti-Christian Defamation]]\n*[[Membership discrimination in California social clubs]]\n*[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]\n*[[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.adl.org Official Website]\n\n{{Anti-Defamation League|state=expanded}}\n{{Antisemitism topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{Organized Jewish Life in the United States}}\n{{World Jewish Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-Defamation League| ]]\n[[Category:1913 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-racist organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish anti-racism]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish political organizations]]\n[[Category:Opposition to antisemitism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1913]]\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Civil liberties advocacy groups in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox organization\n|name         = Anti-Defamation League\n|image        = ADL logo (2018).svg\n|size         = 200px\n|motto        = Fighting Hate for Good\n|formation    = {{Start date and age|1913|09}} (as Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith)\n|founder      = [[Sigmund Livingston]]\n|headquarters = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|type         = [[Civil rights]] law\n|leader_title = Director\n|leader_name  = [[Jonathan Greenblatt]]\n|key_people   = Sigmund Livingston (Founder)<br />Robert G. Sugarman (Chairman)\n|website      = [http://www.adl.org/ www.adl.org/]\n}}\n{{Antisemitism}}\nThe '''Anti-Defamation League''' ('''ADL'''; formerly known as the '''Anti-Defamation League of [[B'nai B'rith]]''') is an international [[Jews|Jewish]] [[non-governmental organization]] based in the [[United States]]. It was founded in late September 1913 by the Independent Order of [[B'nai B'rith]], a [[Jews|Jewish]] [[service organization]]. ADL subsequently split from B'nai B'rith and continued as an independent U.S. Section 501(c)(3) nonprofit. In its 2017 annual information Form 990, ADL reported total revenues of just over $70 million, from contributions and grants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdf.guidestar.org/PDF_Images/2017/131/818/2017-131818723-1035a764-9.pdf|title=ANTI-DEFAMATION LEAGUE FORM 990|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> \n\nADL states that its mission is a dual one: \"To stop the defamation of the Jewish people, and to secure justice and fair treatment to all\" via the development of \"new programs, policies and skills to expose and combat whatever holds us back.\"<ref name=\"ADLCharter\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-mission|title=Our Mission|website=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> Opposing [[Antisemitism]] and extremism, ADL describes its \"ultimate goal\" as \"a world in which no group or individual suffers from bias, discrimination or hate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are|title=Who We Are|website=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe headquarters of ADL are located in [[New York City]]. [[Abraham Foxman]] was the national director from 1987 for more than a quarter century. In November 2014, it was announced that [[Jonathan Greenblatt]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/leadership/staff/jonathan-greenblatt|title=Jonathan Greenblatt, CEO and National Director|last=Anti-Defamation League|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> a serial social entrepreneur, former Silicon Valley tech executive and former Obama Administration official who had not operated within the Jewish communal organization world prior to his hiring, would succeed Foxman as national director in July 2015.<ref>[http://www.jta.org/2014/11/06/news-opinion/united-states/white-house-aide-to-succeed-abe-foxman-as-adl-chief-1 \"White House aide Jonathan Greenblatt to succeed Abe Foxman as ADL chief\"], ''[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]'', November 6, 2014.</ref> The national chair of the governing board of directors is Esta Gordon Epstein.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newengland.adl.org/news/longtime-adl-boston-leader-esta-epstein-named-chair-of-organizations-national-board/|title=LONGTIME ADL BOSTON LEADER ESTA GORDON EPSTEIN NAMED CHAIR OF ORGANIZATION'S NATIONAL BOARD|last=|first=|date=November 8, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>[http://www.adl.org/about-adl/adl-leadership.html Barry Curtiss-Lusher, National Chair] ADL.org, ''accessed November 9, 2014.''</ref> ADL has 25 regional offices in the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-in-the-us|title=Anti-Semitism in the US|work=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019|quote=Through our network of 25 regional offices}}</ref> including a Government Relations Office in Washington DC, and is also active overseas, with an office in Israel and staff in Europe.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-globally|title=Anti-Semitism Globally|work=Anti-Defamation League|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nADL has been criticized both from the right<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/12/anti-defamation-league-trump-232049|title=ADL combats criticism of being too tough on Trump|last=|first=|date=January 1, 2016|website=Politico.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and left of the U.S. political spectrum, including within the American Jewish community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/opinion/.premium-from-left-and-right-why-is-a-league-of-haters-descending-on-the-adl-1.6053744|title=Opinion From Left and Right, Why Is a League of Haters Descending on the ADL?|newspaper=Haaretz|date=May 3, 2018|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020|last1=Cohen|first1=Debra Nussbaum}}</ref> This is in large part -- but by no means only -- because the American far left (which includes some American Jewish groups, such as [[Jewish Voice for Peace]]) has increasingly condemned and sought sanctions against Israel for its treatment of Israeli Arabs and Palestinians living in the territories and has extrapolated from that position that ADL cannot credibly claim to be a civil rights organization as long as it also supports Israel as a Jewish homeland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.losangelesblade.com/2019/01/31/creating-change-2019-creates-controversy-again/|title=Creating Change 2019 creates controversy, again|last=|first=|date=January 31, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28. 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://droptheadl.wordpress.com/why-droptheadl/|title=#DropTheADL: Communities say NO to the Anti-Defamation League in our schools, coalitions, and movements|last=|first=|date=May 30, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the left, key ADL former or present positions that generate criticism, even condemnation, are the organization's support for the existence of [[Israel]] as a Jewish homeland, domestic spying allegations, its former stance on the [[Armenian Genocide]],<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|first1=Rupen|last1=Janbazian|accessdate=2019-09-25|title=ADL's Official Recognition of Armenian Genocide Ends Years-Long Controversy|url=http://armenianweekly.com/2016/05/16/adl-armenian-genocide-2016/|date=16 May 2016|website=The Armenian Weekly}}</ref> since repudiated and apologized for,<ref name=\":0\" /> and what frequently is alleged by the left to be ADL's conflation of opposition to Israel with [[antisemitism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/how-a-jewish-civil-rights-group-became-a-villain-on-the-far-left/|title=How a Jewish civil rights group became a villain on the far-left|last=Sales|first=Ben|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Shira|last1=Hanau|accessdate=2019-09-25|title=Can ADL Be A Moral Voice For Millennials?|url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/can-adl-be-a-moral-voice-for-millennials/|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, rightwing groups and pundits, including very conservative Jewish groups, have attacked ADL, labeling it an arm of the Democratic party (presumably in part because its CEO, [[Jonathan Greenblatt]], was in the Obama administration)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/amari-sohrab/the-adl-smears-mike-pompeo/|title=The ADL Smears Mike Pompeo|last=Ahmari|first=Sohrab|date=April 19, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jns.org/opinion/whatever-happened-to-the-adl/|title=Whatever happened to the ADL?: The attack on Kavanaugh's nomination to the Supreme Court is the latest instance of how Jonathan Greenblatt has turned the venerable anti-Semitism watchdog into a partisan outfit.|last=Tobin|first=Jonathan|date=July 13, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> and decrying its civil rights agenda, which is vehemently in support of immigrants and refugees, trans rights and other [[LGBT|LGBTQ]] rights, against establishment of religion, and against [[Islamophobia|Islamaphobia]]. The ADL has also called for the firing of Trump administration official [[Stephen Miller (political advisor)|Stephen Miller]], the architect of the Administration's immigration policy.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/jewish-groups-stephen-miller-resign-white-nationalist_n_5dd69935e4b0e29d72800575?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly91cy5zZWFyY2gueWFob28uY29tLw&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAG5GoJ0dtOkPudr5tkzXMWY-wRmtd1nHDOfZ1c7WOW3gYQKtSQgDjZaIXDUnko0UMrEJVEYUXG3jMWrrsrV52jBKycFPCh7lje-saS6lbR17o5_4ikE4B7PIIACorUKfLxJXapH0BueU1WTMTER8dUqZKRH2Ep2TZ2Y83nmA0kDE|title=Jewish Groups Demand Stephen Miller Resign From White House|last=Mathias|first=Christopher|date=November 21, 2019|website=HuffPost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Origin ==\nFounded in late September 1913 by [[B'nai B'rith]], with [[Sigmund Livingston]] as its first leader, the ADL's charter states, {{quote|The immediate object of the League is to stop, by appeals to reason and conscience and, if necessary, by appeals to law, the defamation of the Jewish people. Its ultimate purpose is to secure justice and fair treatment to all citizens alike and to put an end forever to unjust and unfair discrimination against and ridicule of any sect or body of citizens.<ref name=ADLCharter />}}\nThe Anti-Defamation League was founded by B'nai B'rith as a response to attacks on Jews; the recent conviction of [[Leo Frank]] was mentioned by [[Adolf Kraus]] when he announced the creation of ADL.<ref>{{cite book|last=Moore|first=Deborah Dash|title=B'nai B'rith and the Challenge of Ethnic Leadership|year=1981|publisher=State University of New York Press|isbn=978-0-87395-480-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/bnaibrithch00moor/page/108 108]|url=https://archive.org/details/bnaibrithch00moor/page/108}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jews in American Politics: Essays|year=2001|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-0-7425-0181-2|page=105|author=Jerome A. Chanes|editor1=Louis S |editor2=y Maisel |editor3=Ira N. Forman |editor4=Donald Altschiller |editor5=Charles Walker Bassett |chapter=Who Does What?}}</ref>\n\n== Goals ==\n[[File:Jonathan Greenblatt by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Jonathan Greenblatt, National Director and CEO of the Anti-Defamation League since 2015]]\nThe stated purpose of the ADL is to fight: {{quote|anti-Semitism and all forms of bigotry (in the United States) and abroad, combat international terrorism, probe the roots of hatred, advocate before the United States Congress, come to the aid of victims of bigotry, develop educational programs, and serve as a public resource for government, media, law enforcement, and the public, all towards the goal of countering and reducing hatred.}} Historically, ADL has opposed groups and individuals it considered to be anti-Semitic and/or racist, including: [[Nazism|Nazis]], the [[Ku Klux Klan]], [[Henry Ford]], Father [[Charles Coughlin]] (leader of the [[Christian Front (United States)|Christian Front]]), the [[Christian Identity]] movement, the [[German-American Bund]], [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazis]], the [[Militia (United States)|American militia]] movement and [[white power skinhead]]s (although ADL acknowledges that there are also non-racist [[skinhead]]s).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/racist_skinheads/ |title=Racist Skinhead Project |publisher=ADL}}</ref><ref>Salberg, Melvin. [https://www.nytimes.com/1994/04/29/opinion/l-adl-acknowledges-nonracist-skinheads-932108.html Letter to the editor (\"A.D.L. Acknowledges Nonracist Skinheads\")]. ''The New York Times''. April 29, 1994.</ref> ADL publishes reports on a variety of countries, regarding alleged incidents of anti-Jewish attacks and propaganda.  Along with the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC), ADL's Center on Extremism (COE) is generally viewed as the most authoritative non-governmental experts on domestic extremists in the United States.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nADL maintains that some forms of [[anti-Zionism]] and [[criticism of Israel]] cross the line into anti-Semitism. The Anti-Defamation League states:\n{{quote|Criticism of particular Israeli actions or policies in and of itself does not constitute anti-Semitism. Certainly the sovereign State of Israel can be legitimately criticized just like any other country in the world. However, it is undeniable that there are those whose criticism of Israel or of \"Zionism\" is used to mask anti-Semitism.<ref>{{cite web|title=Response To Common Inaccuracy: Israel Critics are Anti-Semites|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-israel-critics-are-anti-semites|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 2010, ADL published a list of the \"ten leading organizations responsible for maligning Israel in the US\", which has included [[ANSWER]], the [[International Solidarity Movement]], and [[Jewish Voice for Peace]] for its call for [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS]].<ref>Benhorin, Yitzhak. \"[http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3969798,00.html Jewish group makes ADL blacklist].\" ynet news. October 15, 2010.</ref>  It has not published such a list since.   \n\n=== Fighting antisemitism ===\nIn the second decade of the 21st century ADL and Jews, as well as non-Jews, throughout the United States were generally shocked at the global resurgence of antisemitism,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-pope-antisemitism-idUSKBN1ZJ1LT|title=Pope condemns 'barbaric resurgence' of anti-Semitism|last=|first=|newspaper=Reuters|date=January 20, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> which was manifested in the rise of extremist activity both online and off.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/17/695593556/-antisemitism-here-and-now-author-discusses-resurgence-of-public-anti-semitism|title='Antisemitism: Here And Now' Author Discusses Resurgence Of Public Anti-Semitism|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/anti-semitic-assaults-u-s-more-doubled-2018-adl-reports-n1000246|title=Anti-Semitic assaults in the U.S. more than doubled in 2018, ADL reports|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>A foundational theme of white supremacists was antisemitism, which accompanied or underlay the anti-Muslim, xenophobic, racist, homophobic and other bigotry of these individuals and groups.<ref name=\":3\" /> Social media in particular, amplified hatred and provided what ADL officials characterized as a virtual \"24/7 neo-Nazi rally.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishwebsite.com/featured/adl-urges-congress-to-help-social-media-giants-address-anti-semitism/50933/|title=ADL urges Congress to help social media giants address anti-Semitism|last=|first=|date=January 16, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The number of hate crimes and extremist murders shook the ADL, leading it to reformulate its strategy to focus more resources on fighting antisemitism and extremism: the 2017 white supremacist rally in Charlottesville, Virginia, in which extremists chanted \"Jews will not replace us\" and which led to the murder of [[Charlottesville car attack|Heather Heyer]]; [[Dylann Roof|Dylan Roof]]'s 2015 massacre of African Americans at a prayer group in Charleston, South Carolina; the murder of 11 Jews at Sabbath services in the 2018 [[Pittsburgh synagogue shooting]]; the 2019 [[Poway synagogue shooting]] in California; the 2019 [[Christchurch mosque shooting]]<nowiki/>s in New Zealand; the 2019 Monsey, NY [[Monsey Hanukkah stabbing|Hanukkah stabbing;]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/30/opinion/monsey-new-york-attack.html|title=The Right Response to the Anti-Semitic Attack in Monsey, N.Y.|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 30, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020|last1=Lowey|first1=Nita|last2=Harris|first2=David}}</ref> the series of antisemitic hate crimes in Brooklyn, NY in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/12/27/jewish-mom-son-assaulted-in-latest-anti-semitic-attack-in-brooklyn/|title=Four Jewish women targeted in latest anti-Semitic attacks in Brooklyn|last=|first=|date=December 27, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL has financially supported litigation against the organizers of the Charlottesville rally<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-announces-support-for-ifas-lawsuit-against-neo-nazis-white-supremacists-and|title=ADL Announces Support for IFA's Lawsuit Against Neo-Nazis, White Supremacists, and Hate Groups Responsible for Charlottesville Violence|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> and has lobbied for an array of federal and state laws and policies designed to track, expose, and combat extremism, and has also developed and marketed education programs on the subject.<ref name=\":4\" />  ADL also works in close collaboration with Law Enforcement in response to hate crimes.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/anti-semitism/anti-semitism-in-the-us|title=Anti-Semitism in the US|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2020, after a year's work, ADL published ''Antisemitism Uncovered: A Guide to Old Myths in a New Era.''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://antisemitism.adl.org/?_ga=2.171810404.555282254.1584044588-1012598960.1553545971|title=Antisemitism Uncovered: A Guide to Old Myths in a New Era|last=Anti-Defamation League|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> The Guide is intended to be \"a comprehensive resource with historical context, fact-based descriptions of prevalent antisemitic myths, contemporary examples and calls-to-action for addressing this hate.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> It is organized around seven \"myths\" or antisemitic tropes, and is composed of modules.<ref name=\":1\" /> This Guide also represented ADL's shift from using the spelling \"anti-Semitism\" to \"antisemitism.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://antisemitism.adl.org/?_ga=2.171810404.555282254.1584044588-1012598960.1553545971|title=Antisemitism Uncovered: Notes from the CEO, Footnote 8|last=|first=|date=|website=ADL|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/culture/166092/should-anti-semitism-be-hyphenated/|title=Should anti-semitism be hyphenated|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Coronavirus pandemic of 2020 also saw the launch of Jew hatred and at least two types of conspiracy theory that were resuscitated and revised to encompass the virus crisis,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/listen-tablets-yair-rosenberg-talks-anti-semitism-during-coronavirus-crisis/|title=Listen: Tablet's Yair Rosenberg talks anti-Semitism during coronavirus crisis|last=Rosenberg|first=Yair|date=March 27, 2020|website=The Times of Israel|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> an analysis with which ADL agreed and also exposed. \"'There are people out there in the conspiracy theorist swamp who are talking about this being some kind of Mossad thing, or Israel-operative thing,' Rosenberg said. And there's the other type of theorist 'who just celebrates when Jews die from it, under the cover that anti-Zionism makes it okay to celebrate when random people die.' Many of these people, he said, tweeted horrific things after Israel's first victim, Holocaust survivor Aryeh Stern, passed away.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=@JGreenblattADL|title=Tweet re@yair_rosenberg on #antisemitism and #coronavirusMarch|last=|first=|date=March 27, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Tracking extremists ===\nDuring the 1930s, ADL, along with the American Jewish Committee, coordinated American Jewish groups across the country in monitoring the activities of the German-American Bund and its pro-Nazis, nativist allies in the United States. In many instances, these community-based defense organizations paid informants to infiltrate these groups and report on what they discovered. The longest-lived and most effective of these American Jewish resistance organizations was the Los Angeles Jewish Community Committee (LAJCC), which was backed financially by the Jewish leaders of the motion picture industry. The day-to-day operations of the LAJCC were supervised by a Jewish attorney, [[Leon L. Lewis]]. Lewis was uniquely qualified to combat the rise of Nazism in Los Angeles, having served as the first national secretary of the Anti-Defamation League in Chicago from 1925-1931. From 1934-1941, the LAJCC maintained its undercover surveillance of the German-American Bund, the Silver Shirts and dozens of other pro-Nazi, nativist groups that operated in Los Angeles. Partnering with the American Legion in Los Angeles, the LAJCC channeled eyewitness accounts of sedition onto federal authorities. Working with the ADL, Leon Lewis and the LAJCC played a strategic role in counseling the McCormack-Dickstein Committee investigation of Nazi propaganda activities in the United States (1934) and the Dies Committee investigation of \"un-American activities\" (1938-1940). In their final reports to Congress, both Committees found that the sudden rise in political antisemitism in the United States during the decade was due, in part, to the German government's support of these domestic groups.<ref>{{cite book|last=Rosenzweig|first=Laura|url=https://nyupress.org/books/9781479855179/|title=Hollywood's Spies: The Undercover Surveillance of Nazis in Los Angeles|date=2017|publisher=NYU Press|isbn=9781479855179|location=New York|page=|author-link=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Steven|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/us/hitler-in-los-angeles-9781620405642/|title=Hitler in Los Angeles: How Jews Foiled Nazi Plots Against Hollywood and America|date=2017|publisher=Bloomsbury|isbn=9781620405642|location=New York|page=|author-link=}}</ref>\n\nSince the 1970s, ADL has partnered with the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI) field offices, sharing information learned from monitoring of extremist groups.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=5SOAAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA167 \"Confronting Right Wing Extremism and Terrorism in the USA\"], George Michael. Routledge, Sep 2, 2003. p. 167. Retrieved 27 feb 2017</ref>\n\nADL keeps track of the activities of extremist groups and movements.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/sites/default/files/documents/assets/pdf/combating-hate/ADL_CR_Bigots_on_Bikes_online.pdf|title=Bigots on Bikes: The Growing Links between White Supremacists and Biker Gangs|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> According to ADL Director Abe Foxman: \"Our mission is to monitor and expose those who are anti-Jewish, racist, anti-democratic, and violence-prone, and we monitor them primarily by reading publications and attending public meetings \u2026. Because extremist organizations are highly secretive, sometimes ADL can learn of their activities only by using undercover sources \u2026 [who] function in a manner directly analogous to investigative journalists. Some have performed great service to the American people\u2014for example, by uncovering the existence of right-wing extremist paramilitary training camps\u2014with no recognition and at considerable personal risk.\"<ref>\"A League of His Own\", letter to the editor, ''The Village Voice'' 38:20 (May 18, 1993)</ref> A person apprehended in connection to the [[2002 white supremacist terror plot]] had drawn a cartoon of himself blowing up the Boston offices of ADL.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/16/national/16PLOT.html|title=Boston Couple Plotted Blasts to Incite Race War, Prosecutor Says|date=July 16, 2002|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nADL regularly releases reports on [[Anti-Semitism in the USA|US anti-Semitism]] and extremist activities on both the [[Far-left politics|far left]] and the [[Far-right politics|far right]]. As part of its Law Enforcement Agency Resource Network (L.E.A.R.N.), ADL has published information about the [[Militia Movement]]<ref name=\"militia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/militia-movement|title=The Militia Movement|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en}}</ref> in America and a guide for law enforcement officials titled ''Officer Safety and Extremists''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/sites/default/files/documents/assets/pdf/combating-hate/Officer-Safety-and-Extremists-An-Overview.pdf|title=Officer Safety and Extremists|publisher=ADL|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> An archive of \"[[Mark Pitcavage#Militia Watchdog|The Militia Watchdog]]\" research on U.S. right-wing extremism (including groups not specifically cited as anti-Semitic) from 1995 to 2000 is also available on ADL website.<ref name=\"militia\" />\n\nIn the 1990s, some details of ADL's monitoring activities became public knowledge; the ADL had gathered information about some non-extremist groups which became a contentious issue. In 2013, J.M. Berger, a former nonresident fellow of the [[Brookings Institution]], wrote that media organizations should be more cautious when citing the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC) and ADL, arguing that they are \"not objective purveyors of data\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berger|first1=J. M.|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2013/03/12/the-hate-list/|title=The Hate List|work=Foreign Policy}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, ADL announced that they would be developing profiles on 36 [[alt-right]] and [[alt-lite]] leaders.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/adl-releases-whos-who-guide-of-alt-right-and-alt-lite-extremists/|title=ADL releases 'Who's Who' guide of alt-right and alt-lite extremists|work=The Times of Israel|access-date=2017-07-19|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/from-alt-right-to-alt-lite-naming-the-hate|title=From Alt Right to Alt Lite: Naming the Hate|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2017-07-19}}</ref>  In 2019 and 2020 ADL executives and staff testified multiple times in front of Congressional committees concerning the dangers of domestic extremists,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/policy/defense-national-security/how-to-stop-it-congress-asks-what-the-military-is-doing-about-white-nationalism-in-the-ranks|title='How to stop it': Congress asks what the military is doing about white nationalism in its ranks|last=|first=|date=February 12, 2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> noting that the large majority of extremist murders in the United States over the past decade had been committed by white supremacists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/i-testified-at-a-congressional-hearing-on-white-nationalism-heres-some-of-what-i-wish-we-had|title=I Testified at a Congressional Hearing on White Nationalism. Here's Some of What I Wish We Had Discussed.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/adl-tells-congress-to-curb-online-hate-speech-if-social-media-giants-wont/|title=ADL tells Congress to curb online hate speech if social media giants won't|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> In early 2020, as the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Coronavirus pandemic]] raged, ADL's Center on Extremism<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-on-extremism|title=Who We Are: Center on Extremism|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> began tracking and publishing reports of upsurges in extremist hate and violence targeting Asian-Americans, Chinese, Jews and immigrants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/coronavirus-crisis-elevates-antisemitic-racist-tropes|title=Coronavirus Elevates Antisemitic Racist Tropes|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/03/20/yang-anti-defamation-league-ceo-avoid-coronavirus-scapegoating-racism-column/2877976001/|title=Yang & Anti-Defamation League CEO: Avoid coronavirus racism and scapegoating|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Separation of church and state   ===\nOne of ADL's major focuses is [[Freedom of religion#Judaism|religious freedom]] for people of all faiths.<ref name=\"RelFree\">{{cite web|title=Primer on the First Amendment & Religious Freedom|url=https://www.adl.org/education/resources/backgrounders/the-first-amendment-and-religious-freedom|website=Anti-Defamation League|accessdate=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Religious Freedom|url=https://www.adl.org/what-we-do/discrimination/religious-freedom|website=Anti-Defamation League|accessdate=11 May 2018|language=en}}</ref> In the context of public schools, ADL has taken the position that because [[creationism]] and [[intelligent design]] are religious beliefs, and the government is prohibited from endorsing the beliefs of any particular religion, they should not be taught in [[science]] classrooms: \"The U.S. Constitution guarantees the rights of Americans to believe the religious theories of creation (as well as other theories), but it does not permit them to be taught in public school science classes.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adl.org/issue_religious_freedom/create/creationism_QA.asp |title=Religion in the Science Class? Why Creationism and Intelligent Design Don't Belong |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 6, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020407123320/http://www.adl.org/issue_religious_freedom/create/creationism_QA.asp |archive-date=April 7, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Similarly, ADL supports the legal precedent that it is [[constitutionality|unconstitutional]] for the government to post the [[Ten Commandments]] in courthouses, schools, and other public places: \"True religious liberty means freedom from having the government impose the religion of the majority on all citizens.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://adl.org/10comm/Prohibitions.asp |title=The Ten Commandments Controversy: A First Amendment Perspective \u2013 Prohibitions on Display of the Ten Commandments |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 7, 2006 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20020920090047/http://www.adl.org/10comm/prohibitions.asp |archive-date=September 20, 2002 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> ADL has also condemned the public school [[Bible]] curriculum published by the [[National Council on Bible Curriculum in Public Schools]], saying that it raises \"serious constitutional problems\" and \"advocates the acceptance of one faith tradition's interpretation of the Bible over another\".<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Says Bible Teaching Guide for Public Schools 'Unacceptable' |publisher=ADL |date=November 7, 2005 |url=http://www.jewsonfirst.org/05a/public024.html |access-date=July 11, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071022212940/http://www.jewsonfirst.org/05a/public024.html |archive-date=October 22, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \n\nIn 2008 ADL opposed [[California Proposition 8 (2008)|Proposition 8]] in California; Prop 8 was a successful ballot proposition for a state constitutional amendment opposing same sex marriage that was subsequently overturned by the federal courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2008_California_Proposition_8|title=2008 California Proposition 8|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL submitted amicus briefs supporting same sex marriage in those cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://38.106.4.56/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentID=1228|title=BRIEF OF AMICI CURIAE ANTI-DEFAMATION LEAGUE ET AL. IN SUPPORT OF RESPONDENTS|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307154233/http://38.106.4.56/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentID=1228|archive-date=March 7, 2013|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> While basing its ongoing opposition to that and other anti-LGBTQ+ laws and campaigns primarily on equality and anti-discrimination legal rationales, ADL also consistently cites church/state separation arguments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/its-not-ok-for-businesses-to-discriminate-in-the-name-of-religion|title=It's Not OK for Businesses to Discriminate in the Name of Religion|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Thus, a frequent theme of ADL argument is that freedom of religion was meant to be a shield to protect religious freedom (particularly of minorities and vulnerable constituencies), and not a sword to attack the religious freedom of others.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Diaspora/ADL-slams-controversial-religious-freedom-laws-in-US-396007|title=ADL slams controversial 'religious freedom' laws in US|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nADL has also based its support for women's equality and reproductive choice on, among other legal arguments, the argument that the state should not adopt as law a particular religious belief,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/abortion-bans-undermine-equality-for-all|title=Abortion and Religious Freedom: The Right-Wing Assault on Religious Diversity in Reproductive Freedom|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> although the United States federal courts have not accepted this religious freedom and state/church separation line of argument.\n\n=== Holocaust awareness ===\nADL holds that it is important to remember [[the Holocaust]], in order to prevent such an event from reoccurring. Along with sponsoring events opposing [[Holocaust denial|Holocaust deniers]] and revisionists, ADL has been active in urging action to end modern-day [[ethnic cleansing]] and [[genocide]] in places such as [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnia]], [[Darfur]], and [[Sudan]].{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} ADL gives out its [[Courage to Care Award]] to honor rescuers of Jews during the Holocaust.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\nADL spoke out against an advertising campaign by [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]] (PETA) beginning in 2003 that equated meat-eating with the Holocaust. A press release from ADL stated that, \"PETA's effort to seek 'approval' for their 'Holocaust on Your Plate' campaign is outrageous, offensive and takes chutzpah to new heights. Rather than deepen our revulsion against what the Nazis did to the Jews, the project will undermine the struggle to understand the Holocaust and to find ways to make sure such catastrophes never happen again.\"<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Denounces Peta for its \"Holocaust On Your Plate\" Campaign; Calls Appeal for Jewish Community Support 'The Height Of Chutzpah' |publisher=ADL |date=February 24, 2003 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/HolNa_52/4235_52.htm}}</ref> In May 2005, PETA apologized for its campaign, with PETA President [[Ingrid Newkirk]] stating that causing pain \"was never our intention, and we are deeply sorry\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Rabbinate to phase out 'shackle and hoist' animal slaughter. More humane method to be adopted following claims of cruelty|work=The Jerusalem Post|date=February 19, 2008|last=Wagner|first=Matthew|quote=PETA has denied being motivated by anti-Semitism and even mentions on its Web site the humaneness of traditional Jewish slaughtering methods when done properly. However, PETA has a history of controversial campaigns. On May 5, 2005, PETA issued an apology for its 'Holocaust on Your Plate' exhibit, which traveled to more than 100 cities. The exhibit compared the treatment of farm animals to that of victims of the Nazi concentration camps. PETA President Ingrid Newkirk said she realized that the campaign had caused pain: 'This was never our intention, and we are deeply sorry.'}}</ref>\n\nADL's Education Department focuses on Holocaust and Genocide Education, primarily through its Echoes and Reflections Program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://echoesandreflections.org/|title=CONFIDENTLY TEACH ABOUT THE HOLOCAUST: Echoes & Reflections empowers middle and high school educators with dynamic classroom materials and professional development.|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=Mrach 29, 2020}}</ref> Echoes and Reflections is sponsored by ADL, [[Yad Vashem]], and the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum|United States Holocaust Museum]]. In 2019-20, ADL's national lobbying group and the regional offices refocused efforts on federal and state funding of Holocaust and genocide education, in part as a result of the upsurge of antisemitism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/blog/why-we-need-legislation-to-ensure-the-holocaust-is-taught-in-schools|title=Why We Need Legislation to Ensure the Holocaust is Taught in Schools|last=|first=|date=February 21, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Federal and State Hate Crimes Legislation ===\nADL was also one of the lead organizations campaigning for thirteen years, ultimately successfully, for the [[Matthew Shepard Act|Matthew Shepard and James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act.]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://law.duke.edu/news/michael-lieberman-81/|title=Michael Lieberman '81|last=|first=|date=|website=Duke Law News Releases|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/attorney-general-loretta-e-lynch-hosts-63rd-annual-attorney-general-awards-honoring|title=Attorney General Loretta E. Lynch Hosts the 63rd Annual Attorney General Awards Honoring Department Employees and Others For Their Service|last=|first=|date=October 21, 2015|website=|page=|type=U.S. Department of Justice News Release|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>  The hold-up in passing that law focused on the inclusion of the term \"sexual orientation\" as one of the bases that a crime could be deemed a hate crime.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/year-blaze-bernsteins-killing-parents-turn-alleged-hate/story?id=59754707|title=1 year after Blaze Bernstein's killing, parents look to turn alleged hate crime into 'movement of hope'|last=|first=|date=December 30, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref> ADL also drafted the model hate crimes legislation in the 1980's; it serves a model for the legislation that a majority of states have adopted.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/hate-crime-laws-dont-prevent-violence-against-lgbt-people/|title=Hate Crime Laws Don't Prevent Violence Against LGBT People: So why do many LGBT people, and others, feel so deeply about the need to have them?|journal=The Nation|date=October 2, 2013|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last1=Bronski|first1=Michael|last2=Pellegrini|first2=Ann|last3=Amico|first3=Michael}}</ref>\n\n=== Online content moderation ===\nAs part of its goal of opposing anti-Semitism, ADL has founded the \"Center for Technology and Society\" to target online harassment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-for-technology-and-society|title=Center for Technology and Society|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The goal of this center is to combat cyberbullying through research, education, and active intervention via industry and law-enforcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/who-we-are/our-organization/advocacy-centers/center-for-technology-and-society/about|title=About the Center for Technology and Society|website=Anti-Defamation League|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The ADL has participated in [[YouTube]]'s Trusted Flagger program, and has encouraged YouTube to remove videos which they flag as hate speech, citing the need to \"fight against terrorist use of online resources and cyberhate.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-applauds-google-and-youtube-in-expanding-initiative-to-fight-online-hate|title=ADL Applauds Google and YouTube in Expanding Initiative to Fight Online Hate|website=ADL.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2019/06/05/adl-praises-youtube-for-decision-to-remove-racist-extremist-content/|title=ADL Praises YouTube for Decision to Remove Racist, Extremist Content|website=Algemeiner}}</ref> CTS is also playing a lead role working with the online game industry to fight white supremacist activity on platforms connected with gaming.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/07/25/anti-defamation-league-65-of-gamers-have-experienced-severe-harassment-in-online-games/|title=Anti-Defamation League: 65% of gamers have suffered severe harassment online|last=|first=|date=July 26, 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/two-thirds-of-us-online-gamers-have-experienced-severe-harassment-new-adl-study|title=Two-Thirds of U.S. Online Gamers Have Experienced Severe Harassment, New ADL Study Finds|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\nADL supports [[Israel]] as a [[Jewish and democratic state]],<ref>[https://www.adl.org/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-israel-cant-be-jewish-democratic Response To Common Inaccuracy: Israel Can't be Jewish & Democratic], Anti-Defamation League.</ref> and supports a [[two-state solution]] to the [[Israeli-Palestinian conflict]], negotiated by the parties.<ref>[https://www.adl.org/education/resources/fact-sheets/response-to-common-inaccuracy-bi-national-one-state-solution Response To Common Inaccuracy: Bi-National/One-State Solution], Anti-Defamation League.</ref> The organization vociferously opposed the [[UN General Assembly Resolution 3379|1975 United Nations resolution]] ([[UN General Assembly Resolution 4686|revoked in 1991]]) which equated [[Zionism]] with racism,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/durban/adl_quotes.asp |title=U.N. World Conference Against Racism |publisher=ADL}}</ref> and attempts to revive that formulation at the 2001 U.N. [[World Conference Against Racism]] in [[Durban]], [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/durban/un_anti-zionism.asp |title=U.N. World Conference Against Racism |publisher=ADL}}</ref> ADL also has expressed concern over Israeli legislative proposals that would stifle freedom of expression and undermine Israeli democracy.<ref>[http://www.adl.org/press-center/press-releases/israel-middle-east/adl-concerned-that-proposed-legislation-on-ngo-funding.html ADL 'Concerned That Proposed Legislation on NGO Funding in Israel Would Erode Nation's Democratic Character,'] Anti-Defamation League January 11, 2016:'In 2011, the League urged the Israeli government to work to modify two similar bills regarding donations from foreign governments to Israeli NGOs, and voiced concern over laws that stifle free expression.'</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/reform-joins-adl-ajc-in-opposing-israels-ngo-bill/|title=Reform joins ADL, AJC in opposing Israel's NGO bill|publisher=}}</ref> \n\nWhile ADL was a lead supporter of Congressional legislation prohibiting US individuals and businesses from joining \"unsanctioned boycotts\" such as the 1970's [[Arab League boycott of Israel|Arab League Boycott]] against Israel,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/glossary-terms/arab-economic-boycott|title=Arab Economic Boycott|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> it has taken a different, case-by-case approach to state anti-boycott laws more recently enacted in response to the [[Boycott, Divestment and Sanctions|BDS movement]]. Several of these laws, which seek to prohibit State agencies and instrumentalities from investing in companies that boycott Israel and from entering into contracts with entities that boycott Israel, have been successfully challenged in the courts. The legal challenges have primarily been brought by the [[American Civil Liberties Union|ACLU]] and [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations|CAIR]] on First Amendment constitutional grounds.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/26/us/texas-bds-law/index.html|title=Texas has a law that says contractors can't boycott Israel. But a federal judge just blocked it|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/blog/free-speech/arizona-lawmakers-running-scared-after-anti-boycott-law-ruled-unconstitutional|title=Arizona Lawmakers Running Scared After Anti-Boycott Law Ruled Unconstitutional|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>ADL generally has not publicly supported laws it felt were constitutionally suspect under the First Amendment, both for legal reasons and because the organization believed that such laws, even if what ADL describes as \"well-intentioned,\" were not an effective means of combating the BDS movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-urges-texas-city-to-remove-no-israel-boycott-requirement-from-aid|title=ADL Urges Texas City to Remove 'No Israel Boycott' Requirement from Aid Application|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> However, as a general matter the organization also has not publicly opposed such state laws, preferring to work behind the scenes to try to make such laws less infirm under the Constitution or to propose non-binding resolutions opposing BDS. A possible division of internal views in ADL was disclosed when the liberal Jewish news media organization, [[The Forward]], published ostensibly leaked internal ADL staff memos dating from 2016 that opposed the anti-boycott laws.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/news/416030/revealed-secret-adl-memo-slammed-anti-bds-laws-as-harmful-to-jews/|title=REVEALED: Secret ADL Memo Slammed Anti-BDS Laws As 'Harmful' To Jews|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL did not comment directly on the leaked memos, but the statement it issued in response appeared to acknowledge that there had been, if were not still, sharply divided views within the organization and that it did not try to suppress internal robust discussion.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nADL has publicly stated that it believes that certain founders and leaders of the BDS movement are antisemitic, but has noted that many supporters of BDS, both Jewish and non-Jewish, are not antisemitic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/resources/backgrounders/bds-the-global-campaign-to-delegitimize-israel|title=BDS: The Global Campaign to Delegitimize Israel|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> \n\nADL has condemned the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]]'s (UNHRC)  list of companies doing business with Jewish settlements in Israeli-run territories (West Bank, East Jerusalem, Golan Heights), issued in February 2020, calling it a \"blacklist.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.com/news/world/310631/unhrc-releases-blacklist-of-companies-conducting-business-in-israeli-settlements/|title=UNHRC Releases 'Blacklist' of Companies Conducting Business in Israeli Settlements|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-strongly-condemns-un-councils-blacklist-of-israeli-companies|title=ADL Strongly Condemns U.N. Council's Blacklist of Israeli Companies|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, ADL condemned Senate Republicans in the United States for attempting to ban [[same-sex marriage]] with the [[Federal Marriage Amendment]], and called the proposal discriminatory.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Welcomes Demise Of Same-Sex Marriage Amendment; Expresses 'Dismay' At Senate Vote |publisher=ADL |date=June 7, 2006 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/DiRaB_41/4832_41.htm}}</ref> That same year, the ADL warned that the debate over [[illegal immigration]] was drawing [[neo-nazis]] and [[anti-Semites]] into the ranks of the [[The Minuteman Project Inc.|Minutemen Project]].\n\nIn 2010, during a hearing for Florida House Bill 11 (Crimes Against Homeless Persons), which was to revise the list of offenses judged to be [[Hate crime laws in the United States|hate crimes]] in Florida by adding a person's homeless status,<ref>{{cite web\n| title = flhouse.gov HB 11 \u2013 Crimes Against Homeless Persons\n| url = http://flhouse.gov/Sections/Bills/billsdetail.aspx?BillId=42143&\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}}</ref> the League lobbied against the bill, which subsequently passed in the House by a vote of 80 to 28 and was sent to the Senate,<ref>{{cite web\n| title = flhouse.gov HB 11 Apr 20 2010 \u2013 Voting record Florida House of Representatives\n| url = http://flhouse.gov/Sections/Bills/floorvote.aspx?VoteId=10836&BillId=42143&\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}}</ref> taking the position that adding more categories to the list would dilute the effectiveness of the law, which already includes race, religion, sexual orientation, disability, and age.<ref>{{cite web\n| title = Homeless could be added to Florida's hate crimes law\n| url = http://www.miamiherald.com/2010/04/21/1589541/homeless-could-be-added-to-floridas.html\n| accessdate = April 22, 2010\n}} ''Miami Herald'', Miami Herald Media Co., April 21, 2010, by Lee Logan, Tallahassee Bureau: \"During a committee hearing on the bill, the Anti-Defamation League spoke against the bill, arguing that adding more categories to the hate crimes law would dilute its effect. But lawmakers were swayed by arguments in favor of protecting the homeless.\"</ref>\n\nWhen the [[anti-Mormon]] film ''[[The God Makers]]'' (1982) was produced, Rhonda M. Abrams, Central Pacific (San Francisco) Regional Director for ADL, wrote a critical review, including the following statement:\n\n{{quote|Had a similar movie been made with either Judaism or Catholicism as its target, it would be immediately denounced for the scurrilous piece that it is. I sincerely hope that people of all faiths will similarly repudiate ''The Godmakers'' as defamatory and untrue, and recognize it for what it truly represents - a challenge to the religious liberty of all.<ref>[http://www.fairmormon.org/perspectives/publications/the-truth-about-the-god-makers/ia Letter to Dr. Richard Lindsay], Director of Public Communications, The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, May 25, 1984</ref>}}\n\nADL supports [[Comprehensive Immigration Reform Act of 2007|Comprehensive]] and [[DREAM Act]] legislation that would provide conditional permanent residency to certain illegal aliens of good moral character who graduate from U.S. high schools, arrived in the United States as minors, and lived in the country continuously for at least five years prior to the bill's enactment.<ref>{{cite news|title=Afirman que con el debate de reforma migratoria subieron los cr\u00edmenes de odio|publisher=EFE News Services|date=January 25, 2013|quote= La Liga Antidifamaci\u00f3n Jud\u00eda ( ADL ) asegur\u00f3 hoy que desde que se inici\u00f3 el debate sobre una reforma migratoria integral en Estados Unidos se ha registrado un aumento de los cr\u00edmenes de odio contra los hispanos. ... Por su parte, el director del Departamento de Asuntos Legales de ADL, Steven Freeman, dijo a Efe que esta organizaci\u00f3n aboga por una reforma migratoria integral y el Dream Act}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, ADL condemned remarks by [[Ovadia Yosef]] that the sole purpose of non-Jews was to serve the Jews.<ref>Mozgovaya, Natasha. \"[http://www.haaretz.com/jewish-world/adl-slams-shas-spiritual-leader-for-saying-non-jews-were-born-to-serve-jews-1.320235?localLinksEnabled=false ADL slams Shas spiritual leader for saying non-Jews 'were born to serve Jews'].\" Haaretz Service. October 20, 2010.</ref>\n\nADL has spoken out against [[McCarthyism]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Norwood|first1=Stephen Harlan|last2=Pollack|first2=Eunice G.|title=Encyclopedia of American Jewish History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IB3mBsgfIHQC&pg=PA245|year=2008|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-638-1|page=245}}</ref>\n\nADL has supported some moves of the Trump Administration, and criticized others. For example, the organization welcomed President Trump moving the U.S. Embassy to Jerusalem, thereby underscoring that Jerusalem was the capitol of Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-welcomes-president-trumps-announcement-on-jerusalem-calls-for-focus-on|title=ADL Welcomes President Trump's Announcement on Jerusalem; Calls for Focus on Peace Negotiations and Reducing Tensions|last=|first=|date=December 6, 2017|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL CEO and National Director Jonathan Greenblatt traveled to Israel to join Trump administration officials at the official opening ceremony of the embassy in Jerusalem.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-celebrates-historic-milestone-as-us-embassy-opens-in-jerusalem|title=ADL Celebrates 'Historic Milestone' as U.S. Embassy Opens in Jerusalem|last=|first=|date=May 14, 2018|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> ADL has also called for key Trump Administration executive Stephen Miller, the architect of the Trump administration policies on immigration, to be fired and condemned him as a white supremacist.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Relations with religious and ethnic groups ==\n\n=== Relations with Arabs and Muslims ===\n{{See also|Projects working for peace among Israelis and Arabs}}\n\nIn 2012, ADL released a statement opposing groups like the [[Stop Islamization of America]] and [[Stop Islamization of Europe]], and activists such as [[Pamela Geller]] and [[David Yerushalmi]], describing them as \"anti-Muslim bigots\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/article/stop-islamization-of-america-sioa|title=Stop Islamization of America (SIOA)|website=Anti-Defamation League}}</ref>\n\nSince U.S. Reprentatives [[Rashida Tlaib]] (D-MI) and [[Ilhan Omar]] (D-MN) were elected to the U.S. House of Representatives in late 2018, becoming in 2019 the first two Muslim women to serve in the U.S. Congress,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5445303/ilhan-omar-rashida-tlaib-midterm/|title=Ilhan Omar and Rashida Tlaib Just Became the First Muslim Women Elected to Congress|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> ADL at times has defended them from racist and [[Islamophobia|Islamaphobic]] attacks,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JGreenblattADL/status/1102207176746156035|title=Tweet from ADL CEO Jonathan Greenblatt|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> as well as from what ADL has viewed as partisan efforts to weaponize accusations of antisemitism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitchy.com/brettt-3136/2019/05/13/adl-ceo-says-its-unacceptable-for-elected-officials-to-weaponize-rashida-tlaibs-comments/|title=ADL CEO says it's unacceptable for elected officials to 'weaponize' Rashida Tlaib's comments|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Indeed, Rep. Omar's \"inspiring\" story, as the first Somali-American lawmaker, was included in a book commissioned by ADL. ''The Good Fight,'' published before Rep. Omar's election to Congress, tells the stories of Americans who have fought for equality''.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ADL/status/943186695666708481|title=ADL Tweet, December 19, 2017|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thegoodfightbook.org/|title=Publishers' blurbs for \"The Good Fight\"|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Since their election to Congress, however, ADL also has repeatedly and harshly criticized Reps. Omar and Tlaib<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-statement-concerning-rep-rashida-tlaibs-tweet-on-pending-bds-bill-in|title=ADL Statement Concerning Rep. Rashida Tlaib's Tweet on Pending BDS Bill in Congress|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-calls-on-house-leadership-to-take-action-after-rep-omars-anti-semitic|title=ADL Calls on House Leadership to Take Action After Rep. Omar's Anti-Semitic Tweets|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://freebeacon.com/politics/adl-rejects-omars-good-faith-defense-asks-pelosi-to-condemn-anti-semitic-rhetoric/|title=ADL Rejects Omar's 'Good Faith' Defense, Asks Pelosi to Condemn Anti-Semitic Rhetoric|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> for what it deemed to be antisemitic remarks and the spreading of dangerous antisemitic tropes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2020/jan/28/rashida-tlaib-responds-after-adl-accuses-her-of-sp/|title=Rep. Rashida Tlaib responds after ADL accuses her of spreading anti-Semitic 'blood libel'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>  \n\n=== Relations with African-Americans ===\nIn 1997, the National Center for Black-Jewish Relations of [[Dillard University]], a [[historically black college|historically black university]] in [[New Orleans]], awarded the director of ADL, Abraham H. Foxman, with its first Annual [[Martin Luther King, Jr]].\u2013Donald R. Mintz Freedom and Justice Award.\n\nIn 2004, ADL became the lead partner in the Peace and Diversity Academy, a new New York City public high school with predominantly black and Hispanic students. In celebration of [[Black History Month]], the ADL created and distributed lesson plans to middle and high school teachers about [[Shirley Chisholm]] (1924\u20132005), the first black woman elected to the [[US Congress]], and an important civil rights leader.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nADL has also publicly accused a number of prominent African Americans of being anti-Semitic:\n\n* ADL has catalogued a more than three-decade history of [[Nation of Islam]] leader [[Louis Farrakhan]]'s espousal of anti-Semitic rhetoric such as claims that certain Jews are \"not real Jews\" and that they are \"wicked deceivers of the American people\" who \"sucked [Americans'] blood\", and that powerful Jews promote homosexuality and control black leadership.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/special_reports/farrakhan_own_words2/farrakhan_own_words.asp |title=Farrakhan In His Own Words |publisher=ADL}}</ref> Farrakhan first attracted the attention of the ADL with comments in a March 11, 1984, radio broadcast saying that, \"[[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] was a very great man\".<ref name=\"finalcall\">{{cite journal |title=Farrakhan and the Jewish Rift; How It All Started |journal=[[The Final Call]] |url=http://www.finalcall.com/perspectives/rift.html}}</ref> Farrakhan insists that he was using the word 'great' in the sense of 'Great Depression' or 'great white shark'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.noi.org/judaism-religion/|title=Minister Farrakhan rebuts fraudulent \"Judaism is a Gutter Religion\" canard|date=August 5, 2010|publisher=}}</ref> and on June 24, 1984, he described the Jewish state as \"structured on injustice, thievery, lying and deceit and using the name of God to shield your dirty religion under His holy and righteous name.\"<ref name=\"finalcall\" /> ADL has urged various groups including the [[National Association for the Advancement of Colored People|NAACP]] (whose leader [[Benjamin Chavis]] developed a working relationship with Farrakhan in 1994) to dissociate themselves from Farrakhan and his views.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Foxman |first=Abraham H. |authorlink=Abraham Foxman |date=July 20, 1994 |title=Today's N.A.A.C.P. Draws on History; Set Farrakhan Aside |journal=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9503E7DE143EF933A15754C0A962958260}}</ref>\n* In 1984 ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' reported that then-ADL national director Nathan Perlmutter said that Rev. [[Jesse Jackson]], Sr. was anti-Semitic, after Jackson referred to New York City as \"Hymietown\".<ref>{{cite journal |date=February 23, 1984 |title=Post Reaffirms Report On Jackson Comment |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=13 |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0E10FB3B5D0C708EDDAB0894DC484D81}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |date=February 27, 1984 |title=Jackson Admits Saying 'Hymie' And Apologizes At A Synagogue |journal=[[The New York Times]] |page=16 |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30A14F83C5D0C748EDDAB0894DC484D81}}</ref> However, ADL later reconciled with Jackson and has worked with him on the issue of the Iranian Jewish community.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Rev. Jesse Jackson Meets with Iranian Jewish Families Pledges to Intercede on Behalf of Imprisoned Jews |publisher=ADL |date=June 11, 1999 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASInt_13/3401_13.asp}}</ref>\n* Film Director [[Spike Lee]] was criticized by the Anti-Defamation League for his portrayal of Jewish nightclub owners Moe and Josh Flatbush in his film ''[[Mo' Better Blues]]'' (1990). The Anti-Defamation League said that the characterizations of the nightclub owners \"dredge up an age-old and highly dangerous form of anti-Semitic stereotyping\", and it was \"disappointed that Spike Lee \u2013 whose success is largely due to his efforts to break down racial stereotypes and prejudice \u2013 has employed the same kind of tactics that he supposedly deplores\".<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 16, 1990 |title=Spike Lee's Jews and the Passage From Benign Cliche Into Bigotry|journal=[[The New York Times]] |author=Caryn James|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/08/16/movies/critic-s-notebook-spike-lee-s-jews-passage-benign-cliche-into-bigotry.html}}</ref> Lee's portrayal also angered the B'nai B'rith and other such Jewish organizations, causing Lee to apologize via an Opinion-Editorial article in ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |date=August 13, 2006 |title=The Angriest Auteur|journal=[[New York Magazine]] |author=Ariel Levy|url=http://nymag.com/movies/profiles/19144/}}</ref>\n* During the 2002 election cycle, ADL, in a letter to ''The New York Times'', harshly criticized [[Congressional Black Caucus]] member [[Cynthia McKinney]] of Georgia for launching attacks perceived as racial against her Jewish opponent. According to an August 19, 2002, article in ''The New York Times'', ADL Director Abraham Foxman said, \"It made sense that Jewish Americans would want to contribute to efforts to replace Ms. McKinney\".\n* In February 2005, ADL National Director Abraham Foxman called it hypocritical for hip-hop producer [[Russell Simmons]] to lead an ad campaign against anti-Semitism while, in Foxman's view, also defending or excusing Louis Farrakhan's anti-Semitic statements.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Calls on Russell Simmons to Distance Himself from Minister Farrakhan |publisher=ADL |date=February 14, 2005 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASUS_12/4645_12.htm}}</ref> Later that year ADL urged prominent black leaders including Simmons to reconsider their support for Farrakhan and [[Malik Zulu Shabazz]] organizing the [[Millions More Movement]] and to \"stand up\" against black anti-Semitism.<ref>{{cite press release |title=ADL Urges Prominent African-American Leaders to Reconsider Their Support for the \"Millions More Movement\" |publisher=ADL |date=May 2, 2005 |url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/ASUS_12/4707_12.htm}}</ref> Simmons, responding to ADL Director Abraham Foxman, said, \"simply put, you are misguided, arrogant, and very disrespectful of African Americans, and most importantly, your statements will unintentionally or intentionally lead to a negative impression of Jews in the minds of millions of African Americans\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.millionsmoremovement.com/news/russell-simmons05-09-2005.htm |title=Russell Simmons Responds to Abraham Foxman about the Millions More Movement |last=Simmons |first=Russell |authorlink=Russell Simmons |date=May 9, 2005 |publisher=[[Millions More Movement]]}}</ref> Foxman replied, \"If there were a Jewish event which was led by an out-and-out racist, I would expect Black leaders to say to me that ADL should have nothing to do with it. And I would agree with them, rather than condemn them for their action.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/media_watch/internet/20050510-Russell+Simmons.htm |title=Response to Russell Simmons |date=May 9, 2005 |publisher=ADL |access-date=March 16, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070607153052/http://www.adl.org/media_watch/internet/20050510-Russell+Simmons.htm |archive-date=June 7, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Interfaith camp ===\nADL's New England Regional Office has also established a faith-based initiative called \"The Interfaith Youth Leadership Program\", better known as \"Camp If\", or Camp Interfaith. Involving teenagers of the Christian, Jewish, and Islamic faiths, the camp brings the teens together for a week at camp where the teens bond and learn about each other's cultures. The camp has emerged as a new attempt to foster good relations between younger members of the Abrahamic faiths.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Siek |first=Stephanie V. |date=April 6, 2006 |title=A different kind of camp |journal=[[The Boston Globe]] |url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2006/04/06/a_different_kind_of_camp/}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n{{POV section|date=December 2018}}\n\n===Arab American and African American lawsuit against ADL===\nIn 1996, ADL settled a federal civil lawsuit filed by groups representing [[African Americans]] and [[Arab Americans]] that alleged that the ADL hired agents with police ties to gather information. ADL did not admit any wrongdoing, but agreed to a restraining injunction barring ADL from obtaining information from state employees who are forbidden by law to divulge such information. ADL also agreed to contribute $25,000 to a fund that funds inter-community relationship projects, and cover the plaintiffs' legal costs of $175,000.<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1996-09-04/news/mn-40507_1_anti-defamation-league Anti-Defamation League Settles Lawsuit by Civil Rights Groups], LA Times, 4 September 1996</ref><ref>[https://www.jta.org/1996/09/06/archive/adl-to-pay-200000-to-settle-suit-alleging-spying-activities ADL to Pay $200,000 to Settle Suit Alleging Spying Activities], JTA, 6 September 1996</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QM1hloeMQqgC&pg=PA96&lpg=PA96&dq=%22Anti-Defamation+League%22+settlement+1996&source=bl&ots=d1L3G8qgX8&sig=Auo9IfPqSIcVRuL2g7zlDpFJTF4&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjO5Y7Pr7XfAhWQDuwKHeNbB1MQ6AEwC3oECAIQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Anti-Defamation%20League%22%20settlement%201996&f=false American Jewish Year, Book 1998], page 96</ref>\n\n=== Armenian Genocide controversy ===\n{{Undue weight section|date=February 2019}}\nIn 2007, Abraham Foxman came under criticism for his stance on the [[Armenian Genocide]]. ADL had previously described it as a \"massacre\" and an \"atrocity,\" but not as a \"genocide.\"<ref name=\"http\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/Mise_00/5114_00.htm\n|title=ADL Statement on the Armenian Genocide\n|date=August 21, 2007}}</ref> Foxman had earlier opposed calls for the U.S. Government to recognise it as a \"genocide.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewcy.com/feature/2007-07-09/fire_foxman |title=Fire Foxman: Denying the Armenian Genocide should be the last atrocity perpetrated by the ADL chief.}}</ref> \"I don't think congressional action will help reconcile the issue. The resolution takes a position; it comes to a judgement,\" said Foxman in a statement issued to the [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]. \"The [[Turkey|Turks]] and [[Armenia]]ns need to revisit their past. The Jewish community shouldn't be the arbiter of that history, nor should the U.S. Congress, and \"a Congressional resolution on such matters is a counterproductive diversion and will not foster reconciliation between Turks and Armenians, and may put at risk the Turkish Jewish community and the important multilateral relationship between Turkey, Israel, and the United States.\"\n\nIn early August 2007, complaints about the Anti-Defamation League's refusal to acknowledge the [[Armenian Genocide]] led to [[Watertown, Massachusetts]]'s, unanimous town council decision to end its participation in ADL's \"No Place for Hate\" campaign. (Watertown is known for its Armenian population.) Also in August 2007, an editorial in ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' criticized ADL by saying that, \"as an organization concerned about human rights, it ought to acknowledge the [[genocide]] against the Armenian people during [[World War I]], and criticize Turkish attempts to repress the memory of this historical reality.\"<ref>{{cite news |date= August 3, 2007 |url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/editorial_opinion/editorials/articles/2007/08/03/a_genocide_not_to_be_denied/ |title=A genocide not to be denied |work=[[Boston Globe]]}}</ref> Then on August 17, 2007, ADL fired its regional [[New England]] director, Andrew H. Tarsy, for breaking ranks with the main organization and for saying that ADL should recognize the genocide.<ref name=obrien>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/18/adl_local_leader_fired_on_armenian_issue/\n|title=ADL local leader fired on Armenian issue: Genocide question sparked bitter debate\n|work=The Boston Globe\n|first=Keith\n|last=O'Brien\n|date=August 18, 2007}}</ref> In an August 21, 2007, news release, ADL changed its position and acknowledged the genocide, but maintained its opposition to congressional resolutions aimed at recognizing it.<ref name=\"http\" /> Foxman wrote, \"the consequences of those actions,\" by the [[Ottoman Empire]] against Armenians, \"were indeed tantamount to genocide.\"<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/22/adl_chief_bows_to_critics/\n|title=ADL chief bows to critics: Foxman cites rift, calls Armenian deaths genocide\n|first=Keith\n|last=O'Brien\n|date=August 22, 2007\n|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> The [[Turkish government]] condemned the league's statement.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/08/24/turkey_condemns_statement_by_adl/\n|title=Turkey condemns statement by ADL\n|first=Michael\n|last=Levenson\n|date=August 24, 2007\n|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> Andrew H. Tarsy was rehired by the league on August 27,<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/globe/city_region/breaking_news/2007/08/antidefamation_1.html\n|title=Anti-Defamation League rehires New England director\n|first=Keith\n|last=O'Brien\n|work=The Boston Globe\n|date=September 7, 2007}}</ref> though he has since chosen to step down from his position.<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/news/?content_id=4108\n |title        = Tarsy Resignation Draws Mixed Emotions From Area Colleagues\n |first        = Rachel\n |last         = Axelbank\n |publisher    = Jewish Advocate\n |date         = December 6, 2007\n |access-date  = January 7, 2008\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071210223450/http://www.thejewishadvocate.com/this_weeks_issue/news/?content_id=4108\n |archive-date = December 10, 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = mdy-all\n}}</ref>\n\nThe 2007 ADL \"Statement on the Armenian Genocide,\" was criticized by activists as failing to be a full, unequivocal acknowledgment of the [[Armenian genocide]], because the use of the qualifier \"tantamount\" was seen as inappropriate, and the use of the word \"consequences\" was seen as an attempt to circumvent the international legal definition of genocide by avoiding any language that would imply intent, a crucial aspect of the 1948 UN [[Genocide Convention]] definition. \n\nAfter Foxman's capitulation, the New England ADL pressed the organization's national leadership to support a congressional resolution acknowledging the genocide.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\" /> AT ADL's annual national meeting in early November 2007, the issue of the Armenian Genocide was discussed. After hours of closed-door debate at the annual national meeting in New York, the proposal was withdrawn.<ref name=\"Woolhouse\" /> The organization ultimately issued a one-sentence statement, saying \"The National Commission of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) today, at its annual meeting, decided to take no further action on the issue of the Armenian genocide.\"<ref>http://www.adl.org/PresRele/Mise_00/5162_00.htm</ref>\n\nThe ADL was criticized by many in the Armenian community, including ''The Armenian Weekly'' newspaper, in which writer Michael Mensoian stated:\n\n{{quote|The belated backtracking of the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) in acknowledging the planned, systematic massacre of 1,500,000 Armenian men, women and children as \"\u2026tantamount to genocide\u2026\" is discouraging. Tantamount means something is equivalent. If it's equivalent, why avoid using the term? For the ADL to justify its newly adopted statement because the word genocide did not exist at the time indicates a halfhearted attempt to placate Armenians while not offending Turkey. Historians use the term genocide simply because it is the proper term to describe the horrific events that the Ottoman Turkish government unleashed on the Armenian people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://armenianweekly.com/|title=Home|website=The Armenian Weekly}}</ref>}}\n\nADL had earlier received direct pressure from the Turkish Foreign ministry.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.co.il/hasite/spages/911393.html \u05d8\u05d5\u05e8\u05e7\u05d9\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d9\u05e9\u05e8\u05d0\u05dc: \u05e2\u05d6\u05e8\u05d5 \u05dc\u05e0\u05d5 \u05dc\u05e2\u05e6\u05d5\u05e8 \u05d4\u05db\u05e8\u05d4 \u05d0\u05de\u05e8\u05d9\u05e7\u05d0\u05d9\u05ea \u05d1\u05e9\u05d5\u05d0\u05d4 \u05d4\u05d0\u05e8\u05de\u05e0\u05d9\u05ea] Haaretz, 10/10/07, Barak Ravid</ref> Tarsy submitted his resignation on December 4.<ref name=Woolhouse>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/12/05/adls_regional_leader_resigns/\n|title=ADL's regional leader resigns: Backers cite rift on genocide issue\n|first=Megan\n|last=Woolhouse\n|work=The Boston Globe\n|date=December 5, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn the subsequent months, some [[human rights]] commissions in other Massachusetts communities decided to follow Watertown's lead and withdraw from the ADL's No Place for Hate anti-discrimination program.<ref name=Woolhouse /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://medford.wickedlocal.com/x96464381|title=City recognizes Armenian genocide, suspends ADL membership|last=Esker/medford@cnc.com|first=Sharon Tosto|work=Medford Transcript|access-date=2018-05-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2016, [[Jonathan Greenblatt]], then ADL's CEO and National Director for less than a year, published a blog post in which he wrote \"What happened to the Armenian people was unequivocally genocide\" and urged the U.S. to take a position recognizing the Armenian genocide.<ref>[[Jonathan Greenblatt|Greenblatt, Jonathan]] (May 13, 2016) [https://www.adl.org/blog/adl-on-the-armenian-genocide \"ADL on the Armenian Genocide\"] Anti-Defamation League website</ref>  In late 2019, ADL publicly endorsed and lobbied for a historic Congressional resolution commemorating the Armenian genocide, which passed the House of Representatives with bipartisan support.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/news/press-releases/adl-endorses-congressional-resolution-commemorating-the-armenian-genocide|title=ADL Endorses Congressional Resolution Commemorating the Armenian Genocide|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/29/us/politics/armenian-genocide-resolution.html|title=House Passes Resolution Recognizing Armenian Genocide|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/12/us/politics/senate-armenian-genocide.html|title=Senate Passes Resolution Recognizing Armenian Genocide, in Defiance of Trump|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>  The U.S. Senate passed a similar resolution, which was also backed by ADL, but in December 2019 the Trump Administration, under pressure from Turkey's President Recep Tayyip Erdogan, refused to back recognition of the Armenian genocide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-armenian-genocide-erdogan-turkey-native-americans-a9250281.html|title=Trump refuses to back recognition of Armenian genocide after Erdogan threat|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Role in cancellation of speech by Tony Judt at Polish Consulate ===\nIn 2006, ADL, in addition to the [[American Jewish Committee]], was criticized by academic [[Tony Judt]] for allegedly pressuring the [[Poland|Polish]] [[List of diplomatic missions of Poland#North America|Consulate-General]] in New York to cancel a scheduled appearance by Judt at Network 20/20, a non-profit organization that rents space from the consulate. In an interview with the ''[[New York Sun]]'', Foxman claimed that the group \"had nothing to do with the cancellation,\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Stoll |first=Ira |authorlink=Ira Stoll |date=October 4, 2006 |title=Poland Abruptly Cancels a Speech By Local Critic of the Jewish State |journal=[[The New York Sun]] |url=http://www.nysun.com/article/40911?page_no=1}}</ref> insisting that ADL only called to ask if the event was being sponsored by the Polish government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/media_watch/newspapers/20061116-Chronicle+of+Higher+Ed.htm |title=Article on Free Speech and Israel Gets it Wrong |last=Foxman |first=Abraham H. |authorlink=Abraham Foxman |date=November 16, 2006 |publisher=ADL |access-date=December 18, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070213233147/http://www.adl.org/media_watch/newspapers/20061116-Chronicle+of+Higher+Ed.htm |archive-date=February 13, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Polish Consul General Krzysztof Kasprzyk suggested in an interview with ''[[The Washington Post]]'' that calls by the ADL and the American Jewish Committee were \"exercising a delicate pressure.\"<ref name=\"WP sparks\">{{cite journal |last=Powell |first=Michael |date=October 9, 2006 |title=In N.Y., Sparks Fly Over Israel Criticism |journal=[[The Washington Post]] |pages=A03 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/08/AR2006100800817.html}}</ref> In reference to the role of ADL and the American Jewish Committee in organizing the cancellations, Judt told ''The Washington Post'': \"This is serious and frightening, and only in America\u2014not in Israel\u2014is this a problem. These are Jewish organizations that believe they should keep people who disagree with them on the Middle East away from anyone who might listen.\"<ref name=\"WP sparks\" /> ADL denied the charges. According to Foxman, \"I think they made the right decision... He's taken the position that Israel shouldn't exist. That puts him on our radar.\"<ref name=\"WP sparks\" />\n\n=== Denver defamation suit ===\nIn 1994, ADL became embroiled in a dispute between neighbors in Denver, Colorado. Upon the involvement of ADL, the petty quarreling of next door neighbors, initially about garden plants and pets, quickly escalated into both civil and criminal court cases involving charges of anti-Semitism, and counter charges of defamation.\n\nCandace and Mitchell Aronson, Jewish next door neighbors of William and Dorothy Quigley, used a [[Radio Shack]] police scanner to listen in on the cordless telephone conversations of Mr. and Mrs. Quigley. When the Aronsons heard the Quigleys discuss a campaign to drive them from the neighborhood with \"Nazi scare tactics,\" the Aronsons contacted the Denver office of ADL. Upon the advice of ADL, the Aronsons then recorded the Quigley's private telephone conversations. The conversations included discussions of putting pictures of oven doors on the Aronsons' home (a reference to the Holocaust), burning one of the Aronson children, and wishing that the Aronsons had been killed in a suicide bombing. (The Quigleys later indicated that these remarks were not anti-Semitic, and were only intended to be sick humor.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishsf.com/content/2-0-/module/displaystory/story_id/13674/edition_id/264/format/html/displaystory.html|title=Jewish News Weekly|publisher=}}</ref> Neither the Aronsons nor ADL were aware that Congress had amended federal wiretap law which made it illegal to record conversations from a cordless telephone, to transcribe the material, and to use the transcriptions for any purpose.\n\nNot knowing about the new federal law, the Aronsons used the tapes as the basis for a federal civil lawsuit against the Quigleys in December 1994. A day later, Saul Rosenthal, Regional Director of ADL, appeared at a news conference with the Aronsons in which he described their encounter with the Quigleys as \"a vicious anti-Semitic campaign,\" based solely on conversations he and associates had with the Aronsons. Later that day, Mr. Rosenthal expanded on his remarks in an interview on a Denver radio talk show.\n\nTwo days later, Jefferson County prosecutors used the tapes as the basis for filing criminal charges against the Quigleys.\n\nThe Quigleys became the target of scorn and ridicule. They received threats, and were forced to hire security guards for their home. A package of dog feces was mailed to their house. When they attended church, their priest openly chastised them in his sermon. The family was forced to shop in other towns, to avoid being recognized.<ref>{{cite web|title=Quigley v. Rosenthall|url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-10th-circuit/1360107.html|website=Findlaw|publisher=Findlaw|accessdate=June 23, 2015}}</ref> Mr. Quigley's career with [[United Artists]] suffered serious damage.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lane|first1=George|title=Charges of bigotry backfire|url=http://extras.denverpost.com/news/news0429.htm|accessdate=June 23, 2015|issue=April 29, 2000|newspaper=Denver Post}}</ref>\n\nUpon investigation, and after assistant district attorney Steven Jensen heard on the tapes the context of Mrs. Quigley's remarks, all charges but one, a misdemeanor traffic violation against Mr. Quigley, were dropped. The district attorney issued two letters of apology to the Quigleys, saying he found no evidence that either had engaged in \"anti-Semitic conduct or harassment.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/13/us/privacy-rights-win-over-bias-charges-in-defamation-case.html | work=The New York Times | title=Privacy Rights Win Over Bias Charges In Defamation Case | date=May 13, 2000}}</ref>\n\nThe Quigleys brought a lawsuit against ADL, Rosenthal, the Aronsons, and two ADL volunteer attorneys. The two attorneys agreed to pay $350,000 to the Quigleys in settlement of their claims. The Quigley settlement with the Aronsons did not involve a cash payment. The Quigleys maintained their action against ADL and Rosenthal, which was heard in federal court. A federal jury returned a verdict of $10 million in favor of the Quigleys. ADL appealed.\n\nAccording to an April 13, 2001, article in ''[[The Forward]]'', upon hearing the appeal, a federal judge \"lambasted the ADL for labeling a nasty neighborhood feud as an anti-Semitic event\" and upheld most of Quigley's $10 million [[lawsuit]] for [[slander and libel|defamation]]. According to a report in the ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'', with accrued interest, the judgment amounted to more than $12 million.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-114248316.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608173726/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-114248316.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=June 8, 2013|title=ADL Pays More Than $12 Million to Former Evergreen Couple. (City Desk/Local)|date=March 12, 2004}}</ref>\n\n=== New antisemitism controversy ===\n{{Main|New antisemitism}}\nA book entitled ''The [[New Anti-Semitism]]'' (New York, 1974) by ADL national leaders Arnold Forster and Benjamin R. Epstein argued that a new kind of anti-Semitism is on the rise. A subsequent book, ''The Real Anti-Semitism in America'' (New York, 1982) was written by ADL national leader Nathan Perlmutter and his wife, Ruth Ann Perlmutter. In ''Never Again? The Threat of the New Anti-Semitism'' (San Francisco, 2003), by ADL's national director Abraham Foxman, he states on page 4: \"We currently face as great a threat to the safety and security of the Jewish people as the one we faced in the 1930s\u2014if not a greater one.\"<ref name=\"adl.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.adl.org/Anti_semitism/never_again.asp |title=Never Again? The Threat of the New Anti-Semitism |publisher=ADL}}</ref>\n\nReviewing Forster and Epstein's work in a May 1974 issue of ''[[Commentary (magazine)|Commentary]]'', Earl Raab, founding director of the Nathan Perlmutter Institute for Jewish Advocacy at [[Brandeis University]], argued that a \"new anti-Semitism\" was indeed emerging in America, in the form of opposition to the collective rights of the Jewish people, but he criticized Forster and Epstein for conflating it with anti-Israel bias.<ref>Raab, Earl. \"Is there a New Anti-Semitism?\", ''Commentary'', May 1974, pp. 53\u201354.</ref> Allan Brownfeld writes that Forster and Epstein's new definition of antisemitism trivialized the concept by turning it into \"a form of political blackmail\" and \"a weapon with which to silence any criticism of either Israel or U.S. policy in the Middle East,\"<ref>{{cite journal\n  |title = Anti-Semitism: Its Changing Meaning\n  |last = Brownfeld\n  |first = Allan\n  |journal = [[Journal of Palestine Studies]]\n  |publisher = [[Institute for Palestine Studies]]\n  |issn = 1533-8614\n  |volume = 16\n  |issue = 3\n  |year = 1987\n  |pages = 53\u201367\n  |doi = 10.2307/2536789\n  |jstor = 2536789\n  }}</ref> while Edward S. Shapiro, in ''A Time for Healing: American Jewry Since World War II'', has written that, \"Forster and Epstein implied that the new anti-Semitism was the inability of Gentiles to love Jews and Israel enough.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Shapiro|first=Edward S.|title=A Time for Healing: American Jewry Since World War II|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|year=1992|page=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780801843471/page/47 47]|isbn=0-8018-4347-2|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780801843471/page/47}}</ref>\n\n[[Norman Finkelstein]] has written that organizations such as the Anti-Defamation League have brought forward charges of new anti-Semitism at various intervals since the 1970s, \"not to fight antisemitism, but rather to exploit the historical suffering of Jews in order to immunize Israel against criticism.\"<ref name=Finkelstein21>{{cite book|last=Finkelstein|first=Norman|title=Beyond Chutzpah: On the Misuse of Anti-Semitism and the Abuse of History|publisher=University of California Press|year=2005|pages=21\u201322}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' has reported that the ADL has repeatedly accused Finkelstein of being a \"[[Holocaust denial|Holocaust denier]],\" and that \"these charges have proved baseless.\"<ref name=\"WP sparks\" />\n\n=== Conflict with Jews for the Preservation of Firearms Ownership ===\nADL is an advocate for [[gun control]] legislation.<ref>{{cite web\n|url= http://www.adl.org/civil_rights/platformcommittee-2004.pdf\n|title= ADL Presentation to the Platform Committees of the Democratic and Republican National Conventions\n|accessdate= January 23, 2008\n|date=June 2004\n|publisher= ADL\n|quote= The Anti-Defamation League has been an advocate for strong, effective, and sensible gun control legislation.\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080227040630/http://www.adl.org/civil_rights/platformcommittee-2004.pdf| archivedate= February 27, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> The ADL filed amicus briefs in support of challenged gun control legislation in the Supreme Court cases of ''[[District of Columbia v. Heller]]'' and ''[[McDonald v. City of Chicago]]'', citing the need to keep guns out of the possession of violent extremists.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jta.org/2008/06/27/default/jewish-groups-slam-handgun-decision|publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency|date=June 27, 2008|title=Jewish groups slam handgun decision}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.adl.org/sites/default/files/documents/civil-rights/adl-in-the-courts/amicus-briefs/brief-pdfs/ab-2010-mcdonald-v-city-of-chicago.pdf|title=Brief of Amicus Curiae Anti-Defamation League in Support of Respondent|work=McDonald v. City of Chicago}}</ref>\n\nGun rights group [[Jews for the Preservation of Firearms Ownership]] (JPFO), which espouses the [[Nazi gun control argument]], has been highly critical of the ADL.<ref>The Liberty Crew (September 20, 2007) [http://www.jpfo.org/alerts/alert20070920.htm \"Why Does the ADL Support Nazi-Based Laws?\"] JPFO.org.</ref><ref>Editors (1997\u20131999) [http://www.jpfo.org/filegen-a-m/jpfacts.htm \"JPFO Facts vs. ADL Lies.\"] JPFO.org.</ref><ref>JPFO editors [http://www.jpfo.org/images02/handbill-adl.jpg \"The Anti-Defamation League Is Anti-American.\"] JPFO.org.</ref> Foxman has written about the JPFO: \"Anti-Semitism has a long and painful history, and the linkage to gun control is a tactic by Jews for the Preservation of Firearms Ownership to manipulate the fear of anti-Semitism toward their own end.\"<ref>Foxman, Abraham H. (May 21, 1995) [https://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/21/opinion/l-nra-doesn-t-represent-george-bush-or-even-most-members-jewish-pro-gun-group-549095.html \"N.R.A. Doesn't Represent George Bush or Even Most Members; Jewish Pro-Gun Group.\"] ''New York Times.''</ref>\n\n=== Park51 Community Center controversy ===\nOn July 28, 2010, ADL issued a statement in which it expressed opposition to the [[Park51]] Community Center, which sponsors planned to build near the [[World Trade Center site]] in New York. ADL stated, \"The controversy which has emerged regarding the building of a Community Center at this location is counterproductive to the healing process. Therefore, under these unique circumstances, we believe the City of New York would be better served if an alternative location could be found.\"<ref name=\"berk\" /> ADL denounced what it saw as bigoted attacks on the project. Foxman opined that some of those who oppose the mosque are \"bigots,\" and that the plan's proponents may have every right to build the mosque at that location. Nevertheless, he said that building the mosque at that site would unnecessarily cause more pain for families of some victims of 9/11.<ref name=\"berk\">Jacob Berkman, [http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/07/30/2740283/adl-opposes-world-trade-center-mosque ADL opposes World Trade Center Mosque] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100803005159/http://blogs.jta.org/telegraph/article/2010/07/30/2740283/adl-opposes-world-trade-center-mosque |date=August 3, 2010 }}, [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]], July 30, 2010.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Jacoby |first=Susan |url=http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/spirited_atheist/2010/08/ground_zero_mosque_protected_by_first_amendment--but_its_still_salt_in_a_wound.html |title=The Spirited Atheist: Ground Zero mosque protected by First Amendment \u2013 but it's still salt in a wound|newspaper=The Washington Post |date=August 6, 2010 |accessdate=April 24, 2015| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100817115334/http://newsweek.washingtonpost.com/onfaith/spirited_atheist/2010/08/ground_zero_mosque_protected_by_first_amendment--but_its_still_salt_in_a_wound.html| archivedate= August 17, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes6\">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/05/opinion/l05mosque.html | work=The New York Times | title=The ADL, the Mosque and the Fight Against Bigotry | date=August 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.adl.org/PresRele/CvlRt_32/5820_32.htm \"Statement On Islamic Community Center Near Ground Zero\"], Anti-Defamation League, July 28, 2010.</ref>\n\nThis opposition to the Community Center led to criticism of the statement from various parties, including one ADL board member, the [[American Jewish Committee]], the [[Jewish Community Relations Council|Jewish Community Relations Council of New York]], Rabbi [[Irwin Kula]], columnists [[Jeffrey Goldberg]] and [[Peter Beinart]], the [[Interfaith Alliance]],<ref>Adam Dickter, [http://www.thejewishweek.com/news/new_york/wake_adl_jewish_groups_back_ground_zero_mosque \"In Wake Of ADL, Jewish Groups Back Ground Zero Mosque\"], ''[[The Jewish Week]]'', August 3, 2010.</ref> and the [[Shalom Center]].<ref>Grace Rauh, [http://manhattan.ny1.com/content/top_stories/123265/jewish-leaders-rally-in-support-of-wtc-mosque/ \"Jewish Leaders Rally In Support Of WTC Mosque\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816033945/http://manhattan.ny1.com/content/top_stories/123265/jewish-leaders-rally-in-support-of-wtc-mosque |date=August 16, 2010 }}, ''[[NY1]]'', August 5, 2010.</ref> In an interview with ''[[The New York Times]]'' Abe Foxman published a statement in reaction to criticism.<ref>Abraham H. Foxman, [http://www.adl.org/ADL_Opinions/Interfaith/Mosque_Ground_Zero.htm \"The Mosque at Ground Zero\"], originally published in ''[[Huffington Post]]'', August 2, 2010.</ref> In protest of ADL's stance, [[CNN]] host [[Fareed Zakaria]] returned the Hubert H. Humphrey First Amendment Freedoms Prize ADL awarded him in 2005.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2010/US/08/07/new.york.zakaria.adl/ CNN host returns ADL award over stance on Islamic center], [[CNN]], August 9, 2010.</ref> ADL chair Robert G. Sugarman responded to a critical ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorial<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/04/opinion/04wed1.html A Monument to Tolerance], ''[[The New York Times]]'' editorial, August 3, 2010.</ref> writing, \"we have publicly taken on those who criticized the mosque in ways that reflected anti-Muslim bigotry or used the controversy for that purpose\" and stating that ADL has combated [[Islamophobia]].<ref>Robert G. Sugarman, [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/05/opinion/l05mosque.html \"Letter to New York Times\"] (August 4, 2010) ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU)\n*[[American-Arab Anti-Discrimination Committee]]\n*[[Antisemitism in the United States]]\n*[[Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations]]\n* ''[[Defamation (film)|Defamation]]'' (Documentary movie by [[Yoav Shamir]])\n*[[Gay & Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation]]\n*[[Israel lobby in the United States]]\n*[[Jewish Council for Public Affairs]]\n*[[Jews Against Anti-Christian Defamation]]\n*[[Membership discrimination in California social clubs]]\n*[[Southern Poverty Law Center]]\n*[[Simon Wiesenthal Center]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.adl.org Official Website]\n\n{{Anti-Defamation League|state=expanded}}\n{{Antisemitism topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{Organized Jewish Life in the United States}}\n{{World Jewish Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-Defamation League| ]]\n[[Category:1913 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anti-racist organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish anti-racism]]\n[[Category:Jewish organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Jewish political organizations]]\n[[Category:Opposition to antisemitism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1913]]\n[[Category:Political advocacy groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Civil liberties advocacy groups in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "2600:100e:b052:4777:f834:1382:a539:63ae", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(True.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-Defamation_League"}
{"title_page": "Ude hishigi ashi gatame", "text_new": "{{short description|Judo technique}}\n{{Infobox Judo technique\n|name           = Ude hishigi ashi gatame\n|image          = \n|image_size     = \n|alt            = \n|caption        = \n|class          = [[List_of_Kodokan_judo_techniques#Katamewaza_.28Grappling_Techniques.29|Katamewaza]]\n|sub_class      = [[Kansetsu-waza]]\n|grip           = \n|back_up        = \n|follow_up      = \n|targets        = [[Arm]]\n|counter        = \n|kodokan        = Yes\n|romaji         =Ude-hishigi-ashi-gatame\n|japanese       =\u8155\u632b\u811a\u56fa\n|english        = Side-lying [[arm bar]]\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Ude-Hishigi-Ashi-Gatame'''|\u8155\u632b\u811a\u56fa}}, sometimes called '''Ashi-gatame''' for short, is one of the official 29 grappling techniques of Kodokan Judo. It is one of the nine<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.judoinfo.com/wazalist.htm | title = Official International Judo Federation Techniques | author = Ohlenkamp, Neil\n| date = 7 December 2001 | work = www.judoinfo.com | publisher = JudoInfo.com | accessdate = 17 April 2012}}</ref> joint techniques of the [[Judo Lists#Kansetsu-waza|Kansetsu-waza list]], one of the three grappling lists in Judo's [[Katame-waza]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.judoinfo.com/gokyo3.htm\n| title = Classification of Techniques in Kodokan Judo | author = Ohlenkamp, Neil | date = 6 March 2005 | work = www.judoinfo.com | publisher = JudoInfo.com\n | accessdate = 17 April 2012}}</ref> enumerating 29 grappling techniques.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.judoinfo.com/gokyo2.htm | title = The 29 Official Grappling Techniques of Kodokan Judo | author = Ohlenkamp, Neil | date = 9 August 2006 | work = www.judoinfo.com | publisher = JudoInfo.com & Encino Judo Club | accessdate = 17 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Similar Techniques, Variants, and Aliases ==\nIJF Official Names:\n*Ude-hishigi-ashi-gatame(\u8155\u632b\u811a\u56fa)\n*U.H. ashi-gatame\n*Ashi-gatame(\u811a\u56fa)\n*AGA\n\nAlias: \n*Leg Armlock <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.esdojo.es/2014/08/katame-waza.html |title= Katame-Waza}} </ref>\n*Ude-hishigi-hara-gatame(\u8155\u632b\u8179\u56fa)\n\n== Included Systems ==\n*[[Judo]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Judo technique|Judo Techniques]]\n*[[Judo Lists]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.chez.com/judopassion/pages/technique/techn%20sol/images/ashigatame.jpg Chez.com/Judopassion] Graphical representation 1\n*[http://www.mcorbeil.com/judo/judo%20files/Kansetsuwaza_files/image015.gif Mcorbeil.com/Judo] Graphical representation 2\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Judo}}\n{{judo-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Judo technique]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Judo technique}}\n{{Infobox Judo technique\n|name           = Ude hishigi ashi gatame\n|image          = \n|image_size     = \n|alt            = \n|caption        = \n|class          = [[List_of_Kodokan_judo_techniques#Katamewaza_.28Grappling_Techniques.29|Katamewaza]]\n|sub_class      = [[Kansetsu-waza]]\n|grip           = \n|back_up        = \n|follow_up      = \n|targets        = [[Arm]]\n|counter        = \n|kodokan        = Yes\n|romaji         =Ude-hishigi-ashi-gatame\n|japanese       =\u8155\u632b\u811a\u56fa\n|english        = Side-lying [[arm bar]]\n}}\n{{nihongo|'''Ude-Hishigi-Ashi-Gatame'''|\u8155\u632b\u811a\u56fa}}, sometimes called '''Ashi-gatame''' for short, is one of the official 29 grappling techniques of Kodokan Judo. It is one of the nine<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.judoinfo.com/wazalist.htm | title = Official International Judo Federation Techniques | author = Ohlenkamp, Neil\n| date = 7 December 2001 | work = www.judoinfo.com | publisher = JudoInfo.com | accessdate = 17 April 2012}}</ref> joint techniques of the [[Judo Lists#Kansetsu-waza|Kansetsu-waza list]], one of the three grappling lists in Judo's [[Katame-waza]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.judoinfo.com/gokyo3.htm\n| title = Classification of Techniques in Kodokan Judo | author = Ohlenkamp, Neil | date = 6 March 2005 | work = www.judoinfo.com | publisher = JudoInfo.com\n | accessdate = 17 April 2012}}</ref> enumerating 29 grappling techniques.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.judoinfo.com/gokyo2.htm | title = The 29 Official Grappling Techniques of Kodokan Judo | author = Ohlenkamp, Neil | date = 9 August 2006 | work = www.judoinfo.com | publisher = JudoInfo.com & Encino Judo Club | accessdate = 17 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Technique Description ==\n{{Empty section|date=April 2012}}\n\n== Similar Techniques, Variants, and Aliases ==\nIJF Official Names:\n*Ude-hishigi-ashi-gatame(\u8155\u632b\u811a\u56fa)\n*U.H. ashi-gatame\n*Ashi-gatame(\u811a\u56fa)\n*AGA\n\nAlias: \n*Leg Armlock <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.esdojo.es/2014/08/katame-waza.html |title= Katame-Waza}} </ref>\n*Ude-hishigi-hara-gatame(\u8155\u632b\u8179\u56fa)\n\n== Included Systems ==\n*[[Judo]]\n\n== Technique History ==\n{{Empty section|date=July 2010}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Judo technique|Judo Techniques]]\n*[[Judo Lists]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.chez.com/judopassion/pages/technique/techn%20sol/images/ashigatame.jpg Chez.com/Judopassion] Graphical representation 1\n*[http://www.mcorbeil.com/judo/judo%20files/Kansetsuwaza_files/image015.gif Mcorbeil.com/Judo] Graphical representation 2\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Judo}}\n{{judo-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Judo technique]]\n", "name_user": "Jdcollins13", "label": "safe", "comment": "remove empty section since 2010 / empty section since 2012", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ude_hishigi_ashi_gatame"}
{"title_page": "Coltura (organization)", "text_new": "{{Infobox organization\n| logo = Coltura logo.png\n| type = [[Nonprofit organization|Nonprofit]]\n| key_people = Matthew Metz (Co-director)<br/>Janelle London (Co-director)\n| name = Coltura\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2014}}\n| location = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n| founder = Matthew Metz\n| website = {{URL|https://www.coltura.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Coltura''' is an American [[Environmentalism|environmental activist]]  group based in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://inmenlo.com/2017/12/18/menlo-park-is-the-launch-site-of-the-no-gasoline-movement/|title=Menlo Park is the launch site of the No-Gasoline movement|date=2017-12-18|work=In Menlo|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref> The group promotes environmental policies and produces cultural works aimed at ending America's use of gasoline. Coltura has produced several works critical of gasoline use which have been presented in cities in the United States and Canada. The organization advocates for policies to phase out the sales of new gasoline-powered vehicles by 2030.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mynorthwest.com/774778/coltura-wants-no-gas-cars-after-2030/|title=Advocate wants to force out gas cars in Washington in 2030|last=Monson|first=Dori|date=2017-10-04|work=KIRO Radio 97.3 FM|access-date=2018-01-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Founding ===\nColtura was founded in 2014 by Matthew Metz, an attorney in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]].<ref name=\"Smith 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestranger.com/theater/2016/09/27/24584871/can-performance-art-fight-climate-change|title=Can Performance Art Fight Climate Change?|last=Smith|first=Rich|date=2016-09-27|work=The Stranger|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en}}</ref> Coltura's name comes from an amalgamation of CO<sub>2</sub>, the [[chemical formula]] for carbon dioxide, and the word [[Culture|''culture'']]''.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/environment/he-knows-its-crazy-but-this-seattle-guy-is-pushing-a-total-ban-on-gas-cars/|title=He knows it's crazy, but this Seattle guy is pushing a total ban on gas cars|last=Westneat|first=Danny|date=2017-09-29|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"Kiley 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/coltura-performance-webversion/|title=Seattle street clowns aim to provoke smiles, change hearts on gasoline use|last=Kiley|first=Brendan|date=2016-09-06|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en-US}}</ref> The organization was founded as a nonprofit with a mission of \"eliminating gasoline use in America by 2040\".<ref name=\"Spain 2018\">{{Cite news|url=http://knkx.org/post/inflatable-bubble-fills-smoke-what-happens-next-art-or-guilt-trip|title=This Inflatable Bubble Fills With Smoke. What Happens Next Is Art, Or A Guilt Trip|last=Spain|first=Monica|date=2017-05-31|work=KNKX|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en}}</ref> Metz serves as co-director of the organization along with Janelle London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2017/10/04/opinion-yes-ban-sales-of-new-gas-fueled-vehicles-in-california-by-2040/|title=Opinion: Yes! Ban sales of new gas fueled vehicles in California by 2040|date=2017-10-04|work=East Bay Times|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\n=== Art events ===\nColtura has staged [[street theatre]] and [[performance art]] in a tradition akin to [[commedia dell'arte]].<ref name=\"Kiley 2018\" /> In September 2016, Coltura staged performances at gas stations, public events, and streets in Seattle to raise awareness about pollution-emitting gasoline vehicles. The performances were inspired by the strategies employed by the Colombian politician [[Antanas Mockus]], who as mayor of [[Bogot\u00e1]] hired [[Mime artist|mimes]] to poke fun at drivers who drove past pedestrian crosswalks.<ref name=\"Kiley 2018\" /> Coltura performed at Seattle Design Festival, where they displayed an art installation<ref name=\"Smith 2018\" /> as well as performing at the First Thursday Art Walk and [[Bumbershoot]]. Actors billed as \"gasoline ghosts\", carrying gasoline hoses and nozzles and dressed in white [[leotard]]s, drew attention to the air pollution and [[greenhouse gas]]es created by gasoline use. The \"ghosts\" showed their affection for gasoline, and comedically chased down cars to inhale their exhaust.<ref name=\"Smith 2018\" /><ref name=\"Kiley 2018\" />\n\nIn October 2016, Coltura staged a procession entitled ''Funeral for Gasoline'' as part of No Gasoline Day, in which actors carried a casket containing a [[Fuel dispenser#Fuel nozzles|fuel nozzle]] from the [[Space Needle]] to [[Downtown Seattle]].<ref name=\"Smith 2018\" /><ref name=\"Kiley 2018\" /> Coltura won the 2017 [[Sustainable Seattle]] Arts and Culture Award for their No Gasoline Day performance and \"for helping change cultural norms about the use of gasoline through mobile and interactive live performance, social media, and imagery and videos challenging the cultural status quo.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.seattlepi.com/boomerconsumer/2017/03/10/sustainable-seattle-names-2017-award-winners-citing-regions-advances-in-sustainability/|title=Sustainable Seattle names 2017 award winners, citing region\u2019s advances in sustainability|last=Robison|first=Rita R.|date=2017-03-10|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|access-date=2018-01-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, the group exhibited ''The Gas Trap'', a 25-foot high clear vinyl bubble connected to the tailpipe of a gasoline-powered car, accompanied by a theatrical piece. The work was a collaboration between Metz, Samaj, the Seattle Design Nerds, Alyssa Norling and Grace Orr.<ref name=\"McKenzie-Sutter 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.straight.com/arts/956861/gas-trap-takes-dramatic-look-consequences-gasoline-use|title=The Gas Trap takes a dramatic look at the consequences of gasoline use|last=McKenzie-Sutter|first=Holly|date=2017-08-29|work=Georgia Straight|access-date=2018-01-27|location=Vancouver, British Columbia|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cityartsmagazine.com/waiting-inhale/|title=Waiting to Inhale|date=2017-06-26|work=City Arts Magazine|access-date=2018-01-27|language=en-US}}</ref> During the performance first staged in [[Westlake Park (Seattle)|Westlake Park]] in Seattle, the performers appeared to be trapped inside and gasping for breath as artificial smoke filled the bubble.<ref name=\"Spain 2018\" /> The performance was staged again in Canada on September 10 at the Roundhouse Community Arts and Recreation Centre in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"McKenzie-Sutter 2018\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vancourier.com/gas-trap-bursting-the-carbon-bubble-1.22521662|title=Gas Trap: Bursting the carbon bubble|last=Zeschky|first=Jan|date=2017-09-07|work=Vancouver Courier|access-date=2018-01-27}}</ref>\n\nColtura held a mural contest in 2017 and collaborated with the artist Craig Cundiff to produce a large mural in the industrial [[Georgetown, Seattle|Georgetown]] district of Seattle. It depicts a boy wearing a mask over his mouth and nose, with a view of Seattle's congested highways, hazy sky and setting orange sun in the background.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://seattlemag.com/arts-and-culture/new-georgetown-protest-mural-takes-climate-change-south-seattle-air-pollution|title=New Georgetown Protest Mural Takes on Climate Change, South Seattle Air Pollution|last=Rietmulder|first=Michael|date=2017-11-17|work=Seattle Magazine|access-date=2018-01-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\nColtura\u2019s gas ghosts and gasoline video have also received widespread publicity.<ref>{{cite web |work=KRON San Francisco (TV) |date=2018-09-13 |title=Gas Ghosts at Global Climate Action Summit |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1h8BHl0TAf-p-cpymIFbxsQjwSY0-7SwS/view |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| work=Univision San Francisco (TV) |date=2018-09-13 |title=Gas Ghosts at Global Climate Action Summit |url=https://mobilemoviemaking.com/music-video-calls-for-a-gasoline-free-world/ |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Recharge Required'' report ===\nOn June 1, 2018, Coltura released a report, named ''Recharge Required'', on the status of the State of Washington's varies agencies adherence to a 2007 law<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/opinion/editorial-local-governments-ignoring-law-on-electric-cars/|title=Local governments ignoring law on electric cars|last=Editorial Board|date=2018-06-10|work=The Daily Herald|access-date=2018-06-18|language=en-US}}</ref> requiring \"vehicles in government fleets to run on electricity or biofuel\u2026 'to the extent practicable'\".<ref name=\"Ryan 2018\">{{Cite news|url=http://kuow.org/post/gas-guzzling-cities-state-blow-past-deadline-electric-vehicles|title=Gas-guzzling cities, state blow past deadline for electric vehicles|last=Ryan|first=John|date=2018-06-01|work=KUOW News|access-date=2018-06-18|language=en}}</ref> According to the report, in contrast to the 100% adherence set as the goal by the deadline on June 1, 2015, less than 6% of vehicles in use by county and city agencies<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/environment/washington-state-ordered-agencies-to-buy-electric-cars-theyre-falling-short-report-says/|title=Washington law ordered public agencies to buy electric cars. They're falling short, report says.|last=Bernton|first=Hal|date=2018-06-03|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2018-06-18|language=en-US}}</ref> and 2% of the state's motor pool meet this goal.<ref name=\"Ryan 2018\" />  In Washington State, Coltura\u2019s ''Recharge Required'' report spurred legislative appropriation of $450,000 to study public fleet electrification.\n\n=== Legislative efforts ===\nIn March 2020, Coltura led a coalition to pass Zero Emissions Vehicle legislation in Washington State.<ref>{{cite web| work=Seattle Times |date=2020-03-09 |title=Automakers Required to Sell More Electric Vehicles Under New Legislation in Washington State |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/automakers-required-to-sell-more-electric-vehicles-under-new-legislation-in-washington-state/ |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| work=Investigate West |date=2020-03-09 |title=Electric Cars Get a Boost in Olympia but Broader Climate-Rescue Legislation Withers |url=https://www.invw.org/2020/03/09/electric-cars-get-a-boost-in-olympia-but-broader-climate-rescue-legislation-withers/ |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| work=Crosscut |date=2020-03-10 |title=WA lawmakers pave the way for electric cars but activists want more |url=https://crosscut.com/2020/03/wa-lawmakers-pave-way-electric-cars-activists-want-more |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nColtura also led a coalition that introduced Washington State legislation mandating that all new cars sold be electric by 2030,<ref>{{cite web| work=Government Fleet |date=2019-05-07 |title=Washington State to Conduct EV Analysis for All Public Fleets |url=https://www.government-fleet.com/331352/washington-state-to-conduct-ev-analysis-for-all-public-fleets |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| work=Seattle Times |date=2018-06-03 |title=Washington law ordered public agencies to buy electric cars. They\u2019re falling short, report says. |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/environment/washington-state-ordered-agencies-to-buy-electric-cars-theyre-falling-short-report-says/ |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> \u2013 thereby effectively banning sales of new gasoline vehicles.<ref>{{cite web| work=E&E News |date=2020-02-14 |title=Gasoline car bans: EV savior or 'stupid' idea? |url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1062345205 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| work=Seattle Times |date=2020-02-05 |title=Banning gas cars? It\u2019s a \u2018fringe crazy bill\u2019 no longer |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/banning-gas-cars-its-a-fringe-crazy-bill-no-longer/ |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.coltura.org/}}\n\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Arts organizations based in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Climate change organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Environmental organizations established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Environmental organizations based in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Arts organizations established in 2014]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox organization\n| logo = Coltura logo.png\n| type = [[Nonprofit organization|Nonprofit]]\n| key_people = Matthew Metz (Co-director)<br/>Janelle London (Co-director)\n| name = Coltura\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2014}}\n| location = [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]]\n| founder = Matthew Metz\n| website = {{URL|https://www.coltura.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Coltura''' is an American [[Environmentalism|environmental activist]]  group based in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://inmenlo.com/2017/12/18/menlo-park-is-the-launch-site-of-the-no-gasoline-movement/|title=Menlo Park is the launch site of the No-Gasoline movement|date=2017-12-18|work=In Menlo|access-date=2020-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref> The group promotes environmental policies and produces cultural works aimed at ending America's use of gasoline. Coltura has produced several works critical of gasoline use which have been presented in cities in the United States and Canada. The organization advocates for policies to phase out the sales of new gasoline-powered vehicles by 2030.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mynorthwest.com/774778/coltura-wants-no-gas-cars-after-2030/|title=Advocate wants to force out gas cars in Washington in 2030|last=Monson|first=Dori|date=2017-10-04|work=KIRO Radio 97.3 FM|access-date=2018-01-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Founding ===\nColtura was founded in 2014 by Matthew Metz, an attorney in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]].<ref name=\"Smith 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestranger.com/theater/2016/09/27/24584871/can-performance-art-fight-climate-change|title=Can Performance Art Fight Climate Change?|last=Smith|first=Rich|date=2016-09-27|work=The Stranger|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en}}</ref> Coltura's name comes from an amalgamation of CO<sub>2</sub>, the [[chemical formula]] for carbon dioxide, and the word [[Culture|''culture'']]''.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/environment/he-knows-its-crazy-but-this-seattle-guy-is-pushing-a-total-ban-on-gas-cars/|title=He knows it's crazy, but this Seattle guy is pushing a total ban on gas cars|last=Westneat|first=Danny|date=2017-09-29|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"Kiley 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/coltura-performance-webversion/|title=Seattle street clowns aim to provoke smiles, change hearts on gasoline use|last=Kiley|first=Brendan|date=2016-09-06|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en-US}}</ref> The organization was founded as a nonprofit with a mission of \"eliminating gasoline use in America by 2040\".<ref name=\"Spain 2018\">{{Cite news|url=http://knkx.org/post/inflatable-bubble-fills-smoke-what-happens-next-art-or-guilt-trip|title=This Inflatable Bubble Fills With Smoke. What Happens Next Is Art, Or A Guilt Trip|last=Spain|first=Monica|date=2017-05-31|work=KNKX|access-date=2018-01-26|language=en}}</ref> Metz serves as co-director of the organization along with Janelle London.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eastbaytimes.com/2017/10/04/opinion-yes-ban-sales-of-new-gas-fueled-vehicles-in-california-by-2040/|title=Opinion: Yes! Ban sales of new gas fueled vehicles in California by 2040|date=2017-10-04|work=East Bay Times|access-date=2018-11-09|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\n=== Art events ===\nColtura has staged [[street theatre]] and [[performance art]] in a tradition akin to [[commedia dell'arte]].<ref name=\"Kiley 2018\" /> In September 2016, Coltura staged performances at gas stations, public events, and streets in Seattle to raise awareness about pollution-emitting gasoline vehicles. The performances were inspired by the strategies employed by the Colombian politician [[Antanas Mockus]], who as mayor of [[Bogot\u00e1]] hired [[Mime artist|mimes]] to poke fun at drivers who drove past pedestrian crosswalks.<ref name=\"Kiley 2018\" /> Coltura performed at Seattle Design Festival, where they displayed an art installation<ref name=\"Smith 2018\" /> as well as performing at the First Thursday Art Walk and [[Bumbershoot]]. Actors billed as \"gasoline ghosts\", carrying gasoline hoses and nozzles and dressed in white [[leotard]]s, drew attention to the air pollution and [[greenhouse gas]]es created by gasoline use. The \"ghosts\" showed their affection for gasoline, and comedically chased down cars to inhale their exhaust.<ref name=\"Smith 2018\" /><ref name=\"Kiley 2018\" />\n\nIn October 2016, Coltura staged a procession entitled ''Funeral for Gasoline'' as part of No Gasoline Day, in which actors carried a casket containing a [[Fuel dispenser#Fuel nozzles|fuel nozzle]] from the [[Space Needle]] to [[Downtown Seattle]].<ref name=\"Smith 2018\" /><ref name=\"Kiley 2018\" /> Coltura won the 2017 [[Sustainable Seattle]] Arts and Culture Award for their No Gasoline Day performance and \"for helping change cultural norms about the use of gasoline through mobile and interactive live performance, social media, and imagery and videos challenging the cultural status quo.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.seattlepi.com/boomerconsumer/2017/03/10/sustainable-seattle-names-2017-award-winners-citing-regions-advances-in-sustainability/|title=Sustainable Seattle names 2017 award winners, citing region\u2019s advances in sustainability|last=Robison|first=Rita R.|date=2017-03-10|work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer|access-date=2018-01-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, the group exhibited ''The Gas Trap'', a 25-foot high clear vinyl bubble connected to the tailpipe of a gasoline-powered car, accompanied by a theatrical piece. The work was a collaboration between Metz, Samaj, the Seattle Design Nerds, Alyssa Norling and Grace Orr.<ref name=\"McKenzie-Sutter 2018\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.straight.com/arts/956861/gas-trap-takes-dramatic-look-consequences-gasoline-use|title=The Gas Trap takes a dramatic look at the consequences of gasoline use|last=McKenzie-Sutter|first=Holly|date=2017-08-29|work=Georgia Straight|access-date=2018-01-27|location=Vancouver, British Columbia|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cityartsmagazine.com/waiting-inhale/|title=Waiting to Inhale|date=2017-06-26|work=City Arts Magazine|access-date=2018-01-27|language=en-US}}</ref> During the performance first staged in [[Westlake Park (Seattle)|Westlake Park]] in Seattle, the performers appeared to be trapped inside and gasping for breath as artificial smoke filled the bubble.<ref name=\"Spain 2018\" /> The performance was staged again in Canada on September 10 at the Roundhouse Community Arts and Recreation Centre in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"McKenzie-Sutter 2018\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vancourier.com/gas-trap-bursting-the-carbon-bubble-1.22521662|title=Gas Trap: Bursting the carbon bubble|last=Zeschky|first=Jan|date=2017-09-07|work=Vancouver Courier|access-date=2018-01-27}}</ref>\n\nColtura held a mural contest in 2017 and collaborated with the artist Craig Cundiff to produce a large mural in the industrial [[Georgetown, Seattle|Georgetown]] district of Seattle. It depicts a boy wearing a mask over his mouth and nose, with a view of Seattle's congested highways, hazy sky and setting orange sun in the background.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://seattlemag.com/arts-and-culture/new-georgetown-protest-mural-takes-climate-change-south-seattle-air-pollution|title=New Georgetown Protest Mural Takes on Climate Change, South Seattle Air Pollution|last=Rietmulder|first=Michael|date=2017-11-17|work=Seattle Magazine|access-date=2018-01-27|language=en}}</ref>\n\nColtura\u2019s gas ghosts and gasoline video have also received widespread publicity.<ref>{{cite web |work=KRON San Francisco (TV) |date=2018-09-13 |title=Gas Ghosts at Global Climate Action Summit |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1h8BHl0TAf-p-cpymIFbxsQjwSY0-7SwS/view |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| work=Univision San Francisco (TV) |date=2018-09-13 |title=Gas Ghosts at Global Climate Action Summit |url=https://mobilemoviemaking.com/music-video-calls-for-a-gasoline-free-world/ |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n=== Recharge Required report ===\nOn June 1, 2018, Coltura released a report, named ''Recharge Required'', on the status of the State of Washington's varies agencies adherence to a 2007 law<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/opinion/editorial-local-governments-ignoring-law-on-electric-cars/|title=Local governments ignoring law on electric cars|last=Editorial Board|date=2018-06-10|work=The Daily Herald|access-date=2018-06-18|language=en-US}}</ref> requiring \"vehicles in government fleets to run on electricity or biofuel\u2026 'to the extent practicable'\".<ref name=\"Ryan 2018\">{{Cite news|url=http://kuow.org/post/gas-guzzling-cities-state-blow-past-deadline-electric-vehicles|title=Gas-guzzling cities, state blow past deadline for electric vehicles|last=Ryan|first=John|date=2018-06-01|work=KUOW News|access-date=2018-06-18|language=en}}</ref> According to the report, in contrast to the 100% adherence set as the goal by the deadline on June 1, 2015, less than 6% of vehicles in use by county and city agencies<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/environment/washington-state-ordered-agencies-to-buy-electric-cars-theyre-falling-short-report-says/|title=Washington law ordered public agencies to buy electric cars. They're falling short, report says.|last=Bernton|first=Hal|date=2018-06-03|work=The Seattle Times|access-date=2018-06-18|language=en-US}}</ref> and 2% of the state's motor pool meet this goal.<ref name=\"Ryan 2018\" />  In Washington State, Coltura\u2019s ''Recharge Required'' report spurred legislative appropriation of $450,000 to study public fleet electrification.\n\n=== Legislative efforts ===\nIn March 2020, Coltura led a coalition to pass Zero Emissions Vehicle legislation in Washington State.<ref>{{cite web| work=Seattle Times |date=2020-03-09 |title=Automakers Required to Sell More Electric Vehicles Under New Legislation in Washington State |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/automakers-required-to-sell-more-electric-vehicles-under-new-legislation-in-washington-state/ |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| work=Investigate West |date=2020-03-09 |title=Electric Cars Get a Boost in Olympia but Broader Climate-Rescue Legislation Withers |url=https://www.invw.org/2020/03/09/electric-cars-get-a-boost-in-olympia-but-broader-climate-rescue-legislation-withers/ |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| work=Crosscut |date=2020-03-10 |title=WA lawmakers pave the way for electric cars but activists want more |url=https://crosscut.com/2020/03/wa-lawmakers-pave-way-electric-cars-activists-want-more |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\nColtura also led a coalition that introduced Washington State legislation mandating that all new cars sold be electric by 2030,<ref>{{cite web| work=Government Fleet |date=2019-05-07 |title=Washington State to Conduct EV Analysis for All Public Fleets |url=https://www.government-fleet.com/331352/washington-state-to-conduct-ev-analysis-for-all-public-fleets |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| work=Seattle Times |date=2018-06-03 |title=Washington law ordered public agencies to buy electric cars. They\u2019re falling short, report says. |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/environment/washington-state-ordered-agencies-to-buy-electric-cars-theyre-falling-short-report-says/ |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref> \u2013 thereby effectively banning sales of new gasoline vehicles.<ref>{{cite web| work=E&E News |date=2020-02-14 |title=Gasoline car bans: EV savior or 'stupid' idea? |url=https://www.eenews.net/stories/1062345205 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| work=Seattle Times |date=2020-02-05 |title=Banning gas cars? It\u2019s a \u2018fringe crazy bill\u2019 no longer |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/banning-gas-cars-its-a-fringe-crazy-bill-no-longer/ |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://www.coltura.org/}}\n\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in Seattle]]\n[[Category:Arts organizations based in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Climate change organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Environmental organizations established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Environmental organizations based in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Arts organizations established in 2014]]\n", "name_user": "Maestro David 27", "label": "safe", "comment": "italic font in header", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coltura_(organization)"}
{"title_page": "Omega Phi Chi", "text_new": "{{Infobox fraternity\n|letters       = \u03a9\u03a6\u03a7\n|name          =Omega Phi Chi Multicultural Sorority\n|crest         = Omeg phi chi.png\n|founded       = {{Start date and age|November 9, 1988}}\n|birthplace    = [[Rutgers University]]\n|type          = [[List of social fraternities and sororities|Sorority]]\n|emphasis      = [[Multicultural]] \n|scope         =\n|mission       =\n|vision        =\n|motto         =Destroying All Boundaries. \nUniting All Races. \nOmega Phi Chi. \nWe Dare To Be Different.\n\nPreserving the Past. \nCultivating the Present. \nBuilding the Future. \nOmega Phi Chi. \nWe Dare to Be Different.\n|slogan        =Diversity at its Finest\u00ae\n|maxim         =\n|member badge  =\n|pledge pin    =\n|pledge name   = Optional parameter that changes the word \"Pledge\" in \"pledge pin\" and \"colony pledge pin\". Without this, those parameters default to \"Pledge\".\n|colony badge  =\n|colony pledge pin =\n|colors        = Perfect Pink & Onyx Black\n|symbol        = Heart\n|flag          =\n|flower        =Ladies Pink Slipper also known as Moccasin\n|tree          =\n|jewel         =Onyx\n|mascot        =Black Panther\n|patron greek divinity =\n|publication   =\n|philanthropy  =\n|charterdate   =\n|chartercity   =\n|chapters      = 26\n|colonies      =\n|members       =\n|lifetime      =\n|factoid       = \n|object        =\n|free          =\n|address       =\n|city          =New Brunswick\n|state         =NJ\n|country       =United States\n|homepage      =[http://www.omegaphichi.org/ National Website]|\n|footnotes     =\n}}\n'''Omega Phi Chi Multicultural Sorority, Inc.''' ('''\u03a9\u03a6\u03a7''') is a national [[multicultural]] [[Fraternities and sororities in North America|sorority]] that was established on November 9, 1988 at [[Rutgers\u2013New Brunswick|Rutgers University]] in [[New Brunswick, New Jersey]] by eight women of [[Asian people|Asian]], [[African American]], and [[Latinas|Latina]] descent.\n\n== History ==\nThe founders of Omega Phi Chi were droppies of Mu Sigma Upsilon Sorority Incorporated a group of eight women who felt the need to establish a multicultural organization on the campus of [[Rutgers University\u2013New Brunswick|Rutgers University - New Brunswick]] that spoke to their needs across diverse backgrounds, distinct cultural roots, and the empowerment of the female culture. They came together to found a multicultural sorority; a different type of organization that would not be categorized by [[ethnicity]], [[creed]] or [[culture]]. Since its inception, it has grown to include over 95 different nationalities and has started 24 chapters in New Jersey, New York, Florida, Arizona, Texas, Indiana, and California.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''Founding Mothers'''\n\nThe founding mothers of Omega Phi Chi Multicultural Sorority Inc. are:\n\n* Bernadette Santana - Filipina & Dominican\n* Dawn Gonzalez - Puerto Rican\n* Cindy Cumba - Puerto Rican & Mexican\n* Stacy Richardson - African American\n* Annette Cuevas - Puerto Rican\n* Socorro Valle - Puerto Rican\n* Tracie Davis - African American\n* Magdaly Casillas - Puerto Rican\n\n== Purpose ==\nThe purpose of Omega Phi Chi is to create a unity among all women and promote ethnic diversity by integrating women of all boundaries and cultures. Omega Phi Chi's concept of sisterhood are love, honesty, loyalty, responsibility of one another, and mutual respect. The main objectives of this organization are academic excellence and involvement in community affairs. In addition, Omega Phi Chi prides themselves in promoting professionalism. {{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\n== Facts ==\n*Colors: Perfect Pink and Onyx Black\n*Mascot: Black Panther\n*Flower: Lady's Pink Slipper known as Moccasin\n*Stone: Black Onyx\n*Core Values: Academic Excellence and Involvement in Community Affairs\n*We Step and We Stroll\n\nMottos:\n\"Destroying All Boundaries. Uniting All Races. Omega Phi Chi. We Dare to Be Different.\" <br />\n\"Preserving the Past, Cultivating the Present, Building the Future, Omega Phi Chi, We Dare To Be Different\"\n\n== Undergraduate chapters ==\nThe chapters of Omega Phi Chi:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.omegaphichi.org/undergraduate-chapters|title=Undergraduate Chapters {{!}} Omega Phi Chi Multicultural Sorority, Inc.|website=Omega Phi Chi Multicultural Sorority, Inc. {{!}} Diversity at its Finest &reg;|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n* Alpha - [[Rutgers University\u2013New Brunswick|Rutgers University - New Brunswick]]\n* Beta - [[Rider University]]\n* Gamma - [[New Jersey City University]]\n* Delta - South Orange, New Jersey\n* Epsilon - [[William Paterson University|William Patterson University]]\n* Zeta - [[The College of New Jersey]]\n* Eta - [[Ramapo College of New Jersey]]\n* Theta - [[Kean University]]\n* Iota - [[State University of New York at New Paltz]]\n* Kappa - [[Barry University]] \n* Lambda - [[Arizona State University]]\n* Mu - [[Montclair State University]]\n* Nu - [[Rutgers University\u2013Newark|Rutgers University - Newark]]\n* Xi - [[Florida International University]]\n* Omicron - [[Fairleigh Dickinson University|Fairleigh Dickinson University - Teaneck]]\n* Pi - [[Sam Houston State University]]\n* Rho - [[California State University, Dominguez Hills|California State University - Dominguez Hills]]\n* Sigma - [[Buffalo State College|State University of New York - College at Buffalo]]\n* Tau - [[Hofstra University]]\n* Upsilon - [[Purdue University]]\n* Phi - [[Felician University]]\n* Chi - [[New Jersey Institute of Technology]]\n* Psi - [[Fairleigh Dickinson University|Fairleigh Dickinson University - Florham]]\n* Alpha Alpha - [[Rutgers University\u2013Camden|Rutgers University - Camden]]\n* Alpha Beta - [[Washington State University]] \n* Alpha Gamma - [[Eastern Washington University]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.omegaphichi.org/ Omega Phi Chi Sorority, Inc.]\n\n{{Fraternities and Sororities |collapsed}}\n{{National Multicultural Greek Council}}\n\n[[Category:National Multicultural Greek Council]]\n[[Category:Student societies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1988]]\n\n\n{{Fraternity and Sorority-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox fraternity\n|letters       = \u03a9\u03a6\u03a7\n|name          =Omega Phi Chi Multicultural Sorority\n|crest         = Omeg phi chi.png\n|founded       = {{Start date and age|November 9, 1988}}\n|birthplace    = [[Rutgers University]]\n|type          = [[List of social fraternities and sororities|Sorority]]\n|emphasis      = [[Multicultural]] \n|scope         =\n|mission       =\n|vision        =\n|motto         =Destroying All Boundaries. \nUniting All Races. \nOmega Phi Chi. \nWe Dare To Be Different.\n\nPreserving the Past. \nCultivating the Present. \nBuilding the Future. \nOmega Phi Chi. \nWe Dare to Be Different.\n|slogan        =Diversity at its Finest\u00ae\n|maxim         =\n|member badge  =\n|pledge pin    =\n|pledge name   = Optional parameter that changes the word \"Pledge\" in \"pledge pin\" and \"colony pledge pin\". Without this, those parameters default to \"Pledge\".\n|colony badge  =\n|colony pledge pin =\n|colors        = Perfect Pink & Onyx Black\n|symbol        = Heart\n|flag          =\n|flower        =Ladies Pink Slipper also known as Moccasin\n|tree          =\n|jewel         =Onyx\n|mascot        =Black Panther\n|patron greek divinity =\n|publication   =\n|philanthropy  =\n|charterdate   =\n|chartercity   =\n|chapters      = 26\n|colonies      =\n|members       =\n|lifetime      =\n|factoid       = \n|object        =\n|free          =\n|address       =\n|city          =New Brunswick\n|state         =NJ\n|country       =United States\n|homepage      =[http://www.omegaphichi.org/ National Website]|\n|footnotes     =\n}}\n'''Omega Phi Chi Multicultural Sorority, Inc.''' ('''\u03a9\u03a6\u03a7''') is a national [[multicultural]] [[Fraternities and sororities in North America|sorority]] that was established on November 9, 1988 at [[Rutgers\u2013New Brunswick|Rutgers University]] in [[New Brunswick, New Jersey]] by eight women of [[Asian people|Asian]], [[African American]], and [[Latinas|Latina]] descent.\n\n== History ==\nThe founders of Omega Phi Chi were a group of eight women who felt the need to establish a multicultural organization on the campus of [[Rutgers University\u2013New Brunswick|Rutgers University - New Brunswick]] that spoke to their needs across diverse backgrounds, distinct cultural roots, and the empowerment of the female culture. They came together to found a multicultural sorority; a different type of organization that would not be categorized by [[ethnicity]], [[creed]] or [[culture]]. Since its inception, it has grown to include over 95 different nationalities and has started 24 chapters in New Jersey, New York, Florida, Arizona, Texas, Indiana, and California.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''Founding Mothers'''\n\nThe founding mothers of Omega Phi Chi Multicultural Sorority Inc. are:\n\n* Bernadette Santana - Filipina & Dominican\n* Dawn Gonzalez - Puerto Rican\n* Cindy Cumba - Puerto Rican & Mexican\n* Stacy Richardson - African American\n* Annette Cuevas - Puerto Rican\n* Socorro Valle - Puerto Rican\n* Tracie Davis - African American\n* Magdaly Casillas - Puerto Rican\n\n== Purpose ==\nThe purpose of Omega Phi Chi is to create a unity among all women and promote ethnic diversity by integrating women of all boundaries and cultures. Omega Phi Chi's concept of sisterhood are love, honesty, loyalty, responsibility of one another, and mutual respect. The main objectives of this organization are academic excellence and involvement in community affairs. In addition, Omega Phi Chi prides themselves in promoting professionalism. {{citation needed|date=January 2013}}\n\n== Facts ==\n*Colors: Perfect Pink and Onyx Black\n*Mascot: Black Panther\n*Flower: Lady's Pink Slipper known as Moccasin\n*Stone: Black Onyx\n*Core Values: Academic Excellence and Involvement in Community Affairs\n*We Step and We Stroll\n\nMottos:\n\"Destroying All Boundaries. Uniting All Races. Omega Phi Chi. We Dare to Be Different.\" <br />\n\"Preserving the Past, Cultivating the Present, Building the Future, Omega Phi Chi, We Dare To Be Different\"\n\n== Undergraduate chapters ==\nThe chapters of Omega Phi Chi:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.omegaphichi.org/undergraduate-chapters|title=Undergraduate Chapters {{!}} Omega Phi Chi Multicultural Sorority, Inc.|website=Omega Phi Chi Multicultural Sorority, Inc. {{!}} Diversity at its Finest &reg;|language=en|access-date=2019-07-17}}</ref>\n* Alpha - [[Rutgers University\u2013New Brunswick|Rutgers University - New Brunswick]]\n* Beta - [[Rider University]]\n* Gamma - [[New Jersey City University]]\n* Delta - South Orange, New Jersey\n* Epsilon - [[William Paterson University|William Patterson University]]\n* Zeta - [[The College of New Jersey]]\n* Eta - [[Ramapo College of New Jersey]]\n* Theta - [[Kean University]]\n* Iota - [[State University of New York at New Paltz]]\n* Kappa - [[Barry University]] \n* Lambda - [[Arizona State University]]\n* Mu - [[Montclair State University]]\n* Nu - [[Rutgers University\u2013Newark|Rutgers University - Newark]]\n* Xi - [[Florida International University]]\n* Omicron - [[Fairleigh Dickinson University|Fairleigh Dickinson University - Teaneck]]\n* Pi - [[Sam Houston State University]]\n* Rho - [[California State University, Dominguez Hills|California State University - Dominguez Hills]]\n* Sigma - [[Buffalo State College|State University of New York - College at Buffalo]]\n* Tau - [[Hofstra University]]\n* Upsilon - [[Purdue University]]\n* Phi - [[Felician University]]\n* Chi - [[New Jersey Institute of Technology]]\n* Psi - [[Fairleigh Dickinson University|Fairleigh Dickinson University - Florham]]\n* Alpha Alpha - [[Rutgers University\u2013Camden|Rutgers University - Camden]]\n* Alpha Beta - [[Washington State University]] \n* Alpha Gamma - [[Eastern Washington University]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.omegaphichi.org/ Omega Phi Chi Sorority, Inc.]\n\n{{Fraternities and Sororities |collapsed}}\n{{National Multicultural Greek Council}}\n\n[[Category:National Multicultural Greek Council]]\n[[Category:Student societies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1988]]\n\n\n{{Fraternity and Sorority-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2604:2000:1002:c57f:a5ef:94a9:434:b07c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory:Fixed details)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omega_Phi_Chi"}
